<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Anti-ApartheidMarch     07-15 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Anti-Apartheid March,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NAACP Delegates March on South African Embassy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 1,000 NAACP members, some carrying a
casket to symbolize the burial of apartheid, prayed and
demonstrated before the South African Embassy to protest that
nation's system of racial discrimination.
   Raising their fists and chanting ``let our people go,'' the
demonstrators lifted the grey casket before the embassy entrance,
as NAACP executive director Benjamin L. Hooks led the crowd
Thursday in a series of prayers that ``hearts might be changed.''
   Hooks prayed that ``those white folk in South Africa, that call
themselves Christians, may start acting like Christians and
recognize that they are their brother's keeper ... that we are all
one blood.''
   ``We come here today in the spirit of Walter White, Roy Wilkins,
Martin Luther King ... to say that we won't be satisfied until the
walls of segregation, apartheid and oppression are brought low in
South Africa,'' said the Rev. Jerry Guess, NAACP communications
director.
   ``We come today praying that our own pharaoh, who sits at 1600
Pennsylvania Avenue, will hear these voices (and realize that) we
cannot exist in this world, half slave and half free,'' Guess
prayed, referring to the White House address.
   Hooks then pointed to the casket and pronounced sentence on the
policies of apartheid, segregation, hatred, racial discrmination,
unjust treatment and inequality.
   He led the crowd in the closing words over the coffin, saying,
``dust to dust, ashes to ashes _ apartheid you'll never rise
again!'' The coffin was placed in a white hearse as the
demonstrators sang ``Oh, Freedom,'' a song from the civil rights
movement.
   The half-hour march was the culmination of South Africa Day at
the 79th annual convention of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People. There were no arrests.
   In the morning sessions, Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., and
Randall Robinson, head of TransAfrica, a lobby group for the
Caribbean and Africa, urged the delegates to support legislation to
impose stronger economic sanctions on the African nation.
</TEXT>
