<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Peru-Violence     07-15 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peru-Violence ,0359</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest private television
stations began limiting coverage of guerrilla violence in a bid to
encourage peace, and the government prolonged a state of emergency
to combat the rebels.
   Also Thursday, Maoist rebels from the group known as Shining
Path shot to death the city administrator of Chincha, 120 miles
south of Lima, police said.
   Television coverage of Peru's eight-year rebel insurgency had
become a battle ground among stations in ratings wars, with some
channels dedicating up to 15 minutes a night to violent footage.
   ``The accord of a minute'' was agreed to by Lima channels 2, 4,
5 and 9 _ most of the city's stations. It calls for the time
alloted to local news reports of violence held to 60 seconds per
broadcast.
   Channel 5 press director Carlos Paz said the goal of the
self-imposed pact was to contribute to national pacification.
   President Alan Garcia prolonged a state of emergency for two
months in the coastal capital of Lima and parts of six other states
in the Andes Mountains and Amazon jungle. The announcement was made
in a decree in the official gazette El Peruano.
   Police said three Shining Path guerrilla gunmen killed
administrator Mario Casas, a member of Garcia's center-left Aprista
Party, near his Chincha home and escaped before authorities
arrived. The official was leaving home for work.
   The assassination was carried out like dozens of others by the
rebel band against government and party officials.
   But most of the more than 10,000 people slain during the
insurgency have been highland peasants caught in the fighting
between guerrillas and government forces.
   The state of emergency was first imposed in highland Ayacucho
two years after the Shining Path, inspired by the late Chinese
leader Mao Zedong, launched its insurgency there in 1980 to topple
Peru's elected government and install Marxist rule.
   A state of emergency suspends citizens' rights to meet publicly
and travel freely, while permitting government forces to conduct
searches without warrants and hold suspects for long periods before
filing charges.
</TEXT>
