<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Argentine Freed,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Argentine Court Frees Former Economy Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's top court dropped
illegal arrest and extortion charges against the most prominent
civilian in a former military government.
   But the Federal Court on Thursday also upheld the same charges
against former President Gen. Jorge Videla and former Interior
Minister Gen. Albano Harguindeguy.
   Thursday's decision freed former Economy Minister Jose Martinez
de Hoz. The court gave no reason for its action.
   All three had been charged in the case of two Argentine
businessmen who said they were victimized by the government leaders
in 1976.
   The former economy minister, jailed with Harguindeguy in this
capital since April 27, drove off from prison Thursday without
comment.
   Videla already is serving a life sentence in connection with his
conviction for human rights violations during the military's
1976-83 rule over Argentina.
</TEXT>
