<DOCNO> AP880715-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0322EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NomineeRejection     07-15 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nominee Rejection,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Gives up Bid to Confirm Reagan Judicial Nominee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Republicans say they'll ``make no
effort'' to wage a floor fight for Bernard Siegan, a conservative
appellate court nominee whose writings were cited as too extreme to
win Democratic backing.
   In a vote that had similarities to the rejection last year of
Supreme Court nominee Robert H. Bork, the Democratic-led Judiciary
Committee voted 8-6 along party lines Thursday to recommend Senate
rejection of Siegan.
   The professor of constitutional law at the University of San
Diego was President Reagan's nominee for the 9th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals, covering nine Western states.
   Like Bork, Siegan wrote often on the law, and _ like Bork _ his
views often were contrary to precedents set by the Supreme Court,
especially on civil rights and civil liberties.
   But while senators decided a Supreme Court nominee deserved a
full Senate vote, even Siegan's supporters said no such effort
would be made for him.
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., whose motion to report the
nomination without recommendation failed on a 7-7 tie, said
afterwards that Republicans ``will make no effort to take it to the
floor. It's obvious that it's over.''
   Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah and another Siegan supporter, agreed
that there would be no floor fight.
   Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz. first voted for rejection, but
then sided with the Republican no-recommendation motion.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., who offered the motion to
reject Siegan, criticized the nominee's almost total lack of
experience before federal courts _ he had one case three decades
ago _ and said the nominee practiced ``judicial activism in the
extreme.''
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., agreed that Siegan's writings were
``extreme'' but voted for him anyway, arguing a law professor
should have freedom to write what he chooses.
   Specter, who opposed Bork, said he would be more concerned about
Siegan's views if he were a Supreme Court nominee. An appellate
court candidate would have no choice but to follow Supreme Court
rulings, he said _ a point Siegan made in two confirmation hearings.
   Siegan wrote that prayer in schools could be constitutional,
although the Supreme Court has said otherwise. He contended that
equal weight should be given to property rights and human rights.
He said framers of the 14th Amendment, which guarantees basic
freedoms, never intended its scope to be as broad as that defined
by the Supreme Court.
   Siegan also disagreed with the high court's reasoning in its
1954 decision outlawing school segregation, although he agreed with
the result.
   The landmark ruling, Siegan said, should have been based on the
right of black students to travel to the schools of their choice.
His critics said this would have left students at the schoolhouse
door, without guaranteeing a seat inside.
   Siegan, 63, was only the second judicial nominee to be rejected
by the Judiciary Committee since the Democrats regained control in
January 1987. Bork was the first.
   Although the two men disagreed on some areas of the law, both
wrote often from their positions as law school scholars. Bork went
on to become a federal appellate judge, although he resigned after
his defeat for the high court.
   Siegan, after a state court practice, went on to become a
professor. His lack of federal court experience was cited by
Democrats opposing him.
   ``He hasn't handled a case since I was 12 years old _ 36 years
ago,'' said Sen. Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals has jurisdiction over
Alaska, Arizona, California, Hawaii, Idaho, Montana, Nevada,
Oregon, Washington, Guam and the Northern Mariana Islands.
</TEXT>
