<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0322EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TradeBill     07-15 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade Bill,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen: Campaign Won't Lure Me Away from Trade Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Lloyd Bentsen is promising to keep up
his push for trade legislation even though he expects to spend
considerable time on the vice presidential campaign trail.
   ``I'll be taking some of my time to work on that trade bill here
in the Senate,'' the Texan said Thursday at a meeting of his Senate
Finance Committee. He said he had ``talked to Governor Dukakis on
that'' and received approval to keep working on the trade measure.
   The measure was approved by the House on Wednesday and sent to
the Senate, where there could be floor action before mid-August.
   The decision by Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis to tap
Bentsen as his running mate heightens prospects for Senate approval
of the legislation, in the view of some Democrats.
   In related action, a legislative blueprint for implementing the
U.S.-Canadian free trade agreement won approval Thursday from the
Finance Committee. The plan also cleared the House House Ways and
Means Committee.
   Tariffs between the two nations would be phased out over the
next 10 years under the agreement.
   Under special procedures reserved for international trade pacts,
the administration will now introduce implementing legislation that
follows closely the blueprint drawn up by the two committees.
   Congress guarantees in turn that the legislation gets speeded up
consideration, with amendments ruled out.
   Administration officials promised the Finance Committee that the
legislation would not include subsidies for the U.S. uranium
industry, which had been delaying action by the two committees.
   Both Bentsen and Ways and Means Committee Chairman Dan
Rostenkowski, D-Ill., balked at the uranium subsidy plan. Other
squabbles also were settled and officials said the path appeared
clear for approval of the agreement and the bill.
   ``We've set an example for the entire world on what can be
accomplished with free trade,'' Bentsen said. ``This is a historic
moment.''
   Rostenkowski issued a statement saying the lawmakers had
``reached agreement among ourselves and with the administration on
the details of the implementing legislation.''
   ``I believe that this consultative process has developed a
sound, well crafted implementing bill, which balances all
interests,'' he said.
   ``It fully carries out our obligations under the agreement but
also protects the legitimate intrerests of those few industries
concerned about possible adverse effects on their current business
dealings,'' he said.
</TEXT>
