<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Blacks-Jackson     07-15 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Blacks-Jackson,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Leaders Urge Dukakis To Quickly Move To Mend Rift With
Jackson</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black leaders say it is urgent that Democratic
presidential candidate Michael Dukakis heal his rift with Jesse
Jackson, the man he defeated, and they predict next week's party
convention could be ``on the wild and ragged side.''
   ``There has to be a real healing process set in motion,'' said
Benjamin Hooks, executive director of the National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People, adding that he would try to play
a role in reconciling the two sides in Atlanta.
   ``I'm concerned that the black community not feel that in
snubbing Mr. Jackson, Gov. Dukakis has snubbed them,'' Hooks said.
   ``Up to now the Jackson campaign has been healthy for the
Democratic party, and I see no reason why it shouldn't continue to
be healthy,'' said Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young.
   Black members of Congress planned a series of meetings for this
weekend and early next week aimed at reconciling the party's split
factions. Sessions were being set first with Jackson to develop a
unified strategy, then with Dukakis or his top aide, Paul Brountas.
   ``Clearly the way Jesse Jackson was dealt with, on a personal
basis, looms as a monumental issue,'' said Rep. Ron Dellums,
D-Calif. ``It speaks to how black people are perceived in this
election. He is the personification of the hopes of millions of
people. Whether Mr. Dukakis understands that or not is something
that remains to be seen.''
   Dellums said the snub gives the appearance that Dukakis is
courting conservatives who have been fickle to the Democratic party
and taking for granted the black voters who have been its most
loyal supporters.
   Several black leaders said they expect the path to
reconciliation to be rocky, and Rep. Gus Savage, D-Ill., vowed to
stage several protests, including a Monday march from the grave of
slain civil rights leader Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. to the Omni
convention center.
   ``I think there's going to be a lot of confusion down in
Atlanta, a lot of pain down there,'' Dellums said.
   Added Hooks: ``It will be a little on the wild and ragged side.
But we'll leave there together.''
   Jackson and his supporters were stung by Dukakis' selection of
Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen for the vice presidential spot on the
Democratic ticket, and the hurt was compounded when Jackson first
learned about the choice from reporters rather than directly from
Dukakis.
   Dukakis telephoned Jackson on Wednesday to try to mend the
damage, and Jackson said Thursday he had asked former President
Jimmy Carter to mediate between the two camps. Jackson also said he
got an apology from a top Dukakis aide but no apology from Dukakis.
He said he wasn't seeking one, though.
   The lawmakers said their concerns extended beyond the personal
tiff to the appearance that issues of concern to blacks were being
given short shrift.
   ``We are trying to salvage this,'' said Rep. Mervyn Dymally,
chairman of the Congressional Black Caucus, acknowledging that
there is a wide range of intensity about the matter among the 23
black House members who make up the caucus. ``We are practical
politicians.''
   Some caucus members said they recognized the danger to their
political standing if Jackson appears to be going to the convention
purely as a spoiler, and Young hinted that Jackson should be ready
to compromise.
   ``This party has elected Michael Dukakis as its nominee,'' Young
said. ``His primary responsibility is to bring victory. He can't do
anything for Jesse Jackson or for me or the cities unless he wins
election.''
   The black caucus was working through Rep. Nicholas Mavroules,
D-Mass., to set up meetings with the Dukakis camp, and Mavroules
said he expected there to be a lengthy meeting, perhaps on Tuesday.
   ``I think it would be a very wise idea on the part of the
Dukakis people,'' Mavroules said. ``They can talk at length about
problems, about issues. And if they want, they can talk about the
Jackson thing. ... I would like very much if we could have a nice,
good, normal, united convention.''
   Mavroules said the members of the Congressional Black Caucus
``play a very key role. We need them with us. I think most of them
want this settled.''
</TEXT>
