<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Drought     07-15 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Drought,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says ``We Can Help To Ease The Pain''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, back from a look at what he
called the ``worst natural disaster since the Dust Bowl,'' is
sending a team headed by Secretary of Agriculture Richard Lyng on a
tour of 11 drought-stricken states from Tennessee to the Dakotas.
   Reagan inspected corn and soybean fields in southern Illinois on
Thursday and appealed to Congress to focus its attention on drought
relief, putting aside partisanship and efforts to rewrite the
overall farm laws.
   ``Politics must stop at the parched field's edge,'' Reagan said
in Davenport, Iowa, paraphrasing a traditional foreign policy
slogan that partisanship should stop at the water's edge.
   The president spoke at a luncheon in Davenport after inspecting
crop damage at the Du Quoin State Fair grounds and the nearby farm
of Herman Krone near Marion, Ill.
   ``We should keep our eye on the ball,'' he told the luncheon
audience. ``Drought relief should be just that, drought relief.''
   Both in Davenport and at the fair grounds, Reagan urged the
lawmakers to avoid amendments not relevant to the drought crisis.
   ``What I saw was not a pretty sight,'' Reagan said after walking
through the shriveled fields and viewing them from a helicopter.
   ``We can't make it rain but we can help to ease the pain, and
that's what the federal government will do,'' he told state
agriculture officials and farmers gathered at the fair grounds.
   ``From Montana to Texas, from California to Georgia, and right
here in Illinois, farmers face the worst natural disaster since the
Dust Bowl of the 1930s,'' the president said.
   On Air Force One flying back to Washington, Lyng said he and his
task force plan to visit 11 states, beginning next Tuesday. He
listed Ohio, Indiana, Tennessee, Missouri, Iowa, Oklahoma, North
Dakota, South Dakota, Minnesota, Michigan and Wisconsin. He said he
would be accompanied by representatives of the Interior Department,
Army Corps of Engineers and several other agencies.
   Meanwhile in Washington, the Senate Agriculture Committee
approved a $5.5 billion drought relief bill after adopting 10
amendments. The corresponding committee of the House is considering
a similar bill.
   Lyng told reporters that the Senate bill appeared to be ``pretty
close to the package we've been talking about.''
   In Davenport, Reagan spoke at a luncheon sponsored by Radio
Station WOC and the local chamber of commerce after taking part in
65th anniversary observances of the station, where he began his
entertainment career as an announcer in the 1930s.
   In an interview with WOC, Reagan said he is waiting for the farm
relief bill. ``I will sign it the minute it is delivered to me,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
