<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0328EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     07-15 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Turns Attention To State Budget Crunch</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State budget problems are dogging Michael Dukakis
in the days before he travels to the Democratic National Convention
to receive his party's presidential nomination.
   While most of his headquarters campaign staff made a wholesale
move to the convention site in Atlanta on Thursday, Dukakis spent
most of the day in a search for ways to deal with deficits in
budgets for the current and past fiscal years.
   The governor and his fellow Democrats who dominate the state
legislature were determined to resolve the budget problems before
Dukakis heads for Atlanta on Sunday and deny Republicans an
opportunity to attack the Democratic candidate's claim to be an
efficient manager.
   ``The Atlanta express is rolling,'' Massachusetts House GOP
leader Steven Pierce said during the legislative budget debate.
``You Democrats want out of here. You don't (care) what happens to
the budget.''
   Vice President George Bush, who has clinched the Republican
presidential nomination, already has attacked Dukakis for approving
more than $100 million in new taxes as part of a budget-balancing
plan.
   While Dukakis was trying to clear his desk of state problems, he
also was confronted by threats to his goal of a party convention
that will reflect party unity.
   Jesse Jackson, saying ``I simply want respect and
responsibility,'' suggested that former President Jimmy Carter step
in and mediate differences between the Dukakis and Jackson camps.
   Dukakis spokesman Mark Gearan, asked about Jackson's call for
mediation, said only that the two sides had been talking throughout
the campaign and would keep doing so.
   In Atlanta, Carter spokesman Carrie Harmon confirmed that Carter
had spoken with Jackson by telephone, but would not comment on
whether he would get involved in any mediation effort.
   Both Dukakis and his aides minimized the prospect that Jackson's
displeasure over the handling of Dukakis' selection of Texas Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen as his running mate would endanger party unity.
   But as he left Chicago on a bus caravan for Atlanta, Jackson
refused to rule out the possibility of a convention challenge to
the choice of Bentsen.
   Later, however, after his caravan arrived in Indianapolis,
Jackson said, ``We hope in the next three or four days that matters
will be resolved.''
   And Dukakis, asked during a CBS interview if he expected a
display of unity in Atlanta that would include Jackson, said ``I
expect that you will.''
   ``Democratic conventions seldom begin on a note of unity,'' said
senior Dukakis campaign aide Kirk O'Donnell. ``But in recent years
they have ended on one.''
   Dukakis, as he has done in the past, took a tough line toward
Jackson's complaints about his vice presidential selection process.
   ``Obviously in a contest like this somebody wins and somebody
loses and I'm the guy who's won and it's my job to go out and pick
a running mate,'' he said in the CBS interview.
   Jackson complained that he wasn't notified in advance of the
selection of Bentsen and learned of it from a reporter.
   Mark Gearan, a Dukakis spokesman, said the nominee-to-be called
Jackson on Wednesday. ``The governor obviously made it clear that
it was his own intention for the Reverend Jackson and all of the
candidates to hear the news from no one else but the governor,'' he
said.
   Gearan declined to say whether the governor had apologized.
   Jackson spokesman Ron Brown termed Dukakis' gesture an
``important call and a good start'' toward healing relations, but
made it clear he expects there will be a number of conversations
between the two men in the days ahead.
   Dukakis' only public foray outside the statehouse on Thursday
was a visit to two state troppers recovering from gunshot wounds
suffered in a drug raid.
   Outside Boston City Hospital, Dukakis, using a police cruiser as
a table, signed legislation toughening sentences for people
convicted of possession of cocaine.
   ``We're serious about a war on drugs in this state,'' said the
governor, sounding a familiar campaign theme.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
