<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0339EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen     07-15 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Predicts Tough Fight In Texas</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen is predicting that he and
Michael Dukakis will triumph over Republican George Bush this fall
in the vice president's adopted home state of Texas. But he's not
claiming it will be easy.
   ``I think it will be close. I think it will be tough, but I
think we'll win it,'' the Texas senator said Thursday.
   ``Vamos a ver,'' he said _ Spanish for ``We're going to see.''
   One new poll suggested that Dukakis' choice of Bentsen as his
running mate went down well with Texans. Dukakis pulled even with
Bush in the state after picking Bentsen, CBS News reported Thursday
night.
   Its poll of 580 registered voters on Tuesday and Wednesday found
48 percent supporting Dukakis to 44 percent for Bush. With a margin
of error of four percentage points, that is statistically a dead
hea.
   Polls that were taken before Dukakis picked Bentsen had found a
big Bush lead in Texas.
   Bentsen deferred to his new political partner on Thursday on the
matter of mending the rift with Jesse Jackson, who had lobbied for
the vice presidential nomination.
   ``I know he (Dukakis) has a high regard for Reverend Jackson. I
assume he'll have a meeting with Jackson,'' Bentsen said in a
session with reporters from his home state.
   Bentsen said he believed he was chosen as Dukakis' running mate
because of his legislative experience ``which exposes you to so
many facets of this country of ours,'' his proven ability to work
with Congress, and his exposure through the years to various heads
of state.
   A senator since 1970, Bentsen is being opposed in his
re-election bid this year by Rep. Beau Boulter, a Republican who
has been fighting an uphill battle in the race. Bentsen is legally
allowed to run for both races under a law passed in Texas that
allowed Lyndon B. Johnson to run for vice president with John F.
Kennedy as well as the Senate.
   Bentsen could remove his name from the Senate ballot before
Sept. 6, but the Democrats could not replace him. Boulter says
Bentsen's dual candidacy is unethical.
   If Bentsen wins both elections, he would have to choose one post
or the other. If he gave up his Senate seat, as expected,
Republican Gov. Bill Clements would name an interim senator and
then call a special election to pick someone to complete the
six-year term.
   Already, Texas politicians were moving to stake out a possible
candidacy in the event of such a special election.
   Lt. Gov. Bill Hobby said he would ``certainly seriously
consider'' running if such a special election takes place. State
Agriculture Commissioner John Hightower also said he'd consider a
Senate race. Hightower already had been looking at a 1990 race
against Republican Sen. Phil Gramm.
   Among other Democrats looking to enter the fray are former Gov.
Mark White and Reps. Mike Andrews and Mickey Leland, both of
Houston, and John Bryant of Dallas. Attorney General Jim Mattox
also has expressed interest.
   On the Republican side, Reps. Jack Fields of Houston and Steve
Bartlett of Dallas have shown interest.
   The 1961 special election to replace Johnson in the Senate drew
more than 70 candidates. Republican John Tower won.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
