<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   07-15 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0853,0687</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Cabinet Minister Hit by Stone in West Bank</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to restore first reference to Shapiro; picks up
3rd pvs: He said...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cabinet minister was hit by a rock Thursday
when his car was stoned as he drove through the Israeli-occupied
West Bank, where the army imposed or mantained curfews on several
towns and refugee camps.
   The military administration in the West Bank meanwhile ordered
closed all eight Palestinian schools in Qalqiliya and 15 schools in
nearby Tulkarem until the end of the school year following student
riots, the army said.
   The army reopened 800 West Bank schools on Monday for the first
time in a week. The schools were closed because the army views them
as a focal point of the 7-month-old Palestinian uprising in which
222 Palestinians and four Israelis have died.
   Yosef Shapiro, a minister without portfolio, said on Israel
radio that when his car was stoned near Hebron, ``One stone went
inside and hit me. But we are strong people, and therefore we threw
out the stone and continued to drive.''
   He said it was the third time his car came under Palestinian
attack in the occupied lands.
   ``I think that the government could have done more original and
aggressive things, and in time, so we would not witness these riots
for such a long time,'' the right-wing minister added.
   The army clamped a curfew on Ein Yabrud near Ramallah in the
West Bank after a student protest broke out in the village, Israel
radio reported.
   It said Anabta and Beit Sahur villages; the western part of
Nablus, the West Bank's largest city, and Askar and Aida refugee
camps were also under curfew.
   The army also imposed a curfew on Qalqiliya, where a 12-year-old
boy from the Jewish settlement Ginot Shomron was struck in the head
by a rock Wednesday night. The boy was uncsoncious for hours but
was reported in good condition Thursday.
   Dozens of enraged Jewish settlers tried to enter Qalqiliya after
the attack but were turned away by soldiers, the army said. The
army was investigating reports that windows of three Arab-owned
cars there were smashed.
   Leaders of the Palestinian uprising have called on residents of
the occupied territories, which were taken by Israel from Jordan
and Egypt in the 1967 Six-Day War, to give Palestinian schools
nationalistic names.
   In the biblical West Bank city of Bethlehem, the Nativity School
became Palestinian Eagles School and Bethlehem School is now called
Palestinian Revolution School.
   In east Jerusalem, police arrested a 16-year-old Arab caught
throwing an empty bottle at an Israeli bus, one of about six such
incidents in the city Thursday morning. No one was hurt, a police
spokesman said.
   In central Israel, a small bomb apparently planted by
Palestinian militants exploded just outside Tel Aviv University,
but caused no casualties or damage, police said.
   In Haifa, a district court sentenced an Israeli Arab, Ali Nasser
of Araba village, to 15 months in prison and 18 months suspended
sentence after finding him guilty of erecting a roadblock and
raising outlawed flags of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Police in Beirut, Lebanon, said Moslem guerrillas fired nine
rockets into an Israeli military outpost near Marjeyoun in south
Lebanon before dawn on Thursday. They said the attack was in the
eastern sector of Israel's self-proclaimed security zone, but that
no casualty report was available.
   The police said that hours later, about 40 Israeli troops in
seven armored personnel carriers advanced into Jabal al-Dahr, a
mountainous area north of the security zone, and strafed the area
with machine-gun fire.
   They said three guerrillas were killed Wednesday when Israeli
soldiers and allied Lebanese militiamen of the South Lebanon Army
clashed with Hezbollah fighters in Libbaya, two miles from Jabal
al-Dahr.
   The police said Mohammed Bjaiji, commander of the pro-Iranian,
Shiite Moslem Hezbollah organization in southeast Lebanon, was
among those killed.
   Israel said it lost one soldier in the search-and-destroy
mission Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
