<DOCNO> AP880715-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0238EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PeaceConvoy 3rdLd-Writethru a0402 07-15 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peace Convoy, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0402,0717</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convoy Crosses All Of Its Vehicles Into Mexico</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3-4th grafs pvs, bgng `Mexico has...', with 2 grafs to
UPDATE with comment from convoy spokeswoman on firecrackers,
picking up 5th graf pvs, `The convoy...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NUEVO LAREDO, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The persistent Veterans' Peace
Convoy went through one Mexican customs station Thursday after
crossing the Rio Grande with 14 trucks and a school bus in defiance
of a U.S. trade embargo with Nicaragua.
   ``They're on their way south,'' said Tom Hansen, a spokesman for
the group that opposes U.S. policies toward Nicaragua's leftist
Sandinista government.
   Convoy members were later delayed for a time at a secondary
customs area after Mexican authorities discovered firecrackers in
one of the vehicles, an official said.
   The firecrackers, which were left over from the Fourth of July,
were disposed of and weren't the main cause of the delay, said
Juanita Singer, a convoy spokeswoman in Laredo, Texas.
   Convoy organizers spent much of the day arranging for escorts to
accompany the trucks to the Guatemala border, which are required of
any imports being taken through Mexico in unsealed trucks, she
said. Non-convoy trucks passing through the customs station also
were required to arrange for escorts, she added.
   The convoy paid about $650 for two guards Thursday evening and
headed for Saltillo, Mexico, about 3{ hours away.
   On at least three separate occasions, the U.S. Treasury
Department has blocked the group's trucks from leaving the United
States, contending that taking the vehicles to Nicaragua would
violate a 3-year-old trade embargo.
   The government maintains the food and medical supplies qualify
as humanitarian aid exempt from the Nicaraguan Trade Control
Regulations, but that the vehicles are not humanitarian aid. Convoy
members disagree.
   Eight ``convoyistas'' were arrested Saturday in a tense
confrontation with U.S. Customs officials, Border Patrol agents and
Laredo police after Customs refused to let the convoy cross the
border.
   One of the eight was rearrested early Monday and charged with
blocking traffic at the same bridge when Customs again refused to
let him cross.
   Later Monday, however, the group said it started crossing
vehicles and finally drove the last one across Wednesday. The group
said the first 11 passed without question, while the last four were
told to provide personal and vehicle identification.
   ``A very funny thing that happened was that different officials,
police and border and treasury officials ran into us in Laredo and
different places and advised us to go one at a time late at
night,'' said convoy spokesman Jay Singer. ``And so we tried it and
it worked.''
   ``They `mace' us, they arrest us, they break our windows, they
impound our vehicles _ and then all of a sudden they let us pass,''
said convoy coordinator Raul Valdez, 40, of Austin.
   Valdez said he drove ``Pathfinder,'' the lead convoy vehicle,
directly past U.S. Customs officials and paid his 75-cent bridge
toll at 10:30 p.m. Tuesday. The truck was involved with all three
incidents at which U.S. Customs has blocked the group's exit.
   Customs spokeswoman Donna De La Torre said Thursday that the
convoy had crossed into Mexico without the knowledge or approval of
the U.S. government, and that the group still faces possible
prosecution if it does not return the vehicles within 30 days.
   Violating the Nicaraguan Trade Control Regulations could mean
fines of up to $50,000 and up to 10 years in prison.
   Some of the vehicles bear signs and brightly painted slogans,
including a multicolored school bus emblazoned with, ``Veterans
Peace Convoy to Nicaragua,'' and ``Bikes, Not Bombs.''
   Ms. De La Torre said the government's policy toward the convoy
had not changed.
   Last month, a convoy attempt to cross with 38 vehicles and 106
people was blocked by customs officials who stood in the roadway
and temporarily detained four of the group's trucks. The activists
then drove to Washington, D.C., tried unsuccessfully to meet with
federal officials and returned to Laredo last Friday.
   The convoy is sending some 300 tons of supplies by ship. About
10 tons of supplies were loaded on the vehicles when the group
arrived in Laredo last week for its second attempt at crossing the
border.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880715-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0422EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-HamadiTrial     07-15 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hamadi Trial,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Accused Hijacker Says `Organization of Martyrs' Financed Trip To
Iran</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mohammed Ali Hamadi, charged with
air piracy and murder in the 1985 TWA hijacking to Beirut, said a
Lebanese group called the Organization of Martyrs paid for his
visit to Islamic holy places in Iran.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, told the court Thursday that
he visited Islamic holy sites at Qom and Mashhad, traveling via
Tehran. Asked by the judge to give a date for his trip, Hamadi
first said he could not remember but later said it could have been
in 1985.
   Hamadi has said he spent two years as a fighter with the Amal
militia in Beirut, but has repeatedly denied being a member of
Hezbollah, a radical, Iran-backed Shiite Moslem group in Lebanon.
   The group is believed to be an umbrella organization for
kidnappers holding foreign hostages in Lebanon. One of Hamadi's
brothers, Abdul-Hadi, is Hezbollah's security chief.
   The TWA jetliner was hijacked in June 1985 on a flight from
Athens to Rome.
   U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem of Waldorf, Maryland, was shot
and killed after the hijackers forced the plane to land in Beirut.
Thirty-nine Americans were held hostage during the 17-day ordeal.
   A court document introduced Thursday also indicated that Hamadi
was being sought on a murder charge in Beirut in 1983.
   The document, read by Chief Judge Heiner Mueckenberger, gave no
details. Hamadi said he was not aware of the charges.
   The document was obtained after West German federal
investigators asked authorities in Lebanon for assistance in their
investigation of Hamadi.
   Hamadi's defense attorneys questioned the value of the document
as evidence, saying it was an unsigned telex with few details.
   Hamadi also said that he smuggled explosives into West Germany
because he was afraid of ``committing a sin'' against Islam.
   ``I did not say no because I'm a Moslem and its my duty to obey
those who are wiser,'' Hamadi said, referring to a man he said
ordered him to smuggle liquid explosives into West Germany.
   ``The Koran says obey Allah, obey the prophet and obey those who
give you orders. I was afraid of committing a sin if I did not
accept.''
   He refused to identify the man who ordered him to smuggle the
explosives.
   On Wednesday, Hamadi admitted bringing explosives into West
Germany on two occasions. He was arrested at Frankfurt airport in
January 1987 when liquid explosives were found in his luggage, but
he said he had succeeded in smuggling another shipment a few weeks
earlier.
   In other testimony, Hamadi said he fought in southern Lebanon
against Israeli forces and took part in street battles in Beirut
against ``government soldiers'' and Christian Phalangist militiamen
in Lebanon between 1984 and 1987.
   He said he had been wounded in the arm by a bullet in streeting
fighting in 1985, but could not remember if his arm was still in a
cast in June, when the hijacking took place.
   Hamadi has testified that he was a member of the Shiite Moslem
Amal militia from 1980 to 1982. He said he also took part in
fighting during that period.
   He arrived in West Germany late in 1982 and applied for
political asylum, but returned to Lebanon in November 1984 after
his request was turned down.
   West Germany last year rejected a U.S. request for Hamadi's
extradition.
   A Duesseldorf court sentenced one of his brothers, Abbas Ali
Hamadi, to 13 years in prison in April for the January 1987
kidnappings of two West Germans in Beirut in an attempt to gain
Mohammed's freedom.
   The trial is scheduled to continue on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
