<HEAD>Man Indicted In Rapes Of Nine Girls, Claims To Have Raped 60</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 11th graf, `He was...', to CORRECT date of arrest to
July 6 sted June 6.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nursing-home worker indicted on charges he
raped nine elementary-school girls now claims he has assaulted as
many as 60 children in the last nine years, a spokeswoman for the
county prosecutor said Thursday.
   Anthony Johnson, 22, is ``one of the greater threats to female
children in Chicago who has ever lived,'' said Cook County Criminal
Court Judge Michael Bolan in ordering Johnson held without bond.
   ``We told the judge that in the course of his confession,
Johnson said that he could have assaulted or raped 50 or 60 girls
since the age of 13,'' Lisa Howard of the state's attorney's office
said Thursday.
   ``If any person should be held without bail, it's him,'' Bolan
said at a hearing Wednesday for Johnson.
   Johnson admitted raping eight of the girls aged 6 to 9 who were
cited in the indictment and possibly the ninth, said Assistant Cook
County State's Attorney Paula Becker.
   ``He can't remember all his victims,'' she said.
   There was no comment Thursday from Johnson's attorney, Howard
Towles. The telephone at his office went unanswered.
   The prosecutor's office announced Johnson's indictment Wednesday
on nine counts of criminal sexual assault, as well as on counts of
aggravated unawful restraint and armed violence.
   According to the indictment, the nine victims were assaulted on
the South Side between January and June 24. They were forced into
abandoned buildings and raped after being threatened with death if
they did not cooperate, prosecutors said.
   A knife and brass knuckles were brandished in one of the
attacks, Ms. Howard said. Ms. Becker said police recovered brass
knuckles from Johnson's home.
   He was arrested July 6 after a 9-year-old raped in April
identified him on the street while she rode in a car with her
mother.
   Johnson told police he worked as an orderly for Avenue Care
Center, a South Side nursing home. A woman who answered the phone
there Thursday said an orderly by that name had not been to work in
several days.
   Johnson's arraignment was scheduled for Aug. 4.
