<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-PastaWars Bjt   07-15 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pasta Wars, Bjt,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pasta Resistance: Italy Loses Its Noodle Rule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The land of pure pasta and taut tortellini is afraid
that Italians won't be using the old noodle anymore.
   Italy, the mecca of macaroni since the days of Marco Polo, is
bracing for what purists say will be an invasion of rubbery
ravioli, squishy spaghetti and, heaven forbid, limp linguine.
   ``In the coming weeks, Italians will have to say goodbye to
their beloved firm pasta,'' said the newspaper La Repubblica.
   On Thursday, Italy lost its bid to maintain its so-called
``pasta purity'' law, a 1967 rule requiring all pasta sold in the
country to contain durum wheat, which is firmer and more expensive
than other varieties of wheat.
   The European Economic Community's Court of Justice ruled that
Italy could not use the law to block pasta imports from the other
11 Common Market nations, even though Italy still can compel its
own pasta makers to use durum wheat.
   ``That flavorful and firm macaroni, the product of our able
pasta makers, will be challenged, and maybe even replaced, by the
gluey and insipid pasta from Germany or Holland,'' La Repubblica
moaned.
   Italians have been eating pasta for at least 700 years and claim
it was brought to Italy by Marco Polo. It is always cooked ``al
dente,'' or firm.
   ``We have a profound respect for pasta,'' said Giuseppe Menconi,
director of the Italian Union of Pasta Makers.
   ``Go to Germany and eat their pasta,'' he said in a telephone
interview. ``It practically melts on the plate. Our pasta is alive
on the plate.''
   Italian pasta makers insist the issue was not one of trade
barriers.
   ``This is a question of protecting the consumer,'' said Albino
Ganaspini, the spokesman for Barilla, the world's largest pasta
producer with an output of 450,000 tons a year.
   Italian firms produce about 1.8 million tons of pasta a year,
and the average Italian gulps down about 55 pounds of noodles
annually.
   Ganaspini said imported pasta could cost up to 30 percent less
than the kind made with durum wheat, but predicted few Italian
customers would lower their standards.
   The pasta case was brought to the Common Market's court by West
German pasta producer Drei Glocken after an Italian court sought to
block the company's export of pasta made with a wheat blend.
   The court's decision was based partly on a similar case in March
1987, when it ruled that West Germany's beer purity law violated
EEC free trade rules.
   The German rule had banned beers that did not contain the four
``pure'' ingredients: hops, yeast, malt and water.
   Despite the presence of the cheaper foreign beers, West Germans
have remained loyal to their pure domestic brews. Will Italians
stick to their pure pasta or go for the new wave of noodle?
   ``Sure I'd buy it, because it's cheaper,'' said Orsolina
Petrini, a Roman seamstress.
   But Claudio Cecarelli, owner of a pasta shop in central Rome
founded by his grandmother, said Italians will not mind paying more
for the purer pasta.
   ``When we eat pasta it is with a certain amount of
religiosity,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
