<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     07-15 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinista Crackdown Spurs Dissidents, Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leftist Sandinista government's
violent crackdown on its critics has backfired and given new
momentum to opponents, dissidents say.
   ``These actions are going to strengthen the attitude of the
common people who don't want this regime,'' said Virgilio Godoy, a
former Sandinista labor minister and the president of the
Independent Liberal Party. ``This is the start of the opposition
moving from words to actions.''
   Meanwhile, President Daniel Ortega said that any U.S. decision
to resume arms shipments to the Contra rebels would revive a war in
which a truce was declared months ago.
   ``We hope they (the United States) do not commit this madness,
since it would be newly legitimizing'' the civil war, Ortega said
Thursday on state-run Voice of Nicaragua radio.
   During the crackdown this week, the government broke up a
demonstration, closed independent news outlets and expelled the
U.S. ambassador. The fallout continued Thursday, when the U.S.
House voted 385-18 to condemn Ortega's government for ``brutal
suppression of basic human rights.''
   A similar resolution was passed Wednesday by the Senate. That
measure included the possibility of military aid to the Contras if
present Sandinista policy does not become more democratic.
   ``It's tremendously interventionist and illegal,'' Deputy
Foreign Minister Hugh Tinoco said of the Senate resolution. ``We
call this imperialism.''
   Tinoco defended the crackdown as a response to growing threats
from the Contras and from attempts to destabilize the government.
   ``We can't take this with our arms folded,'' he said in an
interview with The Associated Press. ``What country in the world
wouldn't take measures?''
   On Sunday, government troops used tear gas and truncheons to
crush a demonstration by 100,000 people in Nandaime, south of
Managua.
   The government said 31 demontrators were sentenced to six-month
jail terms on Thursday for violating public security laws. Five
others received the same sentences on Wednesday.
   On Monday, the Sandinistas expelled U.S. Ambassador Richard
Melton and seven diplomats, charging them with crimes against the
Nicaraguan people and saying they authored a destabilization plan
that included the Sunday march.
   At the same time, the government closed the Roman Catholic radio
station and suspended for 15 days the only opposition newspaper, La
Prensa.
   ``The free press was used as part of the destabilization plan,''
Tinoco said.
   La Prensa repeatedly attacked the government. The newspaper had
backed the Sandinistas when they came to power in a 1979
revolutionary war that deposed the dictatorship of Anastasio Somoza.
   The Sandinistas and the Contras negotiated a truce in March and
agreed to discuss a permanent end to their 7-year-old civil war.
But a series of high-level talks collapsed without agreement on
June 9.
   In recent weeks there has been a sharp increase in the number of
Contra attacks reported by the Defense Ministry. At least eight
civilians and several dozen soldiers have been killed in ambushes.
   A source in Santo Domingo in the Dominican Republic said
Thursday that Contra leaders planned to meet there this weekend to
reorganize the rebel organization and select new leadership. The
source spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The rebel group has been plagued by internal disputes between
moderates and hardliners and a lack of cash since U.S. aid was cut
off earlier this year.
   Opposition political groups inside the country, however, said
the government crackdown has fueled the anti-Sandinista movement.
   Enrique Bolanos, head of the Superior Private Enterprise
Council, said the Sandinistas reacted harshly because ``they cannot
stand the tremendous opposition that is gaining momentum.''
   The often fragmented political opposition showed more unity on
Sunday than ever before in striking out against the battered
economy.
</TEXT>
