<HEAD>Stocks Drop, Dollar Steady</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with closing prices; no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar remained steady in trading in Tokyo
Friday after opening higher against the Japanese yen, while stocks
seesawed to finish the day moderately lower.
   The dollar opened at 133.37 yen, up 0.42 yen from Thursday's
close, and stayed within a narrow range throughout the day. The
U.S. currency ended the week at 133.40 yen, up 0.45 yen from
Thursday's final figure.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-share Nikkei Stock Average
first rose, then dropped on profit-taking to end the day down
170.29 points, or 0.6 percent, at 27,913.79, traders said.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar's strength reflected
overnight gains in New York, following increases in U.S. interest
rates. They said many market participants were awaiting the
scheduled release later Friday of U.S. trade figures for May.
   A Bank of Tokyo dealer said the dollar probably would not come
under selling pressure unless the U.S. trade deficit exceeded $13
billion.
