<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Mandela     07-15 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Mandela,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Bans Mandela Birthday Concert</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government banned a
birthday concert for Nelson Mandela because it is terrified of any
event that honors the jailed black leader, anti-apartheid activists
said.
   Activists had hoped to the pop music show would be the highlight
of celebrations marking Mandela's 70th birthday.
   But Aubrey Mokoena, an activist who coordinated arrangements for
the ``Concert for Peace,'' said the Justice Ministry told
organizers Thursday that the show would be scrapped.
   The day-long concert was to feature some of South Africa's top
black musicians and take place near the black township of Soweto.
It was scheduled for Sunday, the day before Mandela's birthday.
   Mandela is probably the most popular leader among South Africa's
disenfranchised black majority. Mokoena said the government
declined to give reasons for the ban.
   ``The only possible conclusion is that the South African
government is terrified of the concept of the Mandela
celebration,'' Mokoena said.
   The organizers had anticipated a crowd of 25,000 people at the
concert and planned to donate the proceeds to charities. They had
arranged to hire a private security firm to ensure that no
disturbances occurred.
   Police last week arrested several people organizing a separate
Mandela birthday celebration in Cape Town. Activists fear that
event will also be banned, but the government has made no
announcement.
   Activists said at a news conference after the arrests that they
were determined to find a way to honor Mandela.
   ``In spite of all the intimidation, in spite of the obvious fear
of the government, our decision is clear: we will celebrate,'' said
the Rev. Allan Boesak, president of the World Alliance of Reformed
Churches.
   ``If we cannot come together in our streets and halls,'' he
said, ``we will celebrate in our homes and churches, but we will
make sure Mandela's birthday does not go by unnoticed.''
   Police refused comment on a South African Council of Churches
report that officers raided offices of Cape Town anti-apartheid
organizations Wednesday, confiscating posters advertising Mandela's
birthday.
   ``The police were looking for documents and posters they could
submit to a magistrate as part of their argument for having the
Mandela birthday celebrations banned,'' the church council said.
``We fail to conceptualize how the celebration of Mr. Mandela's
birthday with song and dance can constitute a threat.''
   Mandela has been jailed since 1962 and received a life sentence
in 1964 after being convicted of plotting a sabotage campaign to
overthrow white-minority rule. When arrested, he was leader of the
guerrilla wing of the outlawed African National Congress.
   Surveys indicate Mandela probably would be elected president if
blacks could vote in national elections.
   His release from Cape Town's Pollsmoor Prison has been sought in
a prolonged international campaign.
   But the government has said it will not free him until he
publicly renounces violence. He has rejected the condition unless
the government lifts its ban on the guerrilla group and dismantles
apartheid.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
