<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     07-15 0986</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sugar Making Comeback Relative To Other Sweeteners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sugar is making a comeback among American
consumers after years of trailing other sweeteners and might be
about ready to hold its own, says an Agriculture Department analyst.
   Robert Barry of the department's Economic Research Service said
that in 1987 Americans used more sugar, instead of less, for the
first time in 12 years. Per capita consumption rose 3 pecent to an
average of 62.2 pounds for the year.
   The deliveries of refined sugar to the food and beverage
industries, and wholesale and retail markets, rose 5 percent from
1986 to more than 7.6 million tons.
   Despite the increase, sugar still made up only about 40 percent
of the 152.4 pounds average 1987 per capita consumption of all
sweeteners, including those with calories and those without.
   Barry said in the July issue of Farmline magazine that growth in
the U.S. population and higher incomes have contributed to greater
sugar use. But there are other reasons, and one of the most
important involves HFCS, or high fructose corn syrup.
   ``After more than a decade of seizing markets from sugar in such
diverse products as beverages, baked goods, jams and other
processed foods, the cheaper to produce HFCS has come close to
reaching its technical limit of substitutability,'' he said. ``This
has stanched the dramatic losses of sugar in the past 12 years.''
   Barry added: ``Of course, there is the possibility of a
technical breakthrough (such as) lower-cost forms of dry fructose
or low-calorie sweeteners.''
   The sugar industry had been threatened by rival sweeteners for
many years but suffered no major losses until about 1975 when HFCS
emerged. Sugar prices were high at the time, and HFCS was cheaper
to produce, an advantage it still holds.
   At the time, in 1975, the beverage industry was sugar's largest
single market, using 25 percent of the sugar available. By last
year beverages used only 3 percent, turning to HFCS and non-caloric
sweeteners for diet drinks. Sugar deliveries to the beverage
industry dropped to 212,000 tons in 1987 from 2 million in 1975.
   But in other industrial uses, sugar and HFCS are not always
interchangeable, Barry said. For example, sugar deliveries to
bakery and cereal manufacturers rose to 1.5 million tons last year
from 1.2 million in 1975.
   Candy makers increased sugar use last year by 9.1 percent from
1986. One reason is that HFCS, a liquid, is less adaptable in candy
manufacture.
   A big question for the future of HFCS involves federal sugar
policy. Barry said that much will depend on whether sugar will
continue to be supported by the government at current price levels,
which encourage the development of substitute sweeteners.
   The U.S. sugar policy also involves imports and measures used to
protect domestic producers from cheaper foreign sugar flooding the
market. Although there was some strengthening, in May the world
price of sugar was still only 9 cents per pound, or only half of
the U.S. support price.
   Bills are in Congress which would lower the support levels,
thereby reducing domestic output and boosting imports. That is the
approach favored by the Reagan administration.
   ``Another initiative by the administration seeks to liberalize
trade through multilateral trade negotiations of the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT),'' he said. ``The goal is to
eliminate trade-distorting subsidies and allow better market access
for sugar worldwide.''
   Barry said a freer world market could reduce sugar prices for
American consumers but would probably also reduce the size of the
U.S. sugar industry.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Missouri and Ohio are the first states to be
officially designated by the Agriculture Department as a natural
disaster areas because of this year's drought, but others are in
line.
   The designation opens the way for farmers in the designated
areas to apply for Farmers Home Administration emergency loans. The
Missouri designation was announced Wednesday by Gov. John Ashcroft
and U.S. Rep. Michael Oxley, R-Ohio, who also announced the Ohio
designation.
   Oxley said 92 percent to 100 percent of Ohio's corn crop will be
lost because of the drought, according to federal estimates.
   According to FmHA officials, 514 counties in Missouri and at
least 13 other states have been logged for official designation. As
of Thursday, those included: Alabama, Arizona, Arkansas,
California, Florida, Idaho, Iowa, Minnesota, Montana, New York,
South Dakota, Tennessee and Texas.
   Other states also have submitted requests, too, the agency said,
including one from Gov. George Sinner who asked that all of North
Dakota be designated. Those, however, had not yet been registered
by FmHA, a spokesman said.
   In his letter to Ashcroft, Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng
said the Missouri request was based on drought damages ``Jan. 1,
1988, through June 24, 1988, and continuing.''
   Lyng said that to be eligible for FmHA emergency loans farmers
``must have multi-peril or federal crop insurance, if available, to
offset any losses sustained in crops'' planted after Jan. 1, 1987,
as required by the 1985 farm law.
   A total of 2,007 counties in 38 states also have been designated
for emergency drought hay and feed assistance through another USDA
agency, the Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation Service.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public comments are being sought by the
Agriculture Department on whether animals should be hot-iron
branded on the jaw for identification under federal programs to
curb certain diseases.
   James W. Glosser, head of the department's Animal and Plant
Health Inspection Service, said Thursday the rule-making procedure
is a result of a petition filed by humane welfare groups asking
that USDA substitute freeze branding or comparable substitute for
the hot-iron method.
   The branding is used to identify cattle and other animals
infected or exposed to brucellosis and tuberculosis.
   Comments can be sent by Sept. 12, including an original and
three copies, to: APHIS-USDA, Room 1143-S, P.O. Box 96464,
Washington, D.C. 20090-6464. Refer to docket number 88-098.
