<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     07-15 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard J. Hemmelsbach is finding
that being adopted by a childless baron is a costly honor.
   The Ferrysburg businessman was one of 10,000 people who
responded to a search by a German baron looking for an heir. The
search was first publicized June 3 on the nationally syndicated
television show, ``A Current Affair.''
   Hemmelsbach, 57, met Baron Theordor von Liebieg last week at the
baron's 100-bedroom castle on the Mosel and Rhine rivers in West
Germany and was chosen heir. He will inherit the castle when the
76-year-old baron dies.
   But there's a catch.
   One of the stipulations was that Hemmelsbach help the baron pay
off a $600,000 mortgage on the castle.
   ``I already have been adopted, but now I have to go out and slay
the dragon,'' Hemmelsbach said.
   He said his adoptive father said he sold the castle several
years ago to a developer who began turning it into a hotel and
restaurant but ran into financial trouble. Now a bank wants to
repossess the castle, Hemmelsbach said.
   Hemmelsbach said the baron also wants his heir to help him raise
$1 million to turn the hotel into an international hotel.
   ``He just does not have the vim and vigor to go out and do these
things, so he said, `This is something my new heir can do, my new
son,''' Hemmelsbach said.
   ``One of the reasons he chose me is because I have an
entrepreneurial background.''
   Hemmelsbach owns two small businesses in the Ferrysburg area,
including a sales company that represents acrylics manufacturers.
He also owns a company that developed an electronic warning device
for the elderly, he said.
   While the television show reported the 1,428-year-old castle was
on 89,000 acres, blueprints show only 100 acres, Hemmelsbach said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Henry Bellmon says he has had a sense
of deja vu on more than one occasion during his second term as
governor, since his first term was more than 20 years ago.
   At a meeting with Democratic leaders this week, several people
said the Republican governor addressed Senate President Bob
Cullison as `Clem' _ Clem McSpadden, that is, who was the Senate
president pro tempore during Bellmon's first term in office.
   Bellmon said Thursday he did not remember the slip but ``it
could have happened. I talked a lot with Clem.''
   He said there was a similar situation recently when he was
talking to a woman who worked at the governor's mansion.
   ``I kept saying Polly, but it wasn't Polly. She worked there 20
years ago. I couldn't believe it.''
</TEXT>
