<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0557EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-Election     07-15 0727</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Election,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Presses Protests; Salinas Urges Unity, Change in Shaken
PRI</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition candidates began a nationwide
round of rallies to press their charges that the governing party
stole the presidential election.
   The victor, Carlos Salinas de Gortari, said the governing
Institutional Revolutionary Party must respond to calls for change
after its biggest losses ever in the July 6 balloting.
   An estimated 15,000 supporters of conservative National Action
Party candidate Manuel J. Clouthier withstood a downpour Thursday
in the western city of Guadalajara to hear him accuse the
government of manipulating the election.
   He said his appearance in Mexico's second largest city was the
first in a national tour to gather signatures in a referendum to
decide whether the party should seek to have the election annulled.
   Clouthier, who won in Guadalajara but finished third nationwide
in results announced Wednesday by the Federal Election Commission,
said he does not know who won. But he said neither Salinas nor
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, candidate of the left, can claim a credible
victory.
   The commission, dominated by the Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI, said Salinas won with 50.36 percent of the vote.
Cardenas followed with 31.12 percent and Clouthier with 17.07
percent.
   Cardenas, candidate of the leftist National Democratic Front and
the Mexican Socialist Party, planned to begin a national tour next
week after a major rally in the huge Zocalo Plaza on Saturday.
   He said he would target regions where he considers ``fraud was
the most brutal and ran roughshod on our party members.'' The son
of one of Mexico's most popular presidents, Cardenas led a
dissident movement in the PRI before breaking away to become
candidate of several small parties.
   Commission figures showed he won in the Federal District, the
adjacent states of Mexico and Morelos, the central western state of
Michoacan and Baja California, the northern half of the peninsula.
   The loss was the biggest ever since the PRI was founded in 1929,
but it still retained control of both houses of Congress.
   Parties supporting Cardenas won four of the 64 Senate seats in
an unprecedented loss for the PRI. Both the left and the right made
inroads in the Chamber of Deputies, the lower house of Congress.
   The absence of any official presidential returns for a week
after the balloting fed reports of fraud and rumors of feuding
between old-guard PRI leaders who wanted their traditional
overwhelming victories and supporters of Salinas, who said he
wanted a clean election.
   Salinas, receiving congratulatory visits from party-affiliated
organizations Thursday, said he had been given ``a clear mandate
for change'' and called for unity among all parties and factions.
   ``The PRI today has the capacity and flexibility to face
successfully the call for change,'' he told state governors and the
party's executive committee. ``May no one try to convert political
plurality into national division.''
   Lorenzo Meyer, academic coordinator at the prestigious Colegio
de Mexico, said that since Mexican independence, elections have
been used to transfer power within a group or party rather than to
decide which would govern or who the leaders would be.
   ``It is because of this tremendous weight of anti-democratic
history that what is happening today is important and it is for
that same reason that the change in electoral custom _ from
non-competitive elections to true elections _ finds so many
obstacles,'' he wrote in the newspaper Excelsior this week.
   Change, he said, is only beginning.
   ``It's obvious that the birth of modern Mexico is turning out to
be a difficult and prolonged delivery and that it's still not known
if it will reach a happy ending,'' he said.
   Some of the PRI's losing candidates said the party must reform
to survive.
   ``With the triumphs obtained by the opposition a profound
restructuring ... of the party to recover the ground lost in the
past elections becomes indispensable,'' Cuauhtemoc Sanchez Barrales
told the newspaper El Sol de Toluca, 40 miles west of Mexico City
in the state of Mexico.
   He lost a congressional election in the Toluca-Metepec district
to a candidate from Cardenas' coalition.
   Julio Millan, an economic consultant who lost a congressional
race to National Action in the capital, said the party ``now has to
demand from officials greater efficiency and dedication, a pure
honesty and an attitude of service that the population is
demanding.''
</TEXT>
