<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-USElection     07-15 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-US Election,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Sends Delegation To Watch US Presidential Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has sent a delegation to the United States
to monitor the American presidential election and study democracy
in action, an official newspaper said today.
   The 10-member group, which left Wednesday, will attend the
conventions of the Democratic and Republican parties and interview
presidential candidates and other important politicians, the Legal
Daily reported.
   The daily said Chinese delegates planned to meet with American
politicans to discuss U.S.-Chinese relations, China's economic and
political development and international affairs.
   The delegation is made up of members of the Chinese People's
Institute of Foreign Affairs, a scholarly group; and the Law
Association of the National People's Congress, China's legislature.
   The newspaper said the delegation was invited to the United
States by the Washington-based Center for Democracy, which includes
members of both American political parties. It advocates democratic
change throughout the world.
   Under the liberalization program begun by senior leader Deng
Xiaoping, China has begun to reform its political system to include
elements of democracy.
   Some elections have been held in cities and counties for
government posts, although most of the candidates have been picked
by the Communist Party.
   Despite the changes, the party remains the dominant force in
Chinese political life, and no serious calls for a multiparty
system have been considered by the authorities in Beijing.
</TEXT>
