<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     07-15 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel To Restudy Issue of Federal Funds for Test Tube Baby
Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Reagan administration official says the
government is going to take another look at whether it should
finance research into test tube fertilization to produce babies.
   Dr. Robert E. Windom, the Health and Human Services Department's
assistant secretary for health, acknowledged under questioning
before a House subcommittee Thursday that a new ethics advisory
board is being formed but said the new panel might not be completed
in time for action before the Reagan administration leaves office
in January.
   Windom told the human resources subcommittee of the House
Committee on Government Operations that the decision to form a
panel to restudy the question on whether to lift a de facto ban on
federally financed research is in response to a recommendation from
Dr. James B. Wyngaarden, director of the National Institutes of
Health. Wyngaarden has recommended the government approve a grant
from Washington University in St. Louis to conduct in vitro
fertilization research.
   Although some 200 private clinics offer such services and some
5,000 babies have been born as a result, the matter of federal
involvement has been an unresolved issue dating back to the Carter
administration.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Drought Shifts East, Little Relief in Sight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Weather Service says it is
shifting eastward its focus on the drought plaguing much of the
nation, but the agency says there's still little relief in sight
for most areas.
   The agency's new short-range forecast on Thursday predicted hot,
dry weather to expand eastward from the Rockies through the Ohio
Valley to the Mid-Atlantic states through next Monday.
   Rapidly moving weather systems are expected to drag weak fronts
along the U.S.-Canadian border, possibly triggering scattered
showers in the extreme northern Plains and upper Mississippi
Valley. The heavy rain which has hit portions of Texas is expected
to diminish.
   Long-term drought conditions now cover a large area of the Great
Lakes region and the Ohio and Tennessee valleys, the agency's
Climate Analysis Center reported.
   In addition, drought conditions persist over large areas of the
northern Great Plains and Rocky Mountains.
</TEXT>
