<DOCNO> AP880715-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0455EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MysteriousBoy     07-15 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mysterious Boy,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sabath Goes to Children's Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hearing-impaired boy whose origins
mystified authorities for months until he was recently reunited
with his family has been placed in a children's home in Mexico.
   Jose de Jesus Garcia Aguilera, 9, was moved to the home in
Ciudad Victoria operated by the Integrated Family Development
agency. He can receive special education for deaf children there,
an agency spokeswoman said Wednesday.
   The boy, known as Sabath, was found last November near downtown
Ciudad Juarez, across the Rio Grande from El Paso. Because he could
barely hear or speak and couldn't write, authorities could not
determine his identity. Finally, the freckle-faced boy's mother was
located in Tampico, a port on Mexico's Gulf Coast.
   The boy, nicknamed Chuy, is staying at a home about 200 miles
from Tampico.
   Social workers tried unsuccessfully to persuade Chuy's mother to
giveup her son for adoption, DIF spokeswoman Juana Barazas de
Galindo said.
   ``She said she couldn't take care of him,'' Ms. Barazas de
Galindo said. ``She didn't want to give him up for adoption because
she was afraid she wouldn't be able to see him. His grandmother
feared he would run away again.''
   The mother reluctantly accepted the agency's decision to move
him to the school, DIF officials said.
   The boy was called Sabath because he was found on a Saturday _
sabado in Spanish. His drawings of what looked like a plane crash
prompted speculation he had survived a crash that killed his
parents and sister. Authorities now believe the pictures might have
been an attempt to tell them Chuy lived near an airport in Tampico.
   His mother, who had been searching for her son for about nine
months and suspected Sabath was her missing child, answered an
advertisement placed by an El Paso Times reporter in a Mexican
newspaper.
   The two were reunited June 28 in Juarez.
   ``His mother will be able to see him every couple of weeks. It's
a long drive but it's possible,'' his uncle, Nicolas Aguilera
Paredes, told the Times in a phone interview.
</TEXT>
