<DOCNO> AP880715-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0628EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FirebombDeaths     07-15 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Firebomb Deaths,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Neighbors Aren't Surprised By Firebombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM IRWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neighbors said they feel certain that rival crack
dealers firebombed a duplex apartment in which four innocent people
died and six other people were injured.
   ``There's been threats to blow up the house. You sit on the
porch and you hear it every day: `I'm going to get my stuff and
I'll be back and I'll blow you up,''' neighbor Dorethea Harrison,
20, told The Detroit News.
   Harrison and her mother and another family were left homeless
Thursday morning when the fire spread to their adjacent duplex on
East Philadelphia, a narrow, tree-lined street on the city's north
side.
   Harrison and other residents said crack cocaine was sold and
used for years at the firebombed apartment.
   Fire Department Lt. Thomas O'Neill identified the dead as
Carroll Jones, 66; Michael Conerly, 32; George Hill, 47; and
Dorothy Jackson, 39.
   The four victims were alcoholics and had nothing to do with the
illegal drugs, Harrison said.
   ``They just drank,'' she said. ``They'd fuss about their wine
and where to get money for wine.'' The victims weren't related,
Harrison said.
   Six people in the two-story building were injured and were taken
to Detroit Receiving Hospital, said hospital spokesman Dennis
Archambault.
   A nursing supervisor who declined to give her name said this
morning that none of them was still there.
   Police and fire officials have disclosed few details of the fire.
   ``All the witnesses that were interviewed have indicated there
was a firebombing,'' said a police arson inspector who wouldn't
give his name. No arrests have been made, police spokesman Sgt.
George Anthony said today.
   ``They did their business right outside,'' Harrison said. ``From
what I'd heard, they'd been arguing earlier (Wednesday) about
money, and they said they'd be back later to settle it.''
   Harrison's mother, Dorethea Thompson, said authorities arrested
several alleged crack dealers and boarded up the duplex about four
months ago.
   ``We were really happy,'' Thompson said. ``Then, a month and a
half later, (crack dealing) started again.''
   Otto Cureton, who lived with his girlfriend and two daughters in
the same duplex as the Thompson family, said he was awakened before
dawn Thursday by the sound of breaking glass. He said he went
outside, saw the fire and also saw five men fleeing on foot.
   Crack was dealt from the duplex next door ``on and off for the
past four years,'' Cureton said. ``Different crews would come in
and deal.'' He agreed with Harrison that an argument among dealers
on Wednesday prompted threats of violence.
   Thompson and Cureton stood in front of their burned duplex and
watched arson investigators throw ashes and charred wood with
shovels out of a window of the unit where the four alcoholics'
bodies were found. Temporarily homeless, they expressed sharply
different feelings about relocating.
   Asked whether she might find a new home in a part of Detroit
untouched by crack, Thompson said: ``I doubt it. Crack is all over.
So I don't know.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
