<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Southam,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vice President Of Southam Newspaper Group Dies At 80</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Watson Southam, a vice-president of the
Southam newspaper group for 27 years, has died at the age of 80.
   Southam died Wednesday of a heart attack after a game of tennis
in Toronto. Southam Inc. is Canada's largest communications and
information company and owns 15 daily newspapers.
   A third-generation member of the family dynasty, Southam was the
son of William James Southam, a former publisher of the Hamilton
Spectator.
   He began his career as a reporter for the Vancouver Province in
1930 and held various positions in the newsroom. By 1945, he was
production manager and moved to Southam's head office in Montreal
to become vice-president.
   Southam's son Peter, 54, said Thursday his father was most
interested in the production of the newspapers.
   ``He was mostly in the technical side,'' said Southam, manager
in the company's department of corporate and technical services at
the head office in Toronto.
   ``He had a deep interest in the presses, in the material things
and in the administrative side all along.''
   Southam retired in 1972. He travelled widely and played tennis
three days a week. He and his wife, Kitten, spent their winters in
Florida.
</TEXT>
