<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0629EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AlohaHearing     07-15 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Aloha Hearing,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Expert: Better Inspections Key To Avoiding Repeat Of Aloha
Accident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Proper aircraft inspection is the ``weak link''
in efforts to prevent accidents like the one that ripped the top
off an Aloha Airlines jetliner at 24,000 feet, a Federal Aviation
Administration expert says.
   A National Transportation Safety Board panel, which winds up
four days of testimony here today, is trying to determine the cause
of the April 28 accident and what it can teach about the problems
of operating aging airplanes.
   Tom Swift, an FAA national resource specialist on aircraft
structures from Long Beach, Calif., also told the hearing Thursday
that he believes the Boeing 737 broke open because a bonded
fuselage joint separated, leading to a rapid failure of the metal
along a line of rivets.
   ``It was the worst-case condition,'' Swift said.
   Another FAA witness told the inquiry board that tiny cracks were
found in nearly half the Boeing 737 jetliners known to have been
inspected under an FAA airworthiness directive issued after the
Aloha accident.
   An 18-foot section blew away from the top of the pressurized
Aloha jet over Hawaii, throwing a flight attendant to her death and
injuring 61 of the 94 people aboard. Passengers in the forward
cabin were exposed to the air while the pilot made an emergency
landing.
   Asked by inquiry chairman John K. Lauber what ``the bottom
line'' was for preventing another such accident, Swift replied it
rested with the airlines and their inspection programs for
corrosion and metal fatigue.
   ``I know where the weak link is, and it's in the inspection,''
Swift said.
   Such inspections are mind-numbing jobs, he said, adding that
research was needed to take the ``human element'' out of the
inspections.
   ``Hell, we put a man on the moon, why can't we develop an
inspection program that can guarantee we can find these cracks?''
he asked.
   The Aloha jet, built in 1969, had had 89,680 landings,
second-highest of any 737.
   Swift, one of the FAA officials who examined the jet, said he
believes adhesive gave way along a lap joint where parts of the
fuselage are bonded and riveted together, most likely because of
corrosion.
   Within a week of the Aloha accident, the FAA ordered all 737s
with 30,000 or more landings to undergo a special visual inspection
of fuselage lap joints, and 737s with more than 50,000 landings to
have additional inspections using high-frequency electronic
equipment.
   Airlines were required to fix any problems found and report test
results to the FAA.
   James W. Hart Jr., manager of the airframe branch in the FAA's
Seattle aircraft certification office, told the NTSB panel 291
planes were affected by the order. As of this week, he said, the
FAA has received reports on 100 planes, of which 49 had cracks.
Five or more cracks were found in 14 of those planes, he said.
   Bill Ashworth, manager of the FAA's Seattle aircraft
certification division, said he was concerned about the cracks but
saw no imminent danger to the planes or to air passengers.
   ``We of course are requiring that all cracks we find be
repaired. That's only prudent maintenance,'' he said.
</TEXT>
