<DOCNO> AP880715-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0631EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PeaceConvoy     07-15 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peace Convoy,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Activists Head Into Mexico Wondering Why They Were Allowed To</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NUEVO LAREDO, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-eight peace activists headed
through Mexico on their way to Nicaragua still wondering why U.S.
officials suddenly stopped enforcing a trade embargo and let them
drive across the Rio Grande.
   ``It's had a lot of us shaking our heads,'' said Gerry Condon,
41, of Santa Cruz, Calif., a coordinator of the Veteran's Peace
Convoy.
   The group cleared Mexican customs stations Thursday night with
14 vehicles after the group paid about $650 for two escorts to
accompany them to the Guatemala border.
   ``It feels great,'' Condon said after the convoy was cleared by
Mexican officials to leave Nuevo Laredo. ``We've been ready to go
for a long time. We feel it's a big victory, even though we have
far fewer people and vehicles than when we came down last month.''
   The U.S. Treasury Department blocked the group's trucks from
leaving the United States at least three times, contending that
taking the vehicles to Nicaragua would violate a 3-year-old trade
embargo.
   The government agrees the food and medical supplies qualify as
humanitarian aid exempt from the Nicaraguan Trade Control
Regulations, but says the vehicles are not humanitarian aid. Convoy
members refused to sign forms promising to return the trucks.
   Eight ``convoyistas'' were arrested Saturday in a confrontation
with officials at the border and one of the eight was rearrested
early Monday when Customs again refused to let him cross.
   But later Monday, the group said it started crossing vehicles
and finally drove the last one across Wednesday.
   ``Maybe they had a policy of going ahead and letting us slip
across as long as we were quiet about it,'' Condon said. ``There
were times when people looked the other way and in fact in some
cases there was nobody looking.''
   U.S. Customs spokeswoman Donna De La Torre in Houston said the
policy toward the convoy had not changed.
   ``We do not routinely stop vehicles heading south,'' Ms. De La
Torre said. ``But if someone announces that they'll be violating
the law, we'll know about it and will be waiting for them,'' she
said.
   She said three of the convoy drivers were allowed to cross
because they told Customs they were going to Mexico.
   The convoy cleared one Mexican customs station Thursday, but at
a second, some firecrackers were confiscated by Mexican
authorities, who insisted the vehicles have escorts. Escorts are
required for people transporting imports through Mexico, customs
officials said.
   The convoy left a psychedelic-painted bus, named ``Peace
Train,'' in Nuevo Laredo, for a charity organization, because they
did not think it would make the trip.
   The convoy first tried to cross the border at Laredo in June
with 38 vehicles and 106 people, but were refused permission. They
returned to Laredo last week with fewer people and vehicles,
because some members of the group had to return to work.
   Thirteen vehicles will stay in Nicaragua, they said, and one
will return.
</TEXT>
