<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Pollard-HungerStrike     07-15 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pollard-Hunger Strike,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Spy Ends Prison Hunger Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARION, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Navy analyst convicted of spying
for Israel has ended a four-day hunger strike at a federal prison
at the urging of his father.
   Jonathan Jay Pollard, 33, began eating Thursday, officials at
the U.S. Bureau of Prison's maximum security penitentiary said.
   ``We are very relieved,'' said Pollard's father Morris, a
biology professor at the University of Notre Dame. The elder
Pollard has kept in daily contact with his son since the hunger
strike began Sunday, and said he convinced Jonathan to end it.
   ``He proved his point and we didn't want this to continue too
long,'' Dr. Pollard said.
   Jonathan Pollard was transferred to Marion last month from a
federal medical facility for convicts at Springfield, Mo., his
father said. Since then, the elder Pollard said, his son's letters
have been diverted to Naval Intelligence in Washington for security
checks, but have never been forwarded to addressees.
   The prisoner began a hunger strike because he believed his
letters weren't being delivered, and because he thought attorneys
were being barred from visiting him, his father said. Pollard also
complained that his ailing wife Anne, also convicted and
imprisoned, was not receiving proper medical care.
   Randy Davis, executive assistant to the warden at Marion, said
Pollard was not visited by an attorney because the court has not
appointed one yet. Naval officials were not available Thursday
night to comment on the allegations concerning his letters.
   Pollard began refusing food Friday morning but ate later in the
day, Davis said. He ate breakfast and lunch Saturday, but refused
to eat dinner, and skipped all meals from Sunday until Thursday,
when he ate breakfast and lunch, the prison said.
   ``He's fine,'' Davis said. ``He wasn't on it (the hunger strike)
long enough to hurt himself.''
   ``I would imagine he thought he got his point across,'' Davis
added.
   Pollard was sentenced last year to life in prison without
parole. He was charged with passing classified information to
Israeli agents in 1985.
</TEXT>
