<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0636EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Liver-Pancreas     07-15 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Liver-Pancreas,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nation's First Liver-Pancreas Transplant Performed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first person to undergo a liver-pancreas
transplant in the United States is making steady progress and
appears to have been cured of his insulin-dependent diabetes, his
doctors say.
   ``He can go to the ice cream parlor now and nothing will happen
to him,'' said Dr. Andreas Tzakis, one of about 10 surgeons who
took part in the landmark operation.
   The 39-year-old New York City man, whose identity was withheld
at his request, received the organs during 16 hours of surgery July
1 at Presbyterian-University Hospital of Pittsburgh.
   In addition to being diabetic since 1969, the man had hepatitis,
an inflammation of the liver, which he got from blood transfusions
during a 1964 heart operation. The diabetes, unrelated to the
hepatitis, struck him when he was 20.
   The man eventually would have died from his condition.
   ``Both he and his wife ... are a very strong couple.
Psychologically, he's doing very good,'' Tzakis said at a news
conference Thursday.
   The man could have been saved with a new liver alone, but
doctors worried the single organ might have failed without a new
pancreas to overcome the diabetes.
   The pancreas, a pear-shaped organ behind the stomach, produces
insulin, a hormone needed to convert sugar, starches and other food
into energy. Severe diabetes prevents the body from producing or
properly using insulin, making daily injections necessary.
   Complications include kidney and heart disease, blindness, nerve
damage and gangrene leading to amputation. Tzakis' patient had
experienced only mild nerve damage and eye problems, which studies
show can sometimes be reversed.
   ``Our patient was an ideal candidate for this operation because
he unfortunately suffered from both diabetes and hepatitis, had the
proper motivation to undergo a complicated procedure and understood
the risk,'' Tzakis said.
   The operation had been performed only twice before, both times
in England, according to Tzakis.
   The patient was in serious condition Thursday, considered
normal, with the main threats being organ rejection or infection,
Tzakis said. He could be discharged in a month or so and remain
near the hospital for another few weeks before returning home.
   Two other diabetics currently are awaiting liver-pancreas
transplants in Pittsburgh, according to Tzakis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
