<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SunnyvaleShootings 1stLd-Writethru a0518 07-15 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sunnyvale Shootings, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0518,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunman Quit When It `Wasn't Fun Anymore'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to drop redundant first reference to Farley</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man charged with killing seven people
and wounding three others at a defense plant said on a tape played
in court that he quit his shooting spree after ``it wasn't fun
anymore.''
   Richard Wade Farley also told police that if the woman who
spurned him had gone out with him ``just once'' he would have left
her alone. Farley's obsession with his former co-worker apparently
culminated in the killings, police said.
   ``I hope she'll never do this to anybody else again. She can't
play with people's lives,'' Farley, 39, said of Laura Black in a
telephone conversation with a police hostage negotiator taped
during the 5-hour siege at ESL Inc. on Feb. 16.
   The tape was played at Farley's preliminary hearing Thursday at
Santa Clara County Municipal Court.
   He indicated to police Lt. Ruben Grijalva on the tape that he
was still angry with Black for spurning his advances. He said Black
got him fired from the company by disclosing a series of letters
he'd written to her.
   Farley also told Grijalva that he knew only one of the 10 people
he gunned down. He said on the tape that the rest just ``popped
up'' in the hallways of the company, and he shot them.
   The former ESL software engineer is charged with seven counts of
murder, three counts of attempted murder, felony vandalism and
second-degree burglary. Police say he walked into the building
loaded down with weapons and ammunition and fired at least 100
rounds.
   ESL is primarily involved in developing computer programs for
Department of Defense classified projects.
   Speaking in a distinctive Texas twang, Farley told Grijalva on
the tape that, ``I came down here to do as much damage to equipment
at ESL as possible.''
   Once he had ``run around and got through being upset it wasn't
any fun anymore,'' he said on the tape.
   Shortly before he surrendered to authorities, he asked Grijalva
on the telephone if Black was still alive.
   ``She can't regret it if she doesn't live,'' he said in the tape.
   He said he believed Black took an ``immediate dislike'' to him.
``She tried to avoid me like the plague,'' he said.
   However, he said on the tape that he has had Black listed on his
life insurance policy as his beneficiary.
</TEXT>
