<DOCNO> AP880715-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0656EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Taiwan     07-15 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Taiwan,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Calls for Communists and Nationalists to Join Hands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's leading daily said today the Communist
Party regards the Nationalist Party on Taiwan as its counterpart
and expressed disappointment that a recent Nationalist congress did
not end a ban on contacts with the mainland.
   The People's Daily, the official voice of the party, said in a
front-page editorial that the two parties have ``unshirkable
duties'' to carry forth the great traditions of the Chinese people.
   ``What we can contribute to the future of our nation and mankind
is unlimited. We hope that the two parties can rid themselves of
past differences and unite hand-in-hand to achieve the cause that
was left unfinished by our ancestors.''
   The Communist and Nationalist parties formed common fronts in
the 1920s and 1930s to fight Chinese warlords and the invading
Japanese, but fought a civil war following the end of World War II
that ended in the flight of Chiang Kai-shek's Nationalists to
Taiwan in 1949.
   The editorial said China ``highly appreciated'' the 13th
Nationalist Party Congress for dismissing the idea of an
independent Taiwan and calling for efforts to attain the historic
task of reunification.
   ``We believe that the trend of relaxing tensions will develop
after the conclusion of the 13th Party Congress. This is what the
people of the two sides expect,'' it said.
   But the daily expressed disappointment that the Nationalists
made no change in their policies of regarding the Communists as
enemies and maintaining the ``three nos'' policy of no contact, no
negotiations and no compromise with the mainland.
   ``This is really against the times and will of the people,'' it
said.
   The Nationalists, while saying the ban on official contacts will
stay, did approve a plan to ease the ban on visits to Taiwan by
mainland Chinese residents, allow import of raw materials from
China and permit Taiwan business investment on the mainland if it
is conducted through a third country.
   Last year the Taipei government removed restrictions on visits
to the mainland by Taiwan residents. Tens of thousands of tourists,
businessmen and people visiting family have since traveled to the
mainland.
   The editorial also said the Nationalists are unreasonable in
their statements that the Communist Party and the people of the
mainland should be separated.
   The Communist Party, it said, has become one with the people of
the mainland.
   The daily said China continues to welcome people from Taiwan for
visits and business and expressed confidence that the policy of
``one country, two systems'' can help reunify the nation.
   Under that system, Hong Kong is to retain its capitalist system
for 50 years after Britain returns the colony to China in 1997.
</TEXT>
