<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Denver neighborhood where two teen-agers were
shot and killed in a 24-hour period is ``at a very explosive point
right now,'' a minister who works with local gangs says.
   An undercover police detective Thursday shot and killed a
teen-ager who allegedly pointed a gun at him across the street from
the scene of a Wednesday night gang-related shooting death, a
police spokeswoman said.
   Rasheen Abdul Riley, 18, was pronounced dead at Denver General
Hospital, said Anne Montoya, police department spokeswoman.
   The plainsclothes detective, Bernard Montoya, yelled ``police''
and then shot Riley after Riley pointed a pistol at him in the
Fuller Park area, Ms. Montoya said.
   Undercover police officers had gone to the area to quiet a crowd
that had gathered to console Gracie Carolina, whose son was killed
Wednesday, Ms. Montoya said.
   One of the officers spotted four or five men lying in the park,
at least one of them with a gun, she said.
   ``This thing was just inflamed over there,'' said officer D.E.
Lindley.
   On Wednesday, Delontay Carolina, 16, was killed in a drive-by
shooting incident, Ms. Montoya said. He was reportedly shot at by
three people in a four-wheel-drive vehicle.
   One juvenile was in custody and warrants were issued for a
second juvenile and Darryl Wilson, 22, of Denver, she said.
   Authorities said the two shootings were not related. ``It is two
unfortunate incidents that occurred in the same area, but it's not
a related incident,'' said Ms. Montoya.
   The Rev. Leon Kelly, who works with youths at the Salvation Army
Red Shield Center, had said before the shooting that the animosity
gang members feel toward each other might spread to police officers
and that the neighborhood is ``at a very explosive point right
now.''
   He said the shooting Wednesday was inevitable. ``It was going to
happen,'' he said. ``It was just a matter of time.
   There have been at least two other gang shooting incidents in
the neighborhood in the past two months.
