<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0709EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Election     07-15 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Election,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservatives Win First Election Of Thatcher's Third Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With a mixture of relief and jubilation, Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative Party today celebrated a
narrow victory in the first special parliamentary election of her
third term.
   Party chairman Peter Brooke hailed the Tory win in west London's
Kensington district as ``a solid vote of confidence in the
government and its policies.''
   Energy Secretary Cecil Parkinson said, ``If there was a time for
protest, this was it _ and the opposition parties cold not
capitalize on it.''
   He said the Conservatives had done well, considering this was
the first chance for voters to protest Mrs. Thatcher's
controversial third term program, which includes an unpopular new
property tax.
   But voters in Kensington, where royal palaces and high-rise
tenements crowd into three square miles, drastically cut the
Conservatives' winning margin in the election Thursday.
   Conservative candidate Dudley Fishburn was declared the winner
with 9,829 votes to 9,014 for second-placed Labor's Ann Holmes when
results were announced early today.
   The winning margin was 815 votes. At the general election in
June 1987, the Conservatives' winning margin over second-placed
Labor in the 48,500-voter district was 4,500.
   The result was bad news for Labor. Bookmakers heavily favored
the Conservatives to keep the Kensington seat, but many political
commentators said Labor had a good chance of victory due to
widespread hostility to Mrs. Thatcher's latest policies.
   Since the 1987 general election, her government has introduced
laws to impose an unpopular new property tax, shaken up the welfare
system and ordered a review of the cherished National Health
Service.
   Labor Party leader Neil Kinnock, on a swing through southern
Africa, said in an interview with the British Broadcasting Corp.
from Harare, Zimbabwe: ``I was optimistic about the possibility of
winning.''
   But he said the current contest for the Labor leadership had
helped damage the party's chances.
   Former Labor Cabinet minister Tony Benn, a hardline leftist, has
issued a formal challenge to take over from Kinnock as Labor leader
and the party is scheduled to vote on the issue this fall.
   Kinnock has renewed warnings to left-wing dissidents that Labor
must adapt its policies or risk a fourth successive general
election defeat. But in response, Benn has accused Kinnock of
seeking to water down Labor's anti-nuclear defense policy and its
traditional demands for more state ownership.
   The outcome of the Kensington poll was also bad news for
Britain's two centrist parties, which paid the price for an
acrimonious merger last spring of their former electoral alliance.
   Both the merged party, the Social and Liberal Democratic Party,
and a breakaway Social Democratic Party ran candidates, splitting
the already minority centrist vote.
   The Social and Liberal Democratic Party candidate William
Goodhart trailed third with 2,546 votes. The Social Democratic
Party candidate John Martin was fourth with 1,190 votes.
   The election of Fishburn, 42, an Eton and Harvard-educated
former senior editor on the respected weekly, The Economist, means
that the Conservatives' huge 101-seat majority over all the other
parties combined in the 650-seat House of Commons remains unchanged.
   The seat had been held for the Conservatives for 20 years by
legislator Sir Brandon Rhys Williams. The election was caused by
his death last November.
   The lackluster campaign in Kensington, which contains thousand
of highly transient apartment dwellers, failed to excite local
electors and only 51 percent voted.
   The Kensington constituency is one of the most starkly divided
in Britain. In its southern part, rows of elegant period houses
belong to some of the wealthiest people in the country.
   Kensington Palace is the London home of Prince Charles and
Princess Diana. Charles' aunt, Princess Margaret, and his cousin,
Prince Michael of Kent, also have apartments in the palace.
   North Kensington, a high immigrant district, is characterized by
shabby streets of state-subsidized housing.
</TEXT>
