<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0713EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Yugoslavia-Unrest     07-15 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia-Unrest,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strikers Converge On Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,500 striking workers from a
bankrupt food-processing plant converged on the capital today to
demand higher wages and more work, Belgrade radio reported.
   The employees of the Agrokomerc company were met by hundreds of
Belgrade police officers who sealed off an area around the
Parliament building, the scene of several previous protests by
disaffected workers in this cash-strapped country. No incidents
were reported today.
   The workers walked off their jobs at the plant in Velika Kladusa
on Thursday, filed into buses late last night and arrived here this
morning to give their complaints to officials, the radio reported.
Velika Kladusa is 250 miles west of Belgrade.
   The radio said a government delegation agreed to hold talks with
the workers.
   About 8,000 Agrokomerc workers are receiving guaranteed minimum
salaries of about $50 monthly, ``which is not enough for
survival,'' Fuad Pasalic, the head of the company's trade union,
was quoted by the radio as telling government officials.
   ``Our children are hungry and have no clothes to wear,'' he
said. He told the government delegation that the workers would not
leave Belgrade until they are given at least $70 a month, the radio
reported.
   The employees also are demanding the replacement of some city
and company officials.
   About 5,000 Agrokomerc workers walked off their jobs Thursday
and 2,000 marched through Velika Kladusa.
   The state Tanjug news agency said that many workers then decided
to head for Belgrade, ``to present their problems to the federal
parliament officials.''
   Agrokomerc was declared bankrupt after it issued uncovered
promissory notes worth the equivalent of about $1 billion.
   Charged with embezzlement and other charges are Fikret Abdic,
the firm's managing director, and several of his associates. They
currently are being tried in Bihac, a Bosnian town near Velika
Kladusa.
   Workers have staged several marches in the streets after the
introduction in May of a government austerity program that allowed
substantial price increases and hefty wage cuts.
   Hungary's austerity measures are designed to curb the country's
175 percent annual inflation and help in repaying a $21 billion
foreign debt by introducing a more market-oriented economy.
</TEXT>
