<2ND_LINE>PM-Murder Racial,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DA: Victim had `KKK' Scrawled on Body</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents; 12th graf may be objectionable to some
readers.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The murder of a 19-year-old black woman
whose body had been scrawled with the letters ``KKK'' may have been
racially motivated, the Ulster County district attorney says.
   ``A racial motive obviously is a legitimate investigatory lead
and we're actively pursuing it,'' Michael Kavanagh said Thursday.
``We don't know that (the killing) was racially inspired ... If it
is racially inspired, that's a horrible development.''
   The letters were scrawled on the body of Anna Kithcart,
apparently with a sharp instrument, Kavanagh said at a news
conference. Miss Kithcart's body was found Tuesday on an abandoned
railroad bed. She was last seen Monday evening.
   There are ``certain parallels'' between the murder and the
Tawana Brawley case, but there was no evidence of a connection in
the cases, Kavanagh said.
   Meanwhile, the Rev. Al Sharpton, an adviser to Miss Brawley's
family, said Thursday that he and his associates would start their
own investigation into whether there was any connection between the
cases.
   Miss Brawley, 16, of Wappingers Falls was found last November
with the letters ``KKK'' and racial epithets scrawled in a
charcoal-like substance on her skin after being missing for four
days. She later said she had been abducted and raped by a group of
white men, but she and her family have refused to cooperate with
the investigation.
   Kingston is about 25 miles north of Wappingers Falls, on the
opposite shore of the Hudson River.
   The existence of the letters on Miss Kitchcart's body was
withheld for more than two days to allow detectives time to
question hundreds of people before the case attracted widespread
attention, said police Chief James Riggins.
   ``I think that if we had announced this from the onset, we would
have had every nut in town calling us up,'' Riggins said.
   Riggins conferred with the FBI, he said, and was told the agency
was unaware of any activities in the area by the Ku Klux Klan or
similar groups.
   Preliminary autopsy results indicated Miss Kithcart was
strangled and struck on the head with a blunt instrument, Riggins
said. A bite on the neck and other marks also were found on her
body.
   Meanwhile, a man arrested Wednesday on a misdemeanor charge for
allegedly ``engaging in sexual conduct'' with Miss Kithcart's
corpse remained in jail on $10,000 bail. Police described the man,
Joseph Kiernan, 41, as a transient.
   The Kingston Daily Freeman reported Thursday that the young
woman's father, Eugene Kithcart, said he hadn't seen his daughter
in two months and believed that she had fallen victim to drugs.
   ``I'm almost positive it was a drug rub,'' Kithcart told the
newspaper.
</TEXT>
