<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bolivia-Cocaine     07-15 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bolivia-Cocaine,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Officials Ban Coca Farms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said it will approve a new
anti-cocaine law that will ban most coca plantations and impose
tougher sentences on drug dealers and corrupt officials.
   The law is the first ban in Bolivia on cultivation of the coca
leaf, which is used to produce cocaine.
   The measure was approved by the lower house of Congress last
week and by the Senate on Thursday. President Victor Paz Estenssoro
said he will sign the law when it reaches his desk.
   The law limits coca plant cultivation to 29,652 acres and bans
production on 76,601 acres. Farmers will receive $2,000 for every
hectare of coca plants they destroy, with $365 of that amount
provided by the United States, which has long pressured Bolivia to
crack down on its cocaine trade.
   The law also toughens penalties against drug traffickers, coca
leaf producers and public officials who take bribes from drug
dealers or who interfere with the prosecution of traffickers.
   ``Over the next five years if the government can get
international backing, cocaine trafficking as it is known in
Bolivia can be seriously interrupted,'' said Frank Mocolini, head
of the DEA office in La Paz.
   Bolivia, South America's poorest country, produces an estimated
one-third of the cocaine that reaches U.S. and European markets.
   Last week, thousands of coca leaf farmers attacked a police and
U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency camp in the Chapare coca-leaf
producing region. Police say at least nine farmers and one
policeman were killed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
