<HEAD>Judge's Solution To Embezzlement Works _ With A Hitch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman ordered by a judge to pay full
restitution for embezzling from an insurance company is accused of
generating the money by stealing from her next employer.
   Ernestine Allen, 37, was sentenced last August to one month's
probation and ordered to repay the $10,300 stolen from Gulf Life
Insurance Co. She told prosecutors family members had agreed to
loan her the money for restitution.
   She was arrested in June 1987 on grand theft charges after Gulf
Life's parent, Gulf Group Service Corp., discovered she had been
writing checks for undocumented insurance claims.
   Mrs. Allen later found a new job at Southeastern Metals
Manufacturing Co. Inc. and repaid the cash, but was charged
Wednesday with second-degree grand theft and five counts of forgery.
   Assistant State Attorney Lance Day said Mrs. Allen took $47,725
from Southeastern Metals by writing 87 payroll checks to a former
employee and depositing the checks in her own bank account.
   Day also accused Mrs. Allen of writing five fraudulent money
orders for a total of $21,100, including one for $10,300, the
amount of the insurance company restitution.
   Bond was set at $45,000 for Mrs. Allen, who was being held in
the Duval County Jail.
