<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Guerrillas-Release     07-15 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Guerrillas-Release,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Colombian Guerrillas Agree to Free Former Presidential Candidate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombian guerrillas have agreed to
free a leading political figure they have been holding since May.
   A communique released Thursday after five hours of negotiations
at the Vatican Embassy here said the M-19 Movement would release
Alvaro Gomez Hurtado before a ``summit meeting'' of Colombian
leaders July 29. Hurtado is a former presidential candidate in
Colombia.
   The leftist group reiterated an offer of a cease-fire, the
statement said. Papal Nuncio Jose Sebastian Laboa read the
communique from representatives of the movement, the Roman Catholic
Church, labor unions and business.
   It said the decisions were made ``in the spirit of finding
routes that lead to a more equitable society, to the preservation
of human rights and reconciliation among Colombians.''
   A seven-member commission from the Conservative and Liberal
parties, the Patriotic Union, labor, industry, the guerrilla
movements and the church, based in Bogota, should prepare an agenda
for the meeting after Gomez Hurtado is released, the communique
said.
   ``The order for the release of Dr. Gomez will be issued by
Carlos Pizarro Leon, commander of M-19 at the earliest opportunity
that circumstances permit,'' it said.
   The communique said the government should participate in the
summit ``to contribute to the success of its deliberations.''
   The movement's formal name is the April 19 Movement.
</TEXT>
