<2ND_LINE>PM-Howard Beach,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Defendant Innocent of All Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury cleared a 19-year-old man of attempted
murder and other charges in the Howard Beach racial attack because
of a faulty identification and other ``loose ends,'' jurors said.
   A second jury is considering lesser charges against four other
defendants accused in the 1986 attack by a white gang on three
blacks, one of whom was killed by a car as he fled the mob in the
Queens neighborhood.
   Thomas Gucciardo was found innocent Thursday of attempted
murder, assault and riot after three days of deliberations. Cheers
filled the courtroom when the verdict was announced. Gucciardo
smiled broadly and hung his head back in relief.
   ``I was scared, but I knew that I hadn't done anything wrong,''
Gucciardo said. He said he was going to ``celebrate, then go back
to school'' at St. John's University.
   His eyes misting, he said, ``I'll go home the first time in a
year and a half a free man.''
   Gucciardo was charged with beating Cedric Sandiford with a tree
limb during the attack that left 23-year-old Michael Griffith dead.
Sandiford, 37, testified he was beaten by the gang until he feigned
unconsciousness.
   Three youths were convicted of manslaughter in an earlier trial.
A fourth youth was acquitted at that trial.
   Jury foreman George Isaris said, ``We had trouble with
identification. It was uncorroborated, and there were a lot of
other loose ends.''
   Gale Vinnette, one of two black jurors, said the description
given by Sandiford of the attacker ``did not match with the person
we saw.''
   Griffith's mother, Jean Griffith, said Thursday's verdict ``is
not justice.''
   ``Nobody knows the pain of what we're going through. For me, I
have nothing. ... I lost everything. My son is dead,'' she said.
   ``We picked the jury,'' said Ed Boyar, an asstant special
prosecutor. ``We believed they would be fair-minded people. For me
to criticize their verdict would be worse than sour grapes,'' he
said.
   The second jury is considering charges of riot against William
Bollander, Thomas Farino and James Povinelli, all 18, and John
Saggese, 20.
   ``I hope our jury sees it the way this jury does,'' said
Povinelli.
</TEXT>
