<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech     07-15 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Businessman Hailed by Reagan as `Hero for 80s' Testifies at
Wedtech Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a day of fraught, sometimes rambling
testimony, Wedtech Corp. founder John Mariotta said illiteracy kept
him from knowing about the illegal goings-on at his scandal-plagued
company.
   ``My reading ability will go as far as a comic book is
concerned. Don't try to tell me to read The (New York) Times or any
technical thing. That's not my game,'' Mariotta, 58, testified
Thursday at his racketeering trial.
   Once hailed by President Reagan as a ``hero for the '80s,''
Mariotta is on trial with Rep. Mario Biaggi, D-Bronx, and five
others on charges of turning Wedtech into a racketeering enterprise
that paid out millions in bribes to obtain government contracts.
   Mariotta denied those allegations, but it was his wide-ranging
stream-of-consciousness responses to his attorney's questions,
accompanied by fist-pounding, hand-wringing and finger-waving, that
provided the courtroom drama.
   Mariotta, the son of Puerto Rican immigrants, has claimed he is
virtually illiterate and that other company executives kept him in
the dark about their illegal activities.
   ``My writing ability is nil,'' said Mariotta, lives in
Scarsdale, a wealthy New York suburb. ``For 20 years you could look
at my company's records, you will not find one letter or any
documentation or anything in my handwriting.''
   Asked if he finished high school, Mariotta, who grew up in New
York's Spanish Harlem, spoke of his parents' fights over his
father's drinking, nights spent riding the subways with his mother,
run-ins with truant officers and his difficulties taking tests.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Mary Shannon complained to the judge
that Mariotta was telling stories irrelevant to his lawyer's
questions.
   With jurors out of the room she asked U.S. District Judge
Constance Baker Motley to make Mariotta stick to the questions
asked ``and not go off on these tangents designed to evoke sympathy
from the jury.''
   Mariotta piped up: ``Your honor, I'm not an intellectual like
these people seem to think that I am. I am not. I am emotionally
upset because it took me 20 years to build this company and you
intellectuals robbed my company from me.''
   During the disjointed testimony Mariotta denied giving Wedtech
stock to Biaggi in exchange for the congressman's help in obtaining
no-bid government contracts.
   Four former Wedtech executives have pleaded guilty to state and
federal crimes ranging from bribery to fraud and testified for the
government in return for leniency. They and other witnesses have
said Mariotta helped create a multimillion-dollar company slush
fund for bribes, payoffs and off-the-books luxuries.
   Wedtech grew from a small machine shop into a $100 million
defense contractor through a Small Business Administration program
that awarded government contracts to minority-owned businesses
without competitive bidding.
   Prosecutors charge that Mariotta concealed from the SBA that he
no longer controlled the company. But Mariotta insisted he was the
dupe of greedy men who later forced him out.
   In 1984 Reagan lauded Wedtech for its hiring of rehabilitated
drug addicts, ex-convicts and former welfare recipients.
   In 1986, after Mariotta was forced out, the Bronx company shut
its doors and filed for bankruptcy.

</TEXT>
