<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BabyAbduction     07-15 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby Abduction,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abducted Baby Shown Off As Her Own</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A secretary accused of kidnapping a
newborn from a hospital had told her boss she was pregnant, took a
maternity leave and then brought a baby to work to show it off, her
employer says.
   Employees put up an ``It's A Girl!'' banner, congratulated Linda
Lou German and held the baby during the office visit Wednesday.
   German, 26, of Wheelersburg, Ohio, was sent to a federal
penitentiary in Lexington, Ky. for psychiatric tests Thursday
following the safe return of three-day-old Lindsey Manns. The woman
was charged with kidnapping.
   It was ``just a case of desperately wanting a baby,'' said FBI
agent Roger Nicely.
   The infant was swiped from a maternity ward crib at Cabell
Huntington Hospital on Tuesday by a woman in a nurse's uniform.
   The baby was reunited with her parents, Linda and Donald Manns
of Harts Creek, early Thursday after German returned the child to
the hospital in good health.
   ``It's just an answer to our prayers to the Lord that got her
back for us,'' said Manns, 23, a coal truck driver.
   ``It was just the happiest time of my life to see my baby
again,'' said Mrs. Manns.
   German's relatives called a special hospital hotline Wednesday
night and German followed with her own call, telling FBI agents her
relatives did not believe the infant was her own, authorities said.
   ``She wanted to come in with the baby to prove to her mother and
her stepfather it was her baby,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney
Joseph Savage.
   German arrived at the hospital with the baby Wednesday night and
told FBI agents she had given birth in early July at a Lexington,
Ky., hospital, Savage said.
   A call to the hospital found no record of the birth, and a
doctor's exam concluded she had not given birth recently, Savage
said.
   German was taken into the room from which the infant was
abducted and ``began to cry and admitted she remembered taking a
baby, but was unable to remember what she did after she took the
baby or what hospital she took the baby from,'' FBI agent James
Kessler said in court papers.
   ``I realize now that this is not my baby,'' FBI agents quoted
German as saying.
   German worked at WUXA-TV in Portsmouth, Ohio, as office manager
and secretary to general manager Tom Watson. ``She looked pregnant
to me,'' he said. ``She came into the office yesterday with the
baby and showed it to the staff.''
   Watson said German, who joined the station in March, called July
6 to say she was taking maternity leave. German called the infant
Lauren Gray.
   ``We were shocked and very sad and my heart, our hearts, go out
to her,'' Watson said. ``She is a nice, softspoken person, and very
capable. Obviously, she thought it was her baby.''
   Watson said German, who has a 3{-year-old daughter, had a
history of miscarriages and might have lost her own baby. Savage
told a U.S. magistrate he believed German had faked her pregnancy
since December.
   The federal kidnapping charge carries a maximum life sentence.
   He said German was believed to have been involved in an
attempted abduction of another baby born at the same hospital.
   In that case, a Marrowbone Creek woman told police that after
she gave birth, a stranger visited her at home, brandished a knife
and threatened to take the baby before family members stepped in
and the woman fled.
</TEXT>
