<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Klan-Park     07-15 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Klan-Park,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Venable Wants No Credit For Park Named For Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STONE MOUNTAIN, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former mayor and ex-Klan leader James
R. Venable says he is appreciative but wants no part of the city's
effort to name a park for him on land he donated.
   City Council voted Tuesday to name a park for Venable, former
imperial wizard of the National Knights of the Ku Klux Klan, in a
move that came under criticism from the NAACP and the
Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith.
   ``I appreciate it,'' Venable said Wednesday, ``but I wouldn't
want any credit for it.''
   Robert Smith, one of the city's two black council members,
favored the move, saying Venable's past affiliation with the Klan
was ``not my concern.''
   ``I was born here and he was not the only one who did not like
blacks here,'' Smith said.
   Nickie Taylor, the receptionist at City Hall, said the phone
rang steadily Thursday. ``We've had people say they won't come into
our city now,'' she said.
   ``I think it's awful,'' said Coleman Seward, vice president of
the DeKalb County branch of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People.
   ``I'm not saying Venable shouldn't be honored in some way, but
not by a public park. I wouldn't go to a park with his name on
it,'' Seward said.
   Gloria Brown, head of a black civic organization here, did not
object. ``We all use the park; blacks on the Little League enjoy it
just like the whites. I think it's wonderful, regardless of his
views,'' she said.
   ``If he's generous enough to donate the land, I don't think it's
unusual that the park was named for him,'' said Ralph Shipp, a
black resident of Stone Mountain.
   Stewart Lewengrub, director of the Southeast region office of
the Anti-Defamation League, wrote Mayor Jane Rhodes, asking the
council to reverse its decision.
   ``The fact that Venable donated the land does not justify naming
the park for him,'' Lewengrub said in a statement. ``If Charles
Manson had donated the land, would they have named the park for
him?''
</TEXT>
