<HEAD>Conference Debates How Christianity Let Holocaust Happen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with resumption of conference,
remarks from Reagan, Kohl; picks up 10th pvs: This crime...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clergymen, scholars and survivors of the Holocaust
today applauded a message from West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
acknowledging his nation's responsibility for the Nazi genocide.
   ``Germans became guilty of that crime as individuals, but they
are collectively liable for the injustice committed in their
name,'' said Kohl's message, read to 500 people attending
``Remembering for the Future,'' a conference on the Holocaust and
its impact on modern generations.
   Kohl joined President Reagan, British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher, French President Francois Mitterrand, Israeli President
Chaim Herzog and European Economic Community head Jacques Delors in
sending messages to the conference on its final day.
   The West German leader's words were read by Robert Maxwell, the
Czech-born Jewish publisher who sponsored the weeklong conference.
Maxwell lauded West Germany's willingness to face its past, and at
his request, Kohl was given a round of applause.
   ``No one can rule out the possibility of comparable atrocities
happening again,'' said Kohl's message. ``It must not be forgotten.
It is an appeal to each one of us to examine our own thoughts over
and over again.''
   It said: ``We Germans are prepared to live with this terrible
truth.''
   Reagan's message said the world ``can never have reminders
enough about the tragedy that results when nations abandon their
reverence for the sanctity of every human life.''
   More than 500 scholars, concentration camp survivors,
theologians, artists and teachers met here to examine how
Christianity could have allowed the Holocaust to happen.
   ``The words `never again' must ever be the pledge of all who
pause in remembrance of those who have perished and of all who
cherish mankind's deepest hopes and ideals,'' Reagan said in his
message.
   The conference, which began in Oxford a week ago, concludes with
leaders of Christian churches joining in prayers for the 6 million
Jewish victims of Nazi Germany's genocide during World War II.
   Boston University professor Elie Wiesel, a Nobel prize-winning
author and survivor of the Buchenwald concentration camp where
10,000 people died daily, said that after a lifetime of studying
and writing about the Holocaust, he still could not understand how
it happened.
   ``Often I think of the children walking slowly, quietly,
obediently, to the flames or to the mass graves, and I am almost
grateful for the pain that links my memory to theirs,'' he said in
a keynote address.
   The conference ranked among the biggest of its kind held outside
the United States, where there has been an expansion in academic
studies of the Holocaust.
   Maxwell, 65, lost most of his family at the hands of the Nazis
in World War II.
   ``This crime, this disaster, has been examined mainly in the
United States,'' Maxwell said Thursday. ``Yet it was in Europe that
it happened.''
   Maxwell's wife Elisabeth, a French Protestant, was the main
organizer of the conference. As a child she lived in a largely
Jewish district of Paris from which most her friends vanished as
the Nazis rounded up the Jews.
   She has long believed that Christianity contained a strong
streak of anti-Semitism.
   The Jewish Chronicle, Britain's top Jewish newspaper, has
predicted that the conference ``could radically affect the way
British people and institutions think'' about the Holocaust.
   Herzog, in his message, said he hoped the meeting would ``help
to shape a future in which the horror will never be forgotten.''
   Mrs. Thatcher said it was important for generations who did not
live through ``those agonized years'' to learn how and why it
happened.
   ``That knowledge will help people everywhere who are determined
that nothing like this shall ever happen again,'' she added in her
message to the conference.
   Organizers timed the meeting just before next week's Lambeth
conference, an international gathering of Anglican bishops. Mrs.
Maxwell said the archbishop of Canterbury, the Most Rev. Robert
Runcie, pledged that the prelates will discuss the outcome of
``Remembering for the Future.''
   Leading participants included American academic specialists on
Jewish-Chr, A. Roy Eckardt and his wife, Alice L.
Eckardt; Holocaust historian Yehuda Bauer and the Rev. Franklin
Littell, an American Methodist minister who helped pioneer
Holocaust studies in the United States.
   In associated events, organizistian relationsers have arranged a London
exhibition of drawings produced by Jews in concentration camps and
a concert at the Royal Opera House featuring works by composers
Dmitri Shostakovich, Benjamin Britten and Gustav Mahler.
</TEXT>
