<HEAD>Secret Service Agent Charged in Assault on Lawyer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Secret Service agent has been indicted on
charges of beating and falsely arresting a lawyer who crossed paths
with a presidential candidate's motorcade while walking to his
apartment.
   Kevin Schatzle, 27, of Princeton, N.J., was charged Thursday
with two civil rights violations, each punishable by up to a year
in jail and $100,000 in fines.
   Richard Ward, agent in charge of the Secret Service's New York
office, said he couldn't recall any previous case in which an agent
was indicted for on-duty actions.
   The five-year veteran of the agency has been on sick leave
because of injuries sustained during the arrest April 10, said Ward.
   Schatzle was accused of kicking and punching Christopher
Gorayeb, 31, and then falsely arresting him near the motorcade of
Sen. Albert Gore, D-Tenn. The agent was part of the security detail
for Gore, who was then campaigning for the Democratic nomination in
the New York primary.
   Schatzle told passers-by who complained about his actions that
the lawyer had spit at him. Gorayeb claimed the agent attacked him
when he yelled an obscenity at the motorcade because one of its
cars almost struck him as he crossed the street.
   A witness videotaped the confrontation and presented the
evidence to authorities.
   Gorayeb, who specializes in personal injury cases, said he
suffered a broken nose and eye, neck and shoulder injuries.
</TEXT>
