<2ND_LINE>PM-Humanitas Awards,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TV Writers Honored For Scripts On Homelessness, Handicapped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A movie about the homeless and episodes of
``thirtysomething'' and ``Frank's Place'' won Humanitas Prizes for
TV scripts that enrich the human spirit.
   The 14th annual awards, including $70,000 in cash prizes, were
presented Thursday.
   David Nemec won the $25,000 Humanitas Prize for the two-hour ABC
drama ``God Bless the Child,'' about a mother and daughter unable
to break a cycle of poverty that leaves them homeless.
   Paul Haggis and Marshall Herskovitz received the $15,000 prize
honoring hour-long scripts for the ABC ``thirtysomething'' episode
``Business as Usual,'' about the death of a character's father.
   Hugh Wilson won the $10,000 prize in the half-hour script
category for ``The Bridge,'' an episode of the CBS series ``Frank's
Place'' that depicted a man's struggle to support his family.
   Joanna Lee received $10,000 for her ABC Afterschool Special
``The Kid Who Wouldn't Quit: The Brad Silverman Story,'' a true
story about a youth with Down Syndrome who attends college.
   Mary Jo Ludin and Lana Raichert claimed the $10,000 award in the
children's animated category for the ``Rocky's Rocky Road'' episode
of the ABC Saturday morning series ``The Flintstone Kids.''
   Marshall Frady and Helen Whitney received a non-monetary award
for their ABC documentary ``They Have Souls Too,'' about the
mentally ill.
   The Humanitas Prizes are given each year by the Human Family
Educational and Cultural Institute.
