<2ND_LINE>PM-Norway-Copter Crash,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Helicopter Makes Emergency Landing in North Sea, All Rescued</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAVANGER, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A helicopter ferrying workers from an
offshore oil rig made an emergency landing in the North Sea today,
and another helicopter rescued all 18 people who were aboard,
officials said.
   All the passengers and crew were safe, said officials at the
Norwegian Rescue Center at Sola Airport near this coastal oil
center.
   Rescue center spokesman Inge Kavle said a Super Puma helicopter
of the Norwegian Helicopter Service Company had to land in the
water about 80 miles southwest of Stavanger due to engine problems.
   ``It was a controlled emergency landing and no crash,'' Kavle
said.
   The 16 passengers and two crew members were picked up from
rubber dinghies by a Sea King helicpter from the same company.
   The Puma helicopter was on its way from the Ula oil rig when it
ran into trouble at 1:10 p.m.
   It was the second time in three days that a helicopter made an
emergency landing in the North Sea. On Wednesday, a helicopter
ditched east of Lerwick in the Shetland Islands. All 21 people on
board were rescued.
