<1ST_LINE>u i PM-China-Shultz 1stLd-Writethru   07-15 0663</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Shultz, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0531,0679</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Says No Agreement With Chinese To Halt Middle East Missile
Sales</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Shultz news conference, wraps
up previous. No pickup. CHANGES byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George Shultz said today that
China made no promises to stop ballistic missiles sales to the
Middle East, but he said the United States should not stop the flow
of high technology to China in response.
   ``We didn't come to any agreements about it (missile sales), but
... I'm sure that the subject will continue to be an important one
on our agenda,'' Shultz told reporters after meeting with senior
leader Deng Xiaoping, Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang and Premier
Li Peng.
   When asked about news reports of a Chinese-Syrian missile deal,
Shultz said Chinese leaders told him their only ballistic missile
sales in the Middle East have been to Saudi Arabia.
   The Los Angeles Times reported Thursday that an agreement was
``consummated'' under which Beijing would sell intermediate-range
M-9 missiles to Syria.
   Senior U.S. administration officials traveling with Shultz have
said the Chinese are believed to be marketing the weapons, which
have a maximum range of about 370 miles, but that U.S. officials
have no indications of a sale.
   The officials say the M-9, which is potentially capable of
striking targets in Israel from Syria, is at least nine months away
from production.
   More than 100 U.S. congressmen sent Shultz a cable Thursday
warning that future transfer of U.S. high technology to China would
be ``jeopardized'' if the sale to Syria went through.
   Shultz said he got word of the cable only after his meetings
with top Chinese leaders, but added, ``I think the way to try to
get at it with the Chinese is other kinds of constructive ways.''
   Angry over alleged Chinese sales of anti-ship Silkworm missiles
to Iran, Washington last fall temporarily froze some high
technology sales to China. The United States has also been critical
of Beijing's sale this spring of intermediate range CSS-2, or East
Wind, missiles to Saudi Arabia.
   In his meeting with Shultz today, Deng said the United States
and China should bring their relationship to a ``higher plane.''
   The 84-year-old senior leader said relations between the United
States and China have improved steadily during President Reagan's
term although ``of course there are still some problems between
us.''
   Shultz held closed-door talks with Li and Zhao. It was his
second day in Beijing. On Saturday he flies to Seoul, South Korea,
the seventh stop on a nine-country trip through Asia and the
Pacific.
   Discussions here focused largely on missile sales and the Khmer
Rouge, the Chinese-backed Cambodian guerrillas who some fear may
muscle their way back into power if Vietnam pulls its troops out of
Cambodia.
   The Khmer Rouge massacred hundreds of thousands of Cambodians
after it took power in 1975. Vietnam ousted them when it invaded in
1978.
   Shultz said the United States and China have ``a very broad
agreement as to certain aspects of that situation,'' including
``rather similar views'' on stopping a Khmer Rouge return to power.
China officially supports a three-party Cambodian opposition
coalition that includes the Khmer Rouge.
   U.S. sources said Foreign Minister Qian Qichen told Shultz on
Thursday that senior Khmer Rouge leaders may retire.
   Shultz said both countries are pressing for a total withdrawal
of Vietnamese troops and both view non-Communist Prince Norodom
Sihanouk as the central figure in a future Cambodian government.
Sihanouk abruptly resigned this week as head of the anti-Vietnamese
coalition.
   Sihanouk and several others proposed a peacekeeping force to
ensure a cease-fire, the peaceful formation of a government and
free elections in Cambodia.
   Vietnam pledged to remove all its troops, currently estimated at
120,000 by U.S. sources, by 1990. This has sparked fears that the
Khmer Rouge would shoulder aside their two, less powerful
non-communist allies in the anti-Vietnamese coalition and seize
power once Hanoi's forces have left.
</TEXT>
