<1ST_LINE>r i PM-CambodiaTalks     07-15 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cambodia Talks,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Will Attend Talks On Cambodian Future</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam has confirmed it will attend
peace talks on Cambodia this month, official Vietnamese radio said
today.
   There had been doubts that Vietnam would participate in the
talks scheduled for July 25 in Bogor, Indonesia. The talks will be
the first among all the warring parties.
   Vietnam had accused the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
of trying to turn the talks into direct negotiations between
Vietnam and guerrilla groups fighting its occupation of Cambodia.
   Vietnam's foreign minister, Nguyen Co Thach, said Tuesday his
country would attend only if ASEAN confirmed it didn't change the
rules of the informal talks.
   Voice of Vietnam radio said Indonesia's Foreign Minister, Ali
Alatas, acting on behalf of ASEAN, asked Vietnam's ambassador to
Jakarta to convey to Thach assurances that ASEAN would respect
rules agreed upon in a July 29, 1987 communique signed by Vietnam
and Indonesia.
   The meeting between Alatas and the Vietnamese ambassador, Tran
Huy Chuong, took place in Jakarta on Tuesday, said the broadcast.
The report was monitored in Bangkok.
   The broadcast said Alatas gave assurances that ``the ASEAN
countries respect the joint Vietnam-Indonesia communique ... and
that ASEAN countries have no intention to turn this meeting into a
talk between Vietnam and the Kampuchean (Cambodian) factions.''
   Vietnam wants the talks held in two stages, with the Cambodians
discussing ``internal problems'' in the first stage and Vietnam
joining in a second stage to discuss ``international aspects'' of
the conflict.
   The three guerrilla groups and the Vietnamese-installed People's
Republic of Kampuchea are to attend the first stage. Vietnam, its
close communist ally Laos, and ASEAN countries are to attend the
second stage.
   The guerrillas are grouped in a coalition and include the
communist Khmer Rouge and the non-communist forces of former
Cambodian leaders Prince Norodom Sihanouk and Son Sann.
</TEXT>
