<DOCNO> AP880715-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1026EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HomelessRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0516 07-15 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Homeless Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0516,0715</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homeless March, Occupy Houses in Nationwide Demonstrations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to UPDATE number of arrests to 78; SUBS 9th graf,
`Later Thursday ...' with two grafs to UPDATE arrests in Washington
and Florida.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Homeless people and their advocates occupied houses, pitched
tent cities and marched through streets demanding ``Housing Now''
as they sought to rally support across the nation. At least 78
people were arrested.
   ``We've made a strong statement that homeless people are going
to get off their knees and fight for their rights,'' said Brian
Flagg, head of the Southern Arizona Coalition for the Homeless,
minutes before he and 10 others were arrested Thursday while
occupying a vacant townhouse in Tucson, Ariz.
   Voter registration drives also were a part of Homeless Action
Day, a protest that organizers said involved at least 60 cities
nationwide.
   ``I'm not really all that far out of the mud, but I can still
see a little bit better than some of these people,'' said Ronald
Dized, a Nashville, Tenn., construction worker who said he used to
be homeless. ``I'd be less than I am if I didn't support this. I've
been through it; I know what it's like to want a home.''
   In Boston, two policemen and a demonstrator were injured in a
fight that erupted after demonstrators tried to occupy a boarded-up
Boston Redevelopment Authority building.
   Some of the 75 people who marched on behalf of the homeless used
crowbars to pry boards off the building, and when police tried to
stop them, they swung the boards at the officers, police spokesman
Thomas F. Santry said.
   Eighteen people were arrested, including one who was charged
with disorderly conduct and possession of a dangerous weapon. Three
others were charged with assault and battery on a police officer.
   Thirty-seven people were arrested when they blocked traffic near
the Capitol in Washington, D.C., including Mitch Snyder, leader of
the Community for Creative Non-Violence, which organized the
protests.
   Later Thursday, Wayne Vorhees, a volunteer with Snyder's group,
climbed a 767-foot broadcast tower in Washington, unfurling a
banner reading ``Housing Now'' and vowing to remain until the
government expands housing opportunities for the poor. Two
companions were arrested and charged with unlawful entry. Vorhees
was coaxed down by police early today and charged with the same
offense.
   Seven people were arrested on trespass charges in St.
Petersburg, Fla., during an attempt to clean and convert a
boarded-up, city-owned house into a shelter for women and children.
Some 100 people had gathered at one of more than 400 houses
purchased by the city on property to be donated to the University
of South Florida.
   Three people were arrested in Columbus, Ohio, on criminal
trespassing charges after an unsuccessful attempt by about 20
homeless people and activists to take over an abandoned building,
police said.
   Speakers at a rally outside The Omni in Atlanta, site of the
Democratic National Convention, said federal support for the
homeless has waned during the Reagan administration, but they said
Democrats share the blame.
   ``Though it's easy to blame the Republicans, the Democrats are
just as responsible for the situation that exists,'' said Keith
Summa of the National Coalition for the Homeless in Atlanta.
   In Philadelphia, the homeless occupied 13 empty government-owned
homes, demanding ownership of the houses and federal money to
rehabilitate them.
   Fifty homeless people and supporters in Nashville, Tenn.,
marched in 90-degree weather, carrying signs bearing such messages
as ``Street people are people.''
   New Jersey's homeless joined their counterparts nationwide by
erecting tent cities and filing a lawsuit against Newark's Housing
Authority, accusing it of demolishing low-income units without
replacing them, contrary to federal law.
   About 100 people demonstrated at Newark City Hall in support of
the class-action lawsuit filed Thursday in state Superior Court,
said David S. Burgess, a leader of the Newark Coalition for
Low-Income Housing.
   Housing Authority Executive Director Milton Buck denied Burgess'
charges and said the authority would fight the lawsuit.
   In Albuquerque, N.M., seven homeless people and 45 supporters
rallied at a park Thursday night, then marched two blocks carrying
signs such as ``Homeless, not helpless,'' and occupied an abandoned
city-owned house. There were no arrests.
</TEXT>
