<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Volkswagen     07-15 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Volkswagen,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last North American Volkswagen Rolls Off Line</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW STANTON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last Volkswagen made in North
America has rolled off the assembly line, but it's not for sale.
   ``The car will remain with the company. It will be a permanent
fixture at Volkswagen,'' said Thomas McDonald, spokesman for
Volkswagen of America Inc., the West German automaker's U.S.
subsidiary.
   The white, two-door 1989 Golf model was completed Thursday
afternoon at the plant, the first foreign-owned automobile assembly
plant in the United States.
   Its final resting place has yet to be determined, McDonald said,
but officials are considering a corporate museum in Wolfsburg, West
Germany, which has about 100 cars.
   There was no fanfare as the car, the 1,197,411th vehicle built
at the plant, rolled off the production line. Photographers and TV
cameras were not allowed to record the event.
   The plant, which produced its first car in 1978, is about 35
miles southeast of Pittsburgh.
   Dogged by faltering sales of its American-built cars, Volkswagen
announced in November it would cut its losses by serving the U.S.
market with vehicles built in West Germany, Mexico and Brazil.
   About 2,500 people eventually will lose their jobs because of
the shutdown.
</TEXT>
