<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0574,0735</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Economic Sanctions Reported in Armenian Enclave; Tass Blames
Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs with Tass blaming food shortage on strike.
Picks up 4th pvs, `The legislature...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities in Azerbaijan are preventing vehicles
carrying foodstuffs from reaching a breakaway region of their
republic and have imposed an economic blockade on the mostly
Armenian area, a local journalist said today.
   The official Tass news agency blamed the supply problems on a
strike in the disputed region, Nagorno-Karabakh. It said more than
130 railway cars loaded with supplies were sitting at the train
station in Stepenakert, the region's main city. More than 300
containers with foodstuffs have not been unloaded, Tass said.
   The journalist from the state broadcasting authority said an
airliner was forced to turn back to neighboring Armenia on Thursday
after Azerbaijani authorities refused to let it land in
Nagorno-Karabakh.
   ``There are no more fruits or vegetables in our shops,'' the
journalist said in a telephone interview from Stepanakert. ``We
have almost no economic ties now with Azerbaijan.''
   The legislature of Nagorno-Karabakh, an enclave the size of
Delaware whose 160,000 inhabitants are mostly Armenian, voted
Tuesday to secede and join Armenia. The Azerbaijani government
called the vote illegal and declared it void.
   ``We are under a virtual economic blockade,'' said the
journalist, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``The Azerbaijanis
are trying to morally kill our movement, to strike down our just
demands.''
   For the past two months, Nagorno-Karabakh has been disrupted by
strikes by ethnic Armenians who want to be united with the Armenian
republic. Armenia followed suit with strikes on July 4 demanding
the annexation.
   The official Tass news agency reported that the situation in
Stepanakert remained tense. A general strike in the city continued.
   The journalist said none of the city's 20 factories was working
and that bus service between Stepanakert and the Armenian cities of
Kirovakan and Kafan was suspended.
   Buses to Yerevan, however, were setting out every other day with
an escort of police brought in from the Stavropol region of
southern Russia, he said.
   On Thursday, an Aeroflot airliner en route from Yerevan to
Stepanakert was forced to turn back after Azerbaijani authorities
refused to let it land in Stepanakert, the journalist said. The
airliner touched down in the Armenian city of Goris, and passengers
returned to Yerevan by bus, he said.
   The journalist said ``several thousand'' troops were patrolling
Nagorno-Karabakh today but that the area was quiet.
   A resident of Stepanakert said Thursday the ethnic dispute had
taken a heavy toll. ``Our situation is very bad because the strike
is continuing. No one is working,'' said the woman, who hung up the
phone before giving her name.
   She said Nagorno-Karabakh residents had to rely on food produced
locally. ``We aren't receiving food from Azerbaijan or Armenia,''
she said, but ``we get some potatoes from the Stepanakert area.''
   Activists said more than 150,000 people held a rally Thursday in
Yerevan urging Armenia's 10 deputies to the Soviet parliament to
press for annexation of Nagorno-Karabakh.
   About three-fourths of the enclave's residents are ethnic
Armenians, most of them Christians, but the region was assigned to
predominately Moslem Azerbaijan in 1923.
   Armenians believe the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the
highest legislative body in the Soviet government, will meet Monday
to consider the Nagorno-Karabakh question.
   In Moscow on Thursday, Foreign Ministry spokesman Vadim P.
Perfilyev said such a meeting was likely but that he didn't know
when it would occur.
   Khovik Vasilyan, an Armenian activist, said by telephone from
Yerevan today that most of the Armenian capital's factories were
still strikebound but that transport was functioning normally in
the city of 1.1 million people.
   He said another rally in Yerevan to press Armenian demands for
annexation was planned Saturday.
   Pravda, the Communist Party daily, said Thursday the work
stoppage in Armenia had cost $65 million in lost production and
that $29 million worth of construction had not been completed.
   Thirty-two people were killed in ethnic riots in February at
Sumgait, Azerbaijan, 26 of them Armenians.
   Tass said that about 20,000 Azerbajanis living in Armenia had
fled to Azerbaijan and that as of Wednesday, 7,265 Armenians who
once lived in Sumgait and other Azerbaijan cities had returned to
Armenia.
</TEXT>
