<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PanamaCanal     07-15 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama Canal,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official: U.S. Will Operate Canal Whether Panama Helps Or Not</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will carry out its
responsibility of operating the Panama Canal ``with or without the
participation of Panama,'' says the chairman of the board of the
Panama Canal Commission.
   The four Panamanian members of the nine-member bi-national board
boycotted the panel's quarterly two-day meeting, which concluded
Thursday in Savannah.
   ``The Panamanian government attempted to stop our meeting,''
chairman William Gianelli said.
   In response to the boycott, the U.S. board members voted
Wednesday not to hold any meetings in Panama until the political
unrest in that country settles down.
   The United States is seeking the ouster of Panamanian leader
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, who is under indictment on drug
charges in Florida.
   The board also approved a $500 million budget for the upcoming
year, a slight increase from the previous year, Gianelli said. The
budget now goes to the federal Office of Management and Budget for
approval.
   Panamanian Foreign Minister Jorge Ritter said earlier this month
that Panamanian representatives will not attend any meetings of the
board until ``the United States normalizes relations with Panama''
and recognizes nominees of the Noriega government.
   The U.S. president appoints the board members, including the
Panamanians, who are nominated by the Panamanian government.
   Noriega also was upset when the canal board canceled a meeting
scheduled for last April in Panama, Gianelli said.
   Gianelli said Panama's boycott of the meetings and the country's
interference in the operation of the canal are diminishing hopes
for a smooth transition to Panamanian ownership at the end of the
century.
   Panama is interfering by not allowing Panamanian canal
administrative staff members to attend the meeting and by
forbidding Panamanian staff to travel to the United States to learn
how to run the canal, Gianelli said.
   Panama has said it will not recognize any action taken by the
canal board members here.
   But Gianelli said any decisions taken by the board without the
votes of the Panamanian directors will be binding on the canal
operation because the commission is a U.S. government agency.
</TEXT>
