<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     07-15 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissident Writers Guild Members Charge Unfair Labor Practices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident scriptwriters have filed a complaint
charging that the striking Writers Guild of America is unlawfully
preventing members from leaving the union and returning to work.
   The complaint filed Thursday by the Writers Coalition asks the
National Labor Relations Board to declare that the guild contract
illegally restricts a writer's ability to resign from it during a
strike.
   If the NLRB rules favorably, some writers may break ranks from
the guild and resume work, according to Writers Coalition spokesman
Lionel Chetwynd.
   Guild spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden said the union will fight the
action. ``We are willing to take a case as far as necessary in the
legal system to have our rules declared legal and enforceable,''
she said.
   The WGA has been on strike against the Alliance of Motion
Picture and Television Producers since March 7 over creative
control and residual payments from reruns.
   The walkout by the 9,000 film and TV writers has resulted in
sweeping layoffs throughout the entertainment industry.
   The labor board will rule on the complaint within 30 days, said
Sidney Rosen, NLRB assistant regional director.
   Also Thursday, NBC announced that ``Magical World of Disney''
was the latest casualty of the strike. It will be pulled from the
fall schedule and replaced with a remake of ``The Hardy Boys,''
which ran on ABC in the late 1970s.
</TEXT>
