<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ConventionProtests     07-15 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Convention Protests,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to fix header</HEAD>
<HEAD>Court Sides With City In Dispute Over Convention Marches</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court today sided with the city
of Atlanta in a dispute with demonstrators who wanted to march on a
street adjacent to the Democratic National Convention site.
   Alternative '88, a coalition of protest groups planning to
demonstrate during the convention next week, went to court after
the city refused to allow parades on Marietta Street adjacent to
the convention site.
   U.S. District Judge Orinda Evans ruled last week that the city
has a significant government interest in guaranteeing delegates'
access to the convention and therefore was justified in barring
parades outside the Omni Hotel and the Georgia World Congress
Center.
   The coalition appealed to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, arguing that ``if traffic problems can be a compelling
reason (for limiting demonstrations), then in fact the sidewalks
and streets are not held in trust for the use of the public.''
   The appeals court today upheld the lower court's ruling, noting
the city had given permission for demonstrators to march within one
block of the convention site.
   ``The visibility of the parade from the actual convention site
is not significantly diminished'' by holding it a block away, the
court said.
</TEXT>
