<HEAD>Davis Enters Chicago Mayoral Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alderman Danny K. Davis has become the first
candidate to announce he will challenge acting Mayor Eugene Sawyer
in a special mayoral election prompted by the November death of
Harold Washington.
   Davis made the announcement Thursday, declaring the city ``on
the brink of disaster'' and ``leaderless.''
   Two other aldermen, Timothy Evans and Lawrence Bloom, have
indicated they also will challenge Sawyer for mayor. Other possible
candidates include Cook County State's Attorney Richard M. Daley
and U.S. Rep. William Lipinski.
   Sawyer was elected acting mayor by City Council shortly after
Washington's death from a heart attack. The special election Feb.
28 will choose someone to serve out the two years left in
Washington's term.
   Davis, 46, is a third-term alderman and Democratic committeeman
of his West Side ward.
