<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Nixon-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0448 07-15 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nixon-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0448,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Would Be Good Veep Pick For Bush, Nixon Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS new grafs 9-11 with more quotes on Bentsen-Dukakis;
picks up pvs graf 9: He accused</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Richard Nixon says if Michael
Dukakis can team up with someone as philosophically different from
him as Lloyd Bentsen, then George Bush should be able to patch up
any differences with Bob Dole.
   Nixon, in a memo to the Bush campaign, recommends Dole as a
running mate for Bush, the certain Republican nominee. However, the
former president also has kind words for Rep. Jack Kemp of New York
and California Gov. George Deukmejian, calling them ``strong
choices.''
   A copy of the note from the former president, who lives in
Saddle River, N.J., was made available to The Associated Press.
Nixon spokesman John Taylor confirmed Nixon wrote it for Bush's
``key strategists.''
   Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater said he received the memo late
Thursday.
   ``I'm reading it with great interest,'' Atwater said.
   ``If Dukakis and Bentsen _ with diametrically different views on
key issues _ can get together, Dole and Bush, who have no
significant philosophical differences, can get together, too,''
Nixon wrote, adding: ``Compared to the Democratic ticket, they
would look like Siamese twins.''
   Bush and Dole had some harsh exchanges back when they were
rivals for the Republican presidential nomination. But Nixon says
even if ``the pundits say'' Bush and Dole don't get along, the two
have a similar outlook and would make an effective team.
   By contrast, he wrote, differences between Dukakis, the governor
of Massachusetts, and Bentsen, the Texas senator, ``run to the
heart of virtually every major economic, social and foreign-policy
issue.''
   ``One is tall. The other is short,'' Nixon begins, ticking off
what he views as Dukakis-Bentsen differences. On such issues as tax
cuts, gun control and aid to the Nicaraguan rebels, the two are as
politically polarized as Dukakis and Bush, the former president
wrote.
   Nixon brushed aside comparisons between the Dukakis-Bentsen
ticket and the 1960 Massachusetts combination of John F. Kennedy
and Lyndon B. Johnson, which beat the ticket of Nixon and Henry
Cabot Lodge.
   ``They overlook a profound and obvious difference,'' Nixon said.
``Kennedy and Johnson were both mainstream Democrats.''
   He accused the Democrats of being ``willing to bury their
differences even if it means burying their principles'' in order to
have a shot at winning Texas, which he called ``the big enchilada.''
   Nixon described Bentsen as ``a mainstream Democrat'' but said
Dukakis ``definitely is not.''
   ``He is a card-carrying member of the McGovern-Mondale wing of
the Democratic Party,'' Nixon said of the Democratic nominee,
referring to former Vice President Walter Mondale and former Sen.
George McGovern of South Dakota, whom Nixon beat in 1972.
   The former president said the Dukakis camp was ``inept'' in
failing to reach Jackson and tell him of Bentsen's selection before
the word got out. But he said it will be in Jackson's own political
interests to stage a reconciliation with the Dukakis camp.
   In an aside, Nixon described Jackson as a ``fire-breathing
radical'' who has ``put on a three-piece suit and run for
president.''
</TEXT>
