<1ST_LINE>r a PM-No-JokeBandit     07-15 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-No-Joke Bandit,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Wanted In `No Joke Bandit' Bank Holdups Turns Self In</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENA PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man claiming to be the ``No Joke
Bandit'' wanted in 35 bank holdups that netted $70,000 turned
himself in to police, the FBI said. The man told reporters a drug
habit drove him to steal.
   Russell Eugene Gadd, 25, walked into a police station Thursday
and identified himself as the man sought in the seven-month string
of robberies in which tellers were given notes saying, ``This is no
joke,'' said FBI spokesman Fred Reagan.
   Witnesses said the robber often reached for his waistband as if
he were armed, but no weapon was ever seen, Reagan said.
   Gadd said he turned himself in to ease pressure on his family
and friends by extensive news coverage of the robberies in southern
California, Reagan said.
   ``I had a bad drug habit and I just couldn't stop,'' Gadd told
KNBC-TV. ``I know I'm going to go to jail. I didn't want to keep
running, so I turned myself in.''
   If convicted, Gadd faces a maximum of 20 years in prison and a
$5,000 fine for each count.
</TEXT>
