<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Airliner's Fuel,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Braniff Flight Returns To Airport With Fuel Leaking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Braniff Airways jet returned to the
airport shortly after takeoff with fuel spewing from a wing tank,
passengers and airport officials said.
   There was no smoke or fire, and no one aboard the Boeing 727 en
route to Chicago was injured, said Carolyn Fennell, spokeswoman for
Orlando International Airport.
   Nancy Weston, Braniff administrative assistant for maintenance,
said today the airline had no comment on the incident.
   A passenger, Lana Perkins, reported that the pilot came out of
the cockpit after other passengers reported fuel gushing from the
right wing about 15 minutes after takeoff late Thursday.
   ``Extinguish your cigarettes. Somebody forgot to put a cap on
the fuel tank. We've got to go back down,'' Mrs. Perkins quoted the
pilot as saying.
   ``People were angry. People were scared,'' added Mrs. Perkins,
32, of Fort Myers.
</TEXT>
