<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1151EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DestroyerSlaying     07-15 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Destroyer Slaying,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sailor Sentenced To Life In Payroll Officer's Killing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sailor convicted of
murdering and robbing a payroll officer aboard a U.S. destroyer was
spared the death penalty and given life imprisonment after
proclaiming his innocence.
   Petty Officer 1st Class Ruben Colon was sentenced Thursday by a
five-member court-martial panel. He was convicted Wednesday of
killing Lt. j.g. Ratish Prasad aboard the USS Hancock at dock here
March 15 and stealing $94,000 from the ship's safe.
   Colon, who had a 14-year military career as a Marine military
policeman and Navy electronic warfare technician, faced the death
penalty because he was found guilty of murder while committing a
robbery.
   The Navy has not executed one of its members since 1849.
   The sentence came after 34-year-old Colon, who did not testify
at his four-day court-martial, read a statement urging panel
members to reconsider the verdict.
   ``There was no one more surprised at your findings than
myself,'' Colon said. ``I was surprised for the simple fact that I
didn't do it.''
   Colon, of Vega Baja, Puerto Rico, pointed out loose ends in the
investigation such as several other suspects who failed polygraph
examinations when questioned about the killing and theft.
   Colon was charged with taking more than $94,000 and 2,575 blank
U.S. Treasury checks. He was arrested April 12 after investigators
found more than $87,000 and the checks in a safe-deposit box rented
in his name.
   ``If you are all convinced Petty Officer Colon is the
perpetrator, death is not appropriate,'' defense attorney Lt.
Matthew Michels argued. ``Make Petty Officer Colon live with it the
rest of his natural life. Make him live with the horror and the
responsibility.''
</TEXT>
