<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Congress-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0430 07-15 0686</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0430,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Renewed Military Aid Seems Possible With Resolutions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with Reagan statement; picks up 2nd graf pvs,
The House.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan today applauded overwhelming
House and Senate votes condemning Sandinista leaders for human
rights abuses and urged Congress to approve swiftly further aid for
Nicaragua's Contra rebels.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, speaking for the
president, said Reagan ``is pleased with the overwhelming,
bipartisan votes'' on the issue.
   ``These votes send the message to the Sandinistas that the
United States is firmly committed to the achievement of freedom and
democracy in Nicaragua,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``The Sandinistas' conduct makes clear that they will not
institute democratic reform and cease their threats to the security
of Central America unless effectively pressured and persuaded to do
so,'' the spokesman said.
   ``To achieve democracy in Nicaragua and security for all of
Central America clearly requires a viable and effective Nicaraguan
Democratic Resistance,'' he said.
   ``When the Congress returns, the president hopes they will move
swifly to enact legislation currently being formulated in the
Senate for further aid to the resistance,'' Fitzwater said.
   The House voted 385-18 on Thursday to condemn Nicaragua's
leftist Sandinista government for ``brutal suppression of basic
human rights.'' It urged the democracies of Central America to meet
to assess the situation.
   The House action followed closely on the 91-4 roll call by which
the Senate on Wednesday night adopted a stronger resolution warning
that military aid to the Contras could be approved if the
Sandinista government continues to frustrate democratic reforms and
does not end human rights abuses.
   Both resolutions condemn the Sandinistas for breaking up a
recent peaceful demonstration, jailing more than 40 people,
including opposition leaders, closing down the newspaper La Prensa
and the Catholic radio station and expelling U.S. Ambassador
Richard Melton and eight other American diplomats.
   Military aid was ended last February, but a $47.1 million aid
package containing $20 million for military purposes was introduced
late Wednesday in the Senate by Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan.
   The White House on Thursday expressed support for the combined
humanitarian and military aid, which would last through next March.
   Under the measure, aid to the Contras would be authorized only
after the president certifies that it is necessary and after both
houses of Congress approve it.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Thursday that the
White House was working with Congress on a new Contra aid bill and
said Dole has been ``very helpful'' in this effort.
   When Reagan was asked Wednesday whether he was supporting
efforts o get a new Contra aid package through Congress, he
responded, ``You bet I am.''
   Advocates of ending military assistance contended the step would
encourage the Sandinistas and Contras to negotiate seriously and to
cooperate in the Central American peace process fostered by Costa
Rican President Oscar Arias.
   American humanitarian assistance to the Contra forces has
continued.
   Until the Sandinista crackdown last weekend there had appeared
to be virtually no prospect that military aid to the Contras would
be restored.
   The House appeared divided on the issue on Thursday.
   ``I expect this body to take stronger action later,'' said Rep.
Robert J. Lagomarsino, R-Calif, echoing many of his colleagues.
   ``This resolution contains strong words; but it is just that _
strong words,'' he said. ``There are no teeth in this resolution.''
   But Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., also speaking for many of his
colleagues, said the United States should do nothing to fuel
further fighting in Central America.
   Bonior said that while it is important to ``condemn any
violations of the principle of democracy,'' he believes there is
still life in the peace process.
   ``The basis for progress, I believe, still remains,'' he said.
   In Senate testimony, Ambassador Melton said he believes
congressional resolutions do little to sway the Sandinistas.
   Melton said he does think ``the Sandinistas are impressed with
any evidence of resoluteness on the part of the Congress and
evidence of bipartisan resolve.''
   But he added, ``I think the Sandinistas are impressed more by
actions than by words.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
