<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Space     07-15 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Space,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Democrats Ask Dukakis To Commit To Strong US Space Program</HEAD>
<HEAD>AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty-four House Democrats are asking Gov.
Michael Dukakis to commit himself to a strong United States space
program to encourage young people to pursue science and engineering
careers.
   ``The present administration has allowed our space program to
lose direction and founder,'' said a letter handed to Dukakis on
Wednesday by Rep. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, whose district includes
NASA's Lewis Research Center.
   She had originated the letter and circulated it among the others
for their signature.
   ``We as Democrats believe that our party must pick up the fallen
torch of space exploration and carry it high,'' it said. ``The next
president will have the choice of leading America to a permanent
presence in space or allowing other, more ambitious countries to
surge ahead.''
   The letter said that a successful space program needs a
well-educated workforce but that young Americans aren't pursuing
the necessary studies.
   ``More than half of all graduate degrees earned in science and
engineering at American institutions go to foreign nationals,'' it
added. ``A strong civilian space program provides incentives for
young people to pursue a career in science and or engineering and
is necessary to ensuring a sturdy American technology base.''
</TEXT>
