<1ST_LINE>u a PM-WomanBishop 1stLd-Writethru a0557 07-15 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Woman Bishop, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0557,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede BUCKHANNON, W.Va.</HEAD>
<HEAD>United Methodist Church Conferences Elect Two Women Bishops</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with woman bishop named in North Central
conference as well as Northeast, black bishop named in Southeast.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two women have been elected bishops of the United Methodist
Church, the fourth and fifth women to hold that position in the
church's 20-year history.
   Delegates of the North Central Jurisdictional Conference meeting
in De Kalb, Ill., on Thursday selected the Rev. Sharon Brown
Christopher, 43, to serve as bishop for the 9.1 million-member
church, the second-largest Protestant denomination.
   Christopher was elected on the 28th ballot by 339 votes.
   ``I am touched in the deepest of ways by the confidence my
Wisconsin colleagues have placed in me, a confidence in the
possibility of my giving leadership through the episcopacy,''
Christopher said.
   Her election came one day after delegates to a United Methodist
Northeast Jurisdictional Conference elected the Rev. Susan Morrison
a bishop in a surprise move.
   Morrison's name was forwarded as a candidate in the sixth round
of balloting Wednesday at the Northeast Jurisdictional Conference
in Buckhannon, W.Va. She won on the 18th ballot, receiving 255 of
392 votes.
   Christopher was assigned to the church's Minnesota district, one
of the jurisdiction's 10 episcopal areas. Morrison was assigned to
the Philadelphia area.
   Judith Craig of Detroit is the only other active female United
Methodist bishop. Leontine Kelly of San Francisco, who retired in
1984, and the late Marjorie Matthews of Wisconsin were the other
women bishops.
   Morrison said was surprised at her election because her name was
added to the ballot without her knowledge.
   ``I'm really kind of stunned,'' said Morrison, council director
of the church's Baltimore conference. ``Nobody approached me to ask
me.''
   The Northeast and North-central conferences were among five
regional conferences the United Methodist Church held this week.
   The Southeast Jurisdictional Conference elected only the second
black bishop in its 48-year history late Wednesday. Joseph Bethea,
55, district superintendent of the North Carolina Conference, was
elected on the 12th ballot.
   ``I see me serving as a kind of model for young people of all
races,'' he said Thursday.
   The United Methodist Church was formed in 1968 by the merger of
the Methodist Church and the Evangelical United Brethren Church.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
