<HEAD>Floods Kill 4 In Western Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rain in western Japan has killed at least
four people and left 11 missing as swollen waters flooded homes,
closed highways and disrupted local train service, police said
Friday.
   Regional police said on Thursday they recovered the bodies of
three family members who drowned when flooding waters washed their
car off a road near Toba, Mie prefecture, 205 miles southwest of
Tokyo along the Pacific coast.
   Police said they recovered another victim late Thursday who
drowned after his motorcyle was swept off a road in the same region
of Mie prefecture.
   Japan's Meteorological Agency said periodic downpours that began
early Thursday would continue in western and central Japan.
   The agency said early Friday that 3.4 inches of rain fell over a
one-hour period in the region of Tottori prefecture, 310 miles
southwest of Tokyo on the Japan Sea side, setting off minor land
slides.
