<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1231EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia     07-15 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strikers Leave Belgrade After Promise of Action</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IVAN STEFANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,500 striking workers from a
bankrupt food processing plant met with government officials in the
capital Friday and returned home after winning a promise of higher
pay.
   More than 5,000 of Agrokomerc's 8,500 workers went on strike
Thursday, demanding more pay in the latest labor unrest caused by
the government's economic austerity plan.
   About 1,500 of the workers rode on buses to Belgrade, where they
were met by hundreds of police officers who sealed off an area
around Parliament.
   Shouts of ``Let's March to Parliament!'' and ``We Are Not Moving
Anywhere!'' went up from the Agrokomerc workers as they pressed for
wage increases and more state investment in the company.
   The workers are receiving guaranteed minimum salaries of about
$50 monthly, ``which is not enough for survival,'' Fuad Pasalic,
the head of the company's trade union, was quoted by Belgrade radio
as telling government officials.
   ``Our children are hungry and have no clothes to wear,'' he said.
   After meeting Bosnian and federal leaders in Belgrade, the
Agrokomerc workers, who appeared tired and dejected, said they won
a promise of a raise to $70 a month. They then boarded the 25 buses
to take them back home.
   Agrokomerc is in the Bosnia town of Velika Kladusa, 250 miles
west of Belgrade. Some of the workers wore the traditional
headscarves and colorful oriental trouser-skirts of the area.
   On Thursday, truck drivers blocked all traffic in Velika
Kladusa, the Politika Ekspres newspaper said.
   Agrokomerc, once touted as a model Socialist enterprise, is
being sold off gradually to cover debts incurred after it
circulated about $1 billion worth of uncovered promissory notes.
   The financial scandal, Yugoslavia's biggest since World War II,
was uncovered in August. Only 8,500 of the company's 13,000
workforce are still on the payroll.
   Workers throughout Yugoslavia are experiencing hardship as the
government implements an austerity program designed to reduce 175
percent inflation and limit the $21 billion foreign debt.
   On July 6, thousands of workers from Yugoslavia's largest rubber
and shoe plant broke into the parliament building to press demands
for higher pay.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
