<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1231EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MiamiChief     07-15 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Miami Chief,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miami Police Chief Retires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police Chief Clarence Dickson announced his
retirement today after 3{ years at helm of an 1,100-member
department rocked by corruption and confronted by rising violence
against its officers.
   ``This was entirely my own idea,'' the department's first black
chief said at a news conference. ``I felt like the highlights of my
career I had already experienced.''
   Dickson, 54, who joined the force in 1960, became eligible for
retirement this year and said he simply decided to take it. He said
one of the highlights of his tenure was eliminating corruption
among Miami police.
   During his tenure, about 100 officers were convicted of crimes,
forced to resign or disciplined for offenses ranging from
participating in a deadly drug ripoff ring to personal drug use.
   In the same period, Miami police officers have been the target
of increasingly violent attacks, with three officers shot in the
line of duty this year, one fatally.
   Police have blamed the violence on rising drug trafficking and
drug use and easier access to guns in this racially mixed city of
370,000.
   City officials immediately announced that Dickson, whose
appointment was seen as a response to the bloody riots in Miami's
Liberty City section in 1980, would be replaced by Assistant Chief
Perry C. Anderson, who is also black.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
