<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1244EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lesotho-Snow     07-15 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lesotho-Snow,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Snowfalls Kill 10, Trap 50,000 in Lesotho</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy snowfalls have trapped
50,000 people in the mountains of Lesotho and many are without
food, firewood and proper clothing, the South African Broadcasting
Corp. said Friday.
   Ten people have been found dead in the past week, according to a
Radio Lesotho report monitored in South Africa.
   Nearly a dozen young boys who shepherd flocks in remote areas of
the mountains died in similar snowfalls in September, when the tiny
kingdom surrounded by South Africa appealed for blankets, rescue
equipment, fuel and food from the Pretoria government.
   A sick man who died before he could be taken to a hospital, and
three children who fell into a dam died in the Maluti mountains
earlier in the week.
   The bodies of three men and three children who died from
exposure in the Letseng-La-Terai area of the Mokhotlong district
were discovered Friday, Radio Lesotho said.
   Royal Air Force helicopters have flown over the Mokhotlong
district, where all roads have been closed by the snow. South
African vehicles have been brought in to scrape paths into the
mountain villages.
   ``Thousands of people have been cut off from the outside world
for a week and they have run out of food and firewood. Many people
have begun eating snow to stay alive,'' said Radio South Africa.
``In many places the children have no shoes, and only one blanket
to protect them from the cold.''
   It noted that when the snow begins to melt, conditions may
worsen, because access roads will be washed out, as they were last
year.
   The heaviest snowfalls in years also have cut off towns and
villages, disrupted road, telephone and electricity links in South
Africa's Natal and eastern Cape provinces.
   The main road from the central Johannesburg-Pretoria area to
Natal is closed, leaving thousands of motorists stranded, and about
100 hikers have been trapped in the Drakensberg Mountains in Natal,
Radio South Africa reported.
   It said the Karasberg Mountains in South-West Africa have
received the heaviest snowfall since 1965.
</TEXT>
