<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1315EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BRF--AdDispute     07-15 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Ad Dispute,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kansas City Bus System Reverses Ban On Nicaragua Ads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The metropolitan-area bus service has
reversed itself and agreed to carry a Quaker group's advertisement
saying ``Nicaragua is not our enemy.''
   The ad was to make its first appearance today on 18 buses of the
Kansas City Area Tranportation Authority.
   The American Friends Service Committee, a national Quaker
organization, asked the agency last fall to carry an ad that
pictured two Nicaraguan children and read: ``Nicaragua is not our
enemy. Let Nicaraguans live in peace.''
   The agency refused, citing its policy against controversial
advertising. It reversed itself after the Quaker group, with the
support of the American Civil Liberties Union, threatened to sue on
free speech grounds.
   Dick Davis, the authority's general manager, said the bus
service felt the case ``was not worth the litigation costs.''
</TEXT>
