<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1307EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Tsongas Bjt   07-15 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tsongas, Bjt,0693</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retransmitting to include Bjt designation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Paul Tsongas Is Alive and Well, Living As Former Senator in
Hometown</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOWELL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There is one well-known Democratic
politician of Greek ancestry from Massachusetts who is not seeking
the presidency and isn't even going to the Democratic convention in
Atlanta.
   ``I have no political ambitions, whatsoever,'' says former U.S.
Sen. Paul Tsongas, once hailed as a liberal maverick on Capitol
Hill. ``We're much happier now than when I was in office.''
   He has scaled down his aspirations since he disclosed that he
had cancer and left the Senate one month before his 43rd birthday.
   The last traces of cancer are gone, but he prefers the limelight
of this old mill town to the spotlight of Washington.
   Though no longer a senator, Tsongas still makes headlines in The
Sun, a 55,000-circulation daily that serves his hometown. It has
been reporting his doings ever since he sat on the Lowell City
Council in the late 1960s and right on through his election to the
U.S. House in 1974, first Democrat to win the district in about 90
years, and to the Senate in 1979.
   One recent edition landed on Tsongas' side porch carrying an
article about his tangle over the ouster of the Lowell school
superintendent.
   He also created a statewide stir recently when, as the head of a
study commission on the environment, he called for a building
moratorium on Cape Cod. The matter, which will be on the November
ballot, is still being hotly debated.
   Tsongas enjoys watching his friend, Gov. Michael Dukakis, reach
for the White House, in particular because the likely Democratic
presidential nominee expounds Tsongas' philosophy that the
Democrats' survival depends on integrating the needs of business.
   ``Liberals have to be concerned with economics. Democrats have
to be the friends of business. ... The major issue facing the
country is the sense of decline, that we're going to be some
latter-day Great Britain,'' he said.
   Although he once floated the idea of running for president, it's
enough for Tsongas to stump for his friend to know he isn't missing
a thing.
   In some ways he prefers wielding influence as an ex-senator.
   ``I'm really struck by how much respect there is for the office
of senator,'' he said. ``It is very special ... and you can use
that. How many 47-year-old former senators do you know?
   ``Certainly in people's dealings with me, they are much more
accepting of me now than when I was in office. I have no political
ambitions, so I'm less tainted. Also, there's the illness issue.''
   In September 1983 he was diagnosed as having non-Hodgkins
lymphoma, a relatively mild cancer of the lymph nodes that attacks
part of the immune system. Nearly four months later, in the middle
of his second run for the Senate, Tsongas decided it would be
better for everyone if he took his wife, Nikki, and their three
daughters home to Lowell.
   Since then he has undergone a bone marrow transplant and has
been declared cancer-free.
   Tsongas works for a prestigious Boston law firm, Foley Hoag &
Eliot, making deals and serving on corporate boards and taking pro
bono assignments.
   His latest battle, over his proposal that construction on the
Cape be halted until the peninsula gets control of development, has
led to abuse from builders and developers while filling his mailbox
with letters from Cape Codders telling him to stick with it.
   ``I know I'm doing well because my political enemies are angry
at me,'' he said, with glee, recalling the wrath of a roomful of
developers at a public hearing on the issue. ``Six hundred people
were shouting at me!''
   He shrugged. `I have nothing to fear, politically, and, with
what I've been through ...''
   ``The day I turn around and there's nobody behind me, is the day
I get out of it. The mail I get is so passionate, you cannot read
that mail and say: `I'm going to walk away.' ''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
