<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ShuttleCrewPatch     07-15 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle Crew Patch,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Space Shuttle Crew Insignia Honors Challenger Astronauts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drawing of a space shuttle lifting
off against a backdrop of a rainbow as a symbol of astronauts'
return to space is featured on the patch the crewmen will wear on
the second post-Challenger shuttle flight.
   A picture of the patch, sprinkled with seven stars to
commemorate the memory of the Challenger crew members, was released
Friday by the space agency.
   Around the border are the last names of the five astronauts who
will fly the mission: Commander Robert L. Gibson, pilot Guy S.
Gardner and mission specialists Jerry L. Ross, Richard M. Mullane
and William M. Shepherd.
   NASA said each crewman contributed to the design.
   Their flight aboard shuttle Atlantis is scheduled for November
and will carry a classified Defense Department payload.
   The crew patch for the first post-Challenger flight _ that of
Discovery in early September _ shows a stylized shuttle lifting off
and includes in the background a sun and the seven-starred Big
Dipper as a tribute to the seven astronauts who died in the
Challenger explosion Jan. 28, 1986.
</TEXT>
