<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ScienceMedalists 5thLd-Writethru a0636 07-15 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Science Medalists, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0636,610</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 9th graf pvs to CORRECT spelling of Goldstein</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saying that America's greatest resource ``is
the genius of our people,'' President Reagan today presented medals
for advances in science and technology to 30 individuals prominent
in research and industrial technology.
   In a brief ceremony at the Old Executive Office Building, Reagan
said that the most important activity that his administration can
do is ``knock down the barriers to progress.''
   ``America's greatest resource is not the land,'' said the
president. ``No, America's greatest resource is the genius of our
people.''
   Earlier, one of the winners, Joseph L. Goldstein of the
University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center in Dallas, said in
an interview that heart disease may be controlled within a
generation through a wider acceptance of healthier lifestyles and
the development of drugs now in the laboratory.
   Goldstein said he expects that people who are genetically
susceptible to heart disease eventually will be identified through
blood tests, and that the number of people killed by heart attack
will be reduced dramatically.
   ``We may control heart disease before we thoroughly understand
it,'' said Goldstein. He said he and other scientists now are
tracking down the precise genetic factors that lead to the
development of atherosclerosis, the major form of heart disease.
Goldstein said this could lead to a blood test that would enable
doctors to identify patients most at risk for heart attack long
before any heart disease has developed.
   Goldstein and Michael S. Brown, also of the University of Texas,
won the Nobel prize for discovery of the basic mechanism
controlling the formation of cholesterol, a major element in the
development of heart disease.
   Twenty of the medal recipients received the national medal of
science, an honor established by Congress in 1959 to recognize
achievements in physical, biological, mathematical, behavioral,
social or engineering sciences.
   In addition to Goldstein and Brown, those receiving the science
medal are William O. Baker of Bell Telephone Laboratories in Murray
Hill, N.J.; Konrad E. Bloch, Harvard University, Cambridge, Mass.;
D. Allan Bromley, Yale University, New Haven, Conn.; Paul Chu,
University of Houston, Houston; Stanley N. Cohen, Stanford
University, Stanford, Calif.; Elias J. Corey, Harvard; Daniel C.
Drucker, University of Florida, Gainesville, Fla.; Milton Friedman,
Stanford; Ralph E. Gomory, IBM, Armonk, N.Y.; Willis M. Hawkins,
Lockheed Corp., Calabasas, Calif.; Maurice R. Hilleman, Merck and
Co., West Point, Pa.; George W. Housner, California Institute of
Technology, Pasadena, Calif; Eric R. Kandel, Columbia University
and the New York State Psychiatric Institute, New York, N.Y.;
Joseph B. Keller, Stanford; Walter Kohn, University of California,
Santa Barbara; Norman F. Ramsey, Harvard; Jack Steinberger,
European Center for Nuclear Research, Geneva, Switzerland, and
Rosalyn S. Yalow, Mt. Sinai School of Medicine, New York, N.Y.
   Reagan is awarding the national medal of technology to 10
people. The winners are Edwin H. Land, founder of the Polaroid
Corp. and now president of the Rowland Institute for Science in
Cambridge; John L. Atwood, Rockwell International Corp., El
Segundo, Calif.; Arnold O. Beckman, Beckman Instruments, Irvine,
Calif.; Paul M. Cook, Raychem Corp., Menlo Park, Calif.; Richard H.
Dennard, IBM, Yorktown Heights, N.Y.; Harold E. Edgerton,
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Cambridge; Clarence L.
Johnson, Lockheed; David Packard, Hewlett-Packard Co., Palo Alto,
Calif.; Raymond Damadian, FONAR Corp., Melville, N.Y., and Paul C.
Lauterbur, University of Illinois at Urbana.
   The technology medal was created in 1980 by Congress to
recognize those who advance American technology and improved the
nation's economy, environment or social well-being.
   A White House spokesman said the medalists were nominated by
committees directed by the Department of Commerce. The names then
were referred to Reagan, who awards the medals and certificates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
