<1ST_LINE>r p AM-AndyYoung     07-15 0744</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Andy Young,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former King Aide Young Now Convention City Mayor and Booster</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He marched with King, won election as Georgia's
first black congressman since Reconstruction and later championed
human rights as U.S. ambassador to the United Nations.
   Now Andrew Young is Atlanta's mayor and chief booster, using the
Democratic National Convention as a hometown showcase for the sales
pitch he makes around the world.
   With 13,000 reporters in town or on the way, Young is scheduling
daily news conferences in contrast to his usual practice of
scheduling none.
   As a prominent black Democratic office-holder, he came under
early pressure to endorse Jesse Jackson. But he steered clear,
saying that as host mayor for the convention he shouldn't be taking
such stands.
   ``I'd like to see Atlanta have a worldwide reputation as a
market center,'' Young said in a recent interview. ``We've been
trying to find ways to create jobs and to wipe out some of the
problems of poverty in our city by actually attracting and
generating new wealth.''
   Young's emphasis on improving Atlanta with private investment
has won enough support from white business leaders to have him
thinking aloud about a run for governor next year on a platform of
economic development.
   But the mayor also bears some bruises from charges he has
forgotten the poor while courting the rich.
   ``I think he has been good for Atlanta as a whole, bringing in
business, but I don't think the low-income community looks at him
as being good for them,'' said Louise Watley, president of the
tenants' association in the Carver Homes housing project.
   Young said he was wounded when Ms. Watley invited him and the
news media to a tenants' meeting and then issued a scathing
``indictment'' of him, starting 90 minutes of accusations by
project residents that he had failed them.
   ``It really hurt because these are people who have always been
my close friends and supporters,'' he said. He also said his
administration has brought jobs to the area around Carver Homes and
money for improvements in the project itself.
   Young said the incident has changed his outlook on handling such
functions _ ``I'm not a sucker and I'm not going to make myself
available to get set up any more'' _ but not his emotions about
dealing with criticism from the poor.
   ``I grew up middle class, so from early childhood I had to deal
with the question of middle class guilt, and I found it not very
productive. So you have to maintain your sense of responsibility,
your sense of vision and hope, but not pay much attention to your
critics,'' said the 56-year-old mayor.
   Young, trained as a minister, was a top aide to Martin Luther
King Jr. during the civil rights movement of the 1960s. After
King's death, he won a congressional seat in an Atlanta district.
Then came his tenure as Jimmy Carter's U.N. ambassador, giving him
an international reputation.
   Since his election as mayor in 1981, he has circled the globe in
search of new business for Atlanta.
   He displays a hands-off approach to the day-to-day running of
the city.
   ``Basically my style is to get intelligent and dedicated people,
get them committed to a vision and in a certain direction and then
give them all the support I can,'' he said.
   Young himself has plenty of supporters.
   ``We were losing a lot of investment to the suburbs, and we've
seen a lot of investment come back into the city'' during Young's
administration, said Dan Sweat, who recently concluded 15 years as
president of Central Atlanta Progress, a downtown business group.
   The Atlanta skyline bristles with new development, and the mayor
can rattle off projects worth several billion dollars, still on the
drawing boards.
   ``It's beyond the comprehension of most of us,'' said Charles
Loudermilk, a businessman and lifelong Atlantan who usually votes
Republican but was an early supporter of Young.
   ``Andy Young has to get a tremendous amount of the credit
because all of us feel good about ourselves, our businesses and our
city, and frankly that was not true when Andy came in,'' said
Loudermilk.
   ``He has an ability to open any door in the world,'' he said.
``I was with him in France and we met with (President Francois)
Mitterand, the mayor and all of the ministers and bankers, and
(Young) is an absolute, absolute world hero.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
