<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugCzar     07-15 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Czar,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Martinez Appoints Metro-Dade Major As Drug Czar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Metro-Dade police major was appointed
Friday as the state's first anti-drug czar, a move Gov. Bob
Martinez hopes will bring Florida's drug problem into the open as a
first step toward recovery.
   Douglas Hughes, 43, will chair Martinez's Drug Policy Task Force
and coordinate drug-war efforts among local state and federal
agencies.
   ``This is not a study commission. This is a recommending,
implementing group,'' said Martinez. ``What this policy unit does
it takes the drug problem out of the closet. It used to be and
still is in many areas, `Let's not acknowledge it because it's bad
for tourism, it's bad for business.'''
   Hughes has been director of Metro-Dade's substance-abuse control
program since its inception in March 1987, coordinating
interagency, school and private-sector efforts against drugs.
Martinez chose him mainly for that experience.
   ``No agency can do it alone,'' said Hughes. ``What you're seeing
much more than ever before, is law enforcement stepping forward ...
and saying we are aware that law enforcement alone cannot solve the
problem. That has brought agencies together.''
   Hughes has 22 years of experience in police work. He was a
member of the New York Police Department from 1964-71, and while a
member of the Metro-Dade force has been district manager for Dade's
Liberty City, an area torn by riots, drugs and poor economy.
   He will remain a member of the Metro-Dade force but will be on
loan to the state to protect his pension, said Martinez. He will
continue to collect a salary of $70,300.
   Brian Ballard, director of operations in the govenor's office,
said $125,000 has been earmarked for the new office. Also, three
departments each will assign one person to Hughes' office.
</TEXT>
