<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1332EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MarineRunner     07-15 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marine Runner,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marine With One-Lung Running Up Mount Whitney</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONE PINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Marine with one lung today neared the
final leg of a 146-mile run from scorching Death Valley, the lowest
point in the contiguous 48 states, to the summit of Mount Whitney,
the highest point.
   Maj. John Bates, 42, began his grueling trek at 8 p.m.
Wednesday. He was expected to reach the end of the paved road and
the start of the trail to 14,464-foot Mount Whitney before noon,
forest Ranger Clark Trowell said.
   Bates faced a 10.3-mile hike up a well-worn but extremely steep
path to the summit. The steepest part of the trail is between
12,000 and 13,700 feet, where even the most experienced hiker
struggles with the thin air.
   The Marine ate salty foods, drank large quantities of water and
took caffeine pills to stay awake but was suffering from cramps and
nausea. Bates, who lost a lung to a bullet in Vietnam in 1966, said
the run was for fun and to inspire other disabled veterans.
   He planned to run nonstop, going from 282 feet below sea level
to Mount Whitney's summit, in hopes of shaving five hours off the
record of 45 hours, 15 minutes.
   He appeared likely to break his personal best time: 63 hours, 12
minutes in 1986. He took two eight-hour sleep breaks during that
run.
   As his figure, blurred by heat waves, bobbed down the road
Thursday, his wife, Stephanie, followed in an air-conditioned
mobile home.
   ``I have been thinking about just yanking him into the car and
driving home,'' she said. She begged her husband to eat more tuna
sandwiches. ``They're a miracle cure _ lots of salt.''
   His run came during the hottest season for Death Valley, with
the daytime air temperature often reaching 120 degrees and the sand
200 degrees, said Death Valley Acting Chief Ranger Russell March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880715-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1335EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson-1972Bjt     07-15 0816</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-1972 Bjt,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson's '88 Delegates Recall '72 Convention Fight With Daley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What a difference 16 years can make. Jesse
Jackson, the solo remaining also-ran in the field of candidates for
the Democratic presidential nomination, had to wage a bitter fight
just to win a seat on the Democratic convention floor in Miami in
1972.
   Nancy Jefferson remembers. One of Jackson's allies at that time
_ just as she is one of his delegates this time _ she was so
pleased with the rebels' victory at that steamy convention that she
took a plunge into a swimming pool with her clothes on.
   ``It was that kind of excitement,'' she says. ``It was a great
day.''
   The challenging bloc of four dozen renegade delegates faced
contempt of court and jail for pursuing their fight.
   Even after they won, it took a 9-0 decision by the U.S. Supreme
Court to nail down the victory. And the event may have played a
role in the demise of the political operation led by then-Chicago
Mayor Richard J. Daley, one of the most powerful big city political
machines in the country.
   Mrs. Jefferson, 64, chief executive officer of the Midwest
Community Council, a West Side group in Chicago, is headed to the
convention in Atlanta with at least four other Illinois delegates
who were with Jackson and then-alderman William Singer in the rebel
group in Miami.
   Here's how it happened:
   A week before the 1972 convention, the party's credentials
committee, which leaned toward George McGovern, granted the
Singer-Jackson delegates convention seats on a 71-61 vote. That
decision was challenged on the first day of the convention, a
session which lasted well into the next morning.
   The challenge failed in a floor vote. The memory still rankles
Thomas Lyons, one of the ousted Daley delegates.
   ``It was one of the most monstrous things I've ever seen,'' said
Lyons, 57, a former state senator. He said he and other delegates
received thousands of votes, ``and we were replaced by ... people
who met in somebody's living room. ... It was a theft.''
   McGovern, the Democratic presidential nominee in 1972, had
helped set the stage for the spectacle of keeping Daley from the
convention floor.
   After the tumultuous 1968 Democratic National Convention in
Chicago, where anti-war demonstrators rocked the city and clashed
with Daley's city police force, McGovern chaired a commission that
rewrote party rules to make room for more minorities, women and
young people.
   ``The Cook County Democratic Committee, under Daley's
leadership, flagrantly violated every aspect of the rules,'' said
Saul Mendelson of Chicago, a Jackson delegate this year who was an
alternate with the 1972 rebels.
   The renegades held their own caucuses so they could offer an
alternative.
   The anti-machine Democrats in the city knew that a simple
protest would result in either a meaningless rebuke to the Daley
forces on the convention floor, or expulsion of the 59 Daley
people, leaving no representation for Chicago.
   Lyons saw the quickly called meetings as a political charade.
Singer agrees that his delegates, chosen in church basements and
living rooms, were not picked in orthodox ways. But ``I don't think
there was anyone in Chicago who didn't know what was going on,'' he
said.
   After the credentials committee action, Daley forces went to
court, and Cook County Circuit Judge Daniel A. Covelli prohibited
the Singer-Jackson delegates from taking their convention seats. He
threatened to jail leaders of the group if they disobeyed.
   Still, the rebels went to the convention, and faced a challenge
on the floor.
   That vote ``shaped up as the most dramatic moment of the 1972
convention,'' according to ``Clout: Mayor Daley and his City,'' a
1975 book by Chicago reporter and commentator Len O'Connor. ``The
power of the old guard was under challenge.''
   Mendelson said Daley, who was keeping in touch with the
delegation from his vacation home in Michigan, would not agree to
offers to split the delegate seats or take over leadership of the
renegades himself.
   When the floor vote was taken, the Singer-Jackson group kept
their seats.
   Critics said the Chicago rift would hurt McGovern's chances.
Maybe they did, but he lost 49 states, including Illinois, to GOP
incumbent Richard Nixon.
   Covelli's contempt-of-court order was stayed pending an appeal.
The Illinois Supreme Court later refused to hear the case, but the
U.S. Supreme Court ruled 9-0 for the Singer-Jackson group. The high
court said that a political party has the right to make and enforce
its own rules. That ended the threat of jail.
   Singer isn't convinced that the 1972 events led to the downfall
of Daley's machine. But Mrs. Jefferson thinks it was one step on
the path of opening political power in the Windy City to those who
had been shut out.
   ``I think it sort of ... changed the whole politics of
Chicago,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
