<1ST_LINE>u w PM-DefenseProbe-Paisley 1stLd-Writethru a05Iraniancivilairliner
07-15 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe-Paisley, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0582,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses to Provide Sealed Affidavit to Paisley Attorneys</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts grafs 2, meanwhile a federal, and 12-14, In Los
Angeles, with magistrate in Los Angeles ordering affidavits
unsealed.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today refused to provide
a sealed government affidavit to attorneys for defense consultant
Melvyn Paisley, a key figure in the massive defense procurement
investigation.
   Meanwhile, a federal magistrate in Los Angeles ordered the
government to unseal four other search warrant affidavits. However,
he delayed the unsealing until 5 p.m. EDT and the government said
it would appeal the decision.
   U.S. District Court Judge James C. Cacheris overruled a
magistrate who last week told Paisley's attorneys they could see
the 61-page affidavit so long as they showed it to no one else,
including Paisley.
   ``The court finds the magistrate's ruling is clearly
erroneous,'' Cacheris said.
   He agreed with U.S. Attorney Henry Hudson's arguments that the
government's case could be hurt by premature disclosure of the
affidavit, which outlines the government's case and provides a
wealth of detail about why investigators are looking into
activities of Paisley and his wife, Vicki.
   The affidavit was used by FBI agents to conduct searches of
Paisley's house and office.
   The government's sensitive investigation involves national
security issues as well as Pentagon officials, Cacheris said.
   E. Lawrence Barcella Jr., Paisley's attorney, said he was
disappointed with the ruling and was considering whether he should
appeal Cacheris' decision to the 4th Circuit Court of Appeals.
   Hudson argued that the Paisleys and their lawyers only wanted
the affidavit to satisfy ``idle curiosity.'' But he said the papers
should remain sealed so the government can complete its probe.
   He promised Cacheris that the affidavit would be released to the
public within about a month.
   Paisley, a former assistant secretary of the Navy, is one of 40
people and companies that have been identified as targets of the
massive investigation of the Pentagon's $150-billion-a-year
procurement process.
   In Los Angeles, the search warrants ordered unsealed by U.S.
Magistrate Joseph Reichmann were executed on June 13 and permitted
government to search the offices of Northrop Corp., Teledyne
Industries, Litton Industries and the home of defense consultant
Fred Lackner.
   ``We are talking about the foundations of our country, the
defense of our country,'' Reichmann said in ruling on motions by
the Los Angeles Times, Copley Newspapers and the National
Broadcasting Corp.
   ``I've come to the conclusion there is this right of access, to
obtain things lodged with the court, prior to the return of an
indictment,'' he said.
   The investigation centers around allegations that defense
consultants paid bribes to Pentagon officials to obtain information
that would help contractors secure government projects.
   No charges have been filed in the investigation, but grand jury
subponeas have been issued to numerous people, including Paisley.
</TEXT>
