<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-GoneFishingBjt     07-15 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Gone Fishing Bjt,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Candidate and Treasury Secretary Vacation in Wyoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the eve of the Democratic National
Convention, Republican George Bush and his chief political mentor,
Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III, are going fishing.
   Whether the two plan to spend 4{ days in the wilds of Wyoming
also casting for a prospective GOP running mate, Bush aides aren't
saying. But, the aides suggest, draw your own conclusions on what
the talk may turn to when the fish aren't biting.
   The vice president and Baker leave for Wyoming on Saturday, and
will remain there until Wednesday morning. Then, Bush plans to hit
the campaign trail hard, with events scheduled during the final two
days of the Democratic convention _ a break with tradition _ and on
through the next weekend.
   Sources said the two will be fly fishing in the Shoshone
National Forest in northest Wyoming _ which covers a lot of
territory.
   Campaign spokeswoman Sheila Tate says she has no idea where Bush
and Baker will be. The closest town, she said, is Cody.
   ``You're looking at someone with zero knowledge,'' said Ms.
Tate, who says she think she's being kept purposely in the dark on
Bush's whereabouts. ``It's the last chance he'll have in many years
to have a few days of normal vacation. He deserves it,'' she said.
   Normal vacation it isn't.
   Besides having with him the man soon expected to become his
campaign chairman, Bush will be taking along a small Secret Service
contingent and communications officers to keep him in touch with
the White House.
   And, because it's deemed an ``official'' vacation rather than a
campaign trip, taxpayers will be picking up the tab for the flight
out on Air Force Two.
   Bush aides also say there'll be a forest ranger along as a guide.
   ``He's the vice president of the United States and he will be in
touch if he needs to be,'' said vice presidential aide Stephen
Hart. ``He's not going to drop off the face of the earth.''
   Bush and Baker are not taking their wives on the vacation.
Barbara Bush will spend most of the time at the Bush's seacoast
retreat in Kennebunkport, Maine.
   ``Happy campers are all boys,'' Ms. Tate said.
   It will be a change of pace for Bush, who does most of his
fishing in the Atlantic Ocean in his 27-foot powerboat off
Kennebunkport. ``He is in a great mood at the prospect of
reaquainting himself with fly fishing techniques,'' Ms. Tate said.
   Baker is a longtime friend and political adviser to Bush. He ran
Bush's 1980 presidential campaign and was senior counsel to the
1984 Reagan-Bush re-election campaign.
   Bush campaign sources say they expect Baker to resign as
treasury secretary to join the Bush campaign as its senior
official, most likely in early August, just before the Republican
convention.
   Although the two administration officials themselves have been
tight-lipped on specific plans, Bush makes it no secret that he
already relies on Baker unofficially for campaign advice. Baker
does not dispute this. ``I return my telephone calls,'' Baker said
in a recent interview.
   There had been speculation that Bush and Baker would be staying
at a cabin near Cody, Wyo., on the South Fork of the Shoshone River
owned by Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo., a close friend of Bush's and
among those mentioned as a possible running mate.
   However, Simpson spokeswoman Mary Kay Hill said Friday that the
vice president would not be staying there and that Simpson had no
plans to join the fishing trip.
   Bush will reappear on Wednesday, the next-to-last night of the
Democratic convention, with two campaign apperances planned in the
the Detroit area. And on Thursday, the day when Dukakis will
deliver his acceptance speech, Bush dips into the South with
campaign events planned in Charlotte, N.C. and Greenville, S.C.
   That will break a longstanding tradition in which presidential
contenders have ceased political activity during the rival party's
nominating convention.
   Bush plans to campaign in Wisconsin and New Jersey the following
day and in Tennessee and Florida July 23. He will address a
business and professional womens' convention in Albuquerque, N.M.,
on July 24.
</TEXT>
