<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ScienceMedalists     07-15 0754</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Science Medalists,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Superconductivity Products For Sale Within 3 Years, Expert Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Products using superconductivity may appear on
the market within three years, but it will take a decade or more
for major applications of the technology, a prominent researcher
said Friday.
   Paul C. W. Chu of the University of Houston commented in an
interview after President Reagan awarded him and 19 other
researchers the national medal of science. Reagan also awarded the
national medal of technology to 10 prominent leaders in the
technical industries.
   Chu, cited in the award description for a series of discoveries
that helped raise the temperature of superconductive materials,
said the new technology probably will be on the market in the form
of special batteries and smoke detectors within two to three years.
   Microelectronics, electrical switches and other thin film
electrical connectors will probably benefit from superconductivity
within five years, Chu said.
   ``But any large scale application is at least 10 years away,''
he said. He predicted that by the end of the century
superconductivity technology will be applied to the transmission of
electricty and in large magnets.
   Superconductivity is a material state that permits electricity
to flow without resistance. For decades, this was thought to occur
only in metals chilled to temperatures approaching absolute zero:
minus 459.6 degrees Fahrenheit.
   But Chu and other researchers, experimenting with ceramic
compounds, have discovered how to raise the minimum
superconductivity temperature to about inus 243 degrees, a
temperature easily maintained with relatively inexpensive liquid
nitrogen.
   Experts believe the technology will permit the manufacture of
large, powerful magnets that could be used in transportation and
medicine. The technology also could substantially reduce the cost
of electricity since about half of generated power is lost to
transmission resistance. Also, superconductivity could speed up
computers and permit the more efficient storage of electricity.
   Chu said many nations now are racing to develop
superconductivity technology and it is not clear who has the lead.
He said he could not predict which nation would make the first
practical application of the new technology, but ``I am very
impressed by the Japanese effort.''
   Reagan, in presenting the medals, said it is vital that the
United States continue to promote research into emerging
technologies that will have a major influence on life in the future.
   The president praised the medal winners as the ``men and women
who are leading us into the new age of technology'' and that one of
the most important jobs of government is ``knocking down the
barriers of progress.''
   ``America's greatest resource is not the land,'' he said. ``No,
America's greatest resource is the genius of our people.''
   Reagan gave 20 researchers the national medal of science, an
honor established by Congress in 1959 to recognize achievements in
physical, biological, mathematical, behavioral, social or
engineering sciences.
   In addition to Chu, those receiving the science medal were
Joseph L. Goldstein and Michael S. Brown of the University of Texas
Southwestern Medical Center, Dallas; William O. Baker of Bell
Telephone Laboratories in Murray Hill, N.J.; Konrad E. Bloch,
Harvard University, Cambridge, Mass.; D. Allan Bromley, Yale
University, New Haven, Conn.;
   Stanley N. Cohen, Stanford University, Stanford, Calif.; Elias
J. Corey, Harvard; Daniel C. Drucker, University of Florida,
Gainesville, Fla.; Milton Friedman, Stanford; Ralph E. Gomory, IBM,
Armonk, N.Y.; Willis M. Hawkins, Lockheed Corp., Calabasas, Calif.;
Maurice R. Hilleman, Merck and Co., West Point, Pa.; George W.
Housner, California Institute of Technology, Pasadena, Calif;
   Eric R. Kandel, Columbia University and the New York State
Psychiatric Institute, New York, N.Y.; Joseph B. Keller, Stanford;
Walter Kohn, University of California, Santa Barbara; Norman F.
Ramsey, Harvard; Jack Steinberger, European Center for Nuclear
Research, Geneva, Switzerland, and Rosalyn S. Yalow, Mt. Sinai
School of Medicine, New York, N.Y.
   The 10 winners of the national medal of technology named by
Reagan were Edwin H. Land, founder of the Polaroid Corp. and now
president of the Rowland Institute for Science in Cambridge, Mass.;
John L. Atwood, Rockwell International Corp., El Segundo, Calif.;
Arnold O. Beckman, Beckman Instruments, Irvine, Calif.; Paul M.
Cook, Raychem Corp., Menlo Park, Calif.;
   Richard H. Dennard, IBM, Yorktown Heights, N.Y.; Harold E.
Edgerton, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Cambridge;
Clarence L. Johnson, Lockheed; David Packard, Hewlett-Packard Co.,
Palo Alto, Calif.; Raymond Damadian, FONAR Corp., Melville, N.Y.,
and Paul C. Lauterbur, University of Illinois at Urbana.
   The technology medal was created in 1980 by Congress to
recognize those who advance American technology and improved the
nation's economy, environment or social well-being.
</TEXT>
