<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan Bjt   07-15 0789</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan, Bjt,0809</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tass: Afghan Rebel Rockets Kill 20 In Kabul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan rebels fired more than 20 rockets into
residential areas of Kabul on Friday, killing 20 people, wounding
34 and damaging a mosque and other buildings in the Afghanistan
capital, the Tass news agency reported.
   The 5:30 a.m. attack, which Tass denounced as ``barbarous'' and
a ``crime,'' was the latest reported on a major population center
in Afghanistan. Fighting has spread throughout the rugged and
mountainous country as the Soviets withdraw their troops.
   Radio Kabul also reported the attack on residential areas of the
Afghan capital. The dispatch was monitored in Islamabad, Pakistan.
   However, Afghan guerrilla leader Abdul Haq told The Associated
Press in Islamabad the insurgents do not target residential
neighborhoods. He said the 15 to 20 rebel targets in Kabul, which
include the airport and Soviet Embassy, are not residential areas.
   Haq claimed Afghan government troops and their Soviet backers
fire rockets into Kabul's residential districts to discredit the
guerrillas and undermine their burgeoning popular support.
   ``We fire five rockets, and suddenly, we see 20 hit,'' Haq said,
disavowing responsibility for all bombardments in Kabul.
   Tass said it was ``monstrous'' to suggest Soviet forces would
fire on a city they still occupied and said one of the 21 rockets
launched on four Kabul neighborhoods Friday exploded next to the
Soviet Embassy. A label on one undetonated missile showed it came
from Egypt, Tass said.
   Afghan President Najib, speaking to members of the armed forces,
said Wednesday the insurgents have become bolder as Soviet troops
depart. Under an accord signed April 14 in Geneva, the Kremlin
committed itself to begin withdrawing its more than 100,000 troops
on May 15, and to complete the pullout by Feb. 15. Half of the
Soviet soldiers are to be home by August.
   ``More than 35,000 Soviet internationalists have returned to
their country,'' Najib said in a speech broadcast by official Kabul
radio and monitored by the British Broadcasting Corp.
   However, Najib said: ``Armed interference in the internal
affairs of our country ... is not only continuing, but has
intensified. ... The extremists engage in savage crimes against
peaceful people.''
   Tass said villages in the provinces of Paktia, Paktika and Kunar
were heavily bombarded by the insurgents Thursday and that at least
five people, including three children, were killed.
   Radio Kabul said a land mine planted by guerrillas exploded
Thursday in a crowded bazaar in Rodat, 30 miles from the border
with Pakistan. Two people were killed and one injured.
   More than 150 civilians were reported killed last weekend when
the anti-Marxist rebels, aided by the United States, used artillery
and rockets to shell populated areas in more than eight provinces.
   On July 8, a car packed with explosives blew up near a downtown
movie theater in the eastern city of Jalalabad, killing 31 people
and injuring 33 others, Soviet and Afghan media said.
   The Soviet withdrawal places the burden of warfare on the Afghan
army, a force many Western observers believe will be unable to
withstand the guerrillas. Tass, however, said Afghan troops had
staged several ``successful operations'' against the rebels
recently.
   It said the army wiped out an insurgent detachment of more than
20 fighters and captured three people who planned to commit
``terrorist acts'' near the southern city of Kandahar.
   Afghanistan's official Bakhtar news agency reported that about
100 anti-government guerrillas were killed in the past week and
that large quantities of weapons were seized, including rocket
launchers, mortars, machine guns, grenade launchers and three
U.S.-made Stinger missiles, Tass said.
   Soviet and Afghan officials maintain they are abiding by the
U.N.-brokered accords on Afghanistan. They have used increasingly
tough language in accusing Pakistan, which is also a signatory, of
blatant violations.
   In particular, the Soviets say Pakistan is allowing its
territory to be used to supply the rebels with weapons and
ammunition and as the home of a rival Afghan government. State-run
Radio Moscow accused Pakistan on Friday of ``crude violations'' of
the Geneva accords.
   The Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman, Vadim P. Perfilyev, told
a government news briefing Thursday the Kremlin may reconsider its
obligations under the agreements if the violations by Pakistan
continue.
   However, he shied away from mentioning any potential Soviet
reaction.
   The commander of Soviet forces in Afghanistan, Lt. Gen. Boris
Gromov, said in a newspaper interview published Sunday that the
violations could force his country to reconsider the withdrawal
timetable.
   The Kremlin sent tanks and troops into Afghanistan in December
1979 to preside over the replacement of one Marxist leader by
another. The Soviets stayed on to fight the guerrillas in a brutal
war in which more than 13,000 Red Army soldiers lost their lives.
</TEXT>
