<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson     07-15 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Bus Caravan Leaving Scarcely a Ripple</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson avoided stirring new
controversy between himself and Michael Dukakis Friday as his
``Rainbow Express'' caravan rolled South, leaving ripples of
attention along the highways.
   The caravan, bound for next week's Democratic National
Convention, included seven buses and an equal number of cars.
Inside were about 120 reporters and photographers, 30 or so
supporters and about a dozen delegates, staffers said.
   They arrived in Lousiville at mid-day for Jackson to have lunch
at an inner-city church. As he entered, Jackson ignored shouted
questions from reporters about a possible meeting with Dukakis.
   He planned rallies in Louisville and in Nashville, Tenn., Friday
night.
   Construction workers stared curiously at the buses festooned
with banners and posters, and knots of people gathered each time
the motorcade swept into a city.
   At rallies along the way, Jackson focused on mobilizing his
supporters, though the Atlanta convention is sure to nominate
Dukakis for president and Dukakis' choice of Lloyd Bentsen for vice
president. Jackson battled Dukakis for the presidential nomination
for months, then lobbied for the No. 2 slot.
   In the midst of a tense, week-long focus on relations between
the Jackson and Dukakis camps, Jackson concentrated on the
Republicans and their expected nominee, George Bush.
   ``We survived Reagan, we can survive anything,'' Jackson said.
``We're getting ready to send Bush back into private life.''
   In meetings with reporters, Jackson said he'll meet with Dukakis
``at an appropriate time.'' Former President Carter could help
mediate ``at the appropriate time.''
   For the moment, Jackson seemed content to work on his convention
speech and prepare for a showy arrival in Atlanta on Saturday.
   His was the first bus in the caravan, equipped with a kitchen.
He was accompanied by his children and advisers.
   Wife, Jackie, was helping prepare for his arrival.
   ``She was wise enough to fly to Atlanta,'' Jackson said.
   ``We're not picking up passengers; we're registering,'' Jackson
said. ``Because of travel time, we're not encouraging additional
passengers.''
   Jackson did draw distinctions between the credentials of an
anointed leader of the party, and his own role.
   ``I may never get the leader label,'' Jackson said. ``But
leaders have followers and support.''
   ``When I look at those who have been to the White House and
those who are trying to go ... I may or may not get there, but I'm
qualified,'' Jackson said.
</TEXT>
