<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--GEBuilding     07-15 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--GE Building,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RCA Building To Be Renamed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anyone looking for the RCA Building entrance on
Sixth Avenue next year is in for some confusion.
   They changed the name of Sixth Avenue to the Avenue of the
Americas years ago; early next year, they're changing the name of
the RCA Building, the 70-story landmark in the center of
Rockefeller Center, to the G.E. Building.
   General Electric purchased RCA and its network television
division, NBC, two years ago. The building is the network's
headquarters, and has carried the RCA name for more than five
decades.
   In a memo to employees Wednesday, NBC President Robert Wright
said the company intended ``to change the name of the building and
the signage to the G.E. Building, to reflect our current
ownership.''
   ``It seems sort of the obvious evolution of things,'' said NBC
spokeswoman Betty Hudson. The building is owned by Rockefeller
Center, but General Electric has the right to change the name.
   Five blocks away, there is another landmark building known as
the General Electric Building. It was once known as the RCA Victor
Building before G.E. moved in in 1933.
</TEXT>
