<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     07-15 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Administration Cuts West Bank School Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military administration said Friday it
would end the school year in the occupied West Bank in a week, and
Arab students complained they would lose a month of studies and
fail their final exams.
   Also Friday, a United Nations official blamed prolonged army
curfews and Palestinian commercial strikes for cash shortages in
the occupied Gaza Strip.
   The official, who requested anonymity, also reported problems in
the delivery of food supplies to Gaza's refugee camps. But he said
no one was going hungry in the strip, where 650,000 Palestinians
live.
   In another development, an 18-year-old Arab was wounded in the
leg during a clash with soldiers in Gaza's Bureij camp, a local
reporter said. The army said it was not aware of the incident.
   A spokesman for the Israeli military administration in the West
Bank said the school year would end on July 21, with final exams
likely to begin Saturday.
   Palestinian students said the step would chop a month off the
school year and give them no time to study for their exams. They
said the school year had been scheduled to end in mid-August.
   But the military spokesman, Olivier Rafovitz, said the dates in
August had only been tentative. He said the measure was not
political but ``a purely technical decision.''
   At the height of the Arab uprising in February, the army closed
800 West Bank schools, claiming they were major centers of
Palestinian unrest. The schools were reopened in a three-stage
procedure ending June 6.
   Since the reopening, the military administration ordered several
dozen schools closed until the end of the school year. It also kept
280,000 Palestinian students in the West Bank out of school for a
week after student riots.
   Arab students said the new measure meant they would fail their
exams.
   ``There is no time to study. If we go for exams, nobody would
pass,'' said Issam Ismaeel, 18, of Bethlehem High School. ``They
are trying to pressure us and it's clear they are after our
failure.''
   A curfew on Nablus, the largest West Bank city with 120,000 Arab
residents, entered its fourth day Friday.
   Curfews also continued in the town of Qalqilya, the vilage of
Beit Sahur and the Aida refugee camp near Bethlehem, and two other
West Bank villages. In Beit Sahur, villagers have been confined to
their homes for eight days.
   A U.N. relief official said prolonged curfews in Gaza have
caused financial shortages. He cited a 15-day curfew imposed last
month on the Bureij camp after its Arab municipality resigned in
response to threats from leaders of the 7-month-old Arab uprising.
   Since the uprising began in December, 222 Palestinians and four
Israelis have been killed.
   The official also blamed a six-week ban on Gazans leaving for
work in Israel and Arab-ordered commercial strikes for the economic
difficulties.
   The official said the army was letting U.N. relief trucks
deliver basic food supplies to the camps, and said there was no
real food shortage. ``What you've got is shortages of money,'' he
said.
   The Israeli daily Haaretz, however, quoted an Israeli reserve
trooper Friday as saying: ``In the past few days I have given out
watermelons, cantaloupes and some even come and beg me for bread.
We know there is a severe food shortage in the camps.''

</TEXT>
