<1ST_LINE>r a AM-InterstateLink     07-15 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Interstate Link,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>I-64 Link Opens With Fanfare; Businesses On Old Road Fear For
Their Welfare</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BECKLEY, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Arch Moore ceremoniously snipped a
ribbon Friday to open the last 36-mile link of interstate highway
system in his state, but businesses on a competing road say the new
route spells disaster for them.
   After two decades of delay, the completed stretch of Interstate
64 between Sam Black Church and Beckley creates 1,125 miles of
continuous four-lane travel from Norfolk, Va., to St. Louis.
   The new road should shave an hour off the travel time between
Charleston and White Sulphur Springs, in the southeastern part of
the state, reducing the trip to 1{ hours.
   At the opening ceremony, Moore called the $313.5 million link a
``monument to progress.''
   But for businesses along a 190-stretch of two-lane U.S. 60,
which has been southern West Virginia's lifeline for decades, I-64
can only mean a drastic drop in travelers.
   ``I think it'll be really disastrous,'' said Pat Rogers, who
works at Pioneer Village Country Store in Chimney Corner, 45 miles
east of Charleston.
   ``Given a choice, I don't think anyone will drive (U.S.) 60,''
Rogers said. ``You can be there for days.''
   U.S. 60 snakes over and around steep mountains, and the narrow
lanes are crowded by coal-truck convoys that often slow traffic to
15 or 20 mph.
   The 2{-hour trip from Charleston to Lewisburg on the Virginia
border is ``white-knuckle driving,'' state Department of Highways
spokesman John Gallagher said.
   The state expects a sharp decline in attendance at Hawks Nest
and Babcock state parks, along U.S. 60.
   ``I'm convinced that there will be an impact, and that it will
not be a positive one,'' said state Commerce Commissioner Robert
Trocin.
   But officials are hoping that the drop in visitors to the parks
will be more than offset by the expected boost I-64 will have in
the tourism economy of the depressed southern counties, now heavily
dependent on coal.
   They estimate that I-64 will increase the number of travelers on
the interstate system in southern West Virginia by 20 to 40 percent.
   ``We will see an influx of commercial building and development
that hasn't been available to us before,'' said Beckley-Raleigh
County Chamber of Commerce President Bill Wilbur.
   As originally planned, I-64 would have run along U.S. 60's
route. In the mid-1960s, however, the route was changed to protect
wetlands and to shorten the road, causing years of construction
delays. Instead of running directly from Lewisburg to Charleston,
it now runs to Beckley, 51 miles south of the capital.
   Friday's dedication took place on the east end of the $29
million Glade Creek Bridge on a platform festooned with red, white
and blue balloons. Joining Moore were former Govs. Hulett Smith and
Okey Patteson and the state's two U.S. senators and four
congressmen.
   The Department of Highways estimated the turnout at 10,000 but
Moore put the figure at 50,000. Traffic was backed up for several
miles in the broiling sun as motorists and spectators waited for
the dignitaries to snip the ribbon and open the road to traffic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
