Scottish movie ``Local Hero.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DAVOS, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A friend of Prince Charles who broke
both legs in an avalanche that narrowly missed the prince returned
to England on Friday after a four-month hospital stay.
   Patricia Palmer-Tomkinson, walking on crutches, was released
from Davos hospital and flew home from Zurich accompanied by her
husband, Charles.
   She underwent surgery several times for multiple fractures after
the March 10 avalanche above the Swiss town of Klosters.
   Six plates and 40 screws remain in Mrs. Palmer-Tomkinson's legs,
hospital spokesman Rosmarie Holliger said.
   Maj. Hugh Lindsay, 34, a friend of Charles and an aide to his
mother, Queen Elizabeth II, was killed in the snowslide, which
occurred on an extremely steep slope away from official marked runs.
