<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buster Poindexter has it good: His act is on
tour, he appears in a widely seen liqueur ad, his song ``Hot Hot
Hot'' has hit the charts, and he even has a role in an upcoming
movie with Bill Murray.
   The permanently tuxedoed Buster Poindexter, who is an alter-ego
created by former rock star David Johansen of the flamboyant New
York Dolls, is thriving in his lounge-lizard character.
   For his nightclub act he draws on Gilbert and Sullivan, Patti
Page, Muddy Waters, Archie Bell and plenty of singers from the
1920s through the '40s.
   ``When the Beastie Boys came out, I thought they were the
hippest band since the Dolls. They were saying the same thing we
were _ I am somebody,'' Johansen said.
   Murray saw Poindexter's act and got Johansen a role as the Ghost
of Christmas Past in the movie ``Scrooged,'' to be released at
Christmastime. The credits will roll his real name.
   In addition to a new album and the success of ``Hot Hot Hot,''
Poindexter also is a star of an Amaretto advertisement. He was
approached when he became a semiregular on ``Saturday Night Live.''
Soon the ``Amaretto di Buster'' ad was splashed all over magazines.
