<DOCNO> AP880715-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1503EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 3rd-LdWritethru a0584 07-15 0919</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 3rd-Ld Writethru, a0584,9890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Carter Not Needed as Mediator</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Tops with 8 grafs to update with Dukakis, Jackson comments,
picking up in 2nd graf pvs, As Jackson</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis today dismissed as unnecessary Jesse Jackson's
proposal for former President Carter to act as a mediator between
their two campaigns.
   ``We don't need mediators,'' the nominee-to-be said in an
interview in the governor's office in Boston.
   Dukakis said he and Jackson talked eariler today, but he refused
to discuss the substance of the conversation.
   Asked if he expected Jackson's name to be offered to the
convention for the vice presidential nomination, Dukakis said he
didn't know.
   In Louisville, Jackson declined to discuss the phone call except
in general terms.
   ``Clearly, the governor understands the steps that are now
necessary for unity and partnership to be achieved,'' he said.
   Asked if he would allow his name to be put into nomination
Thursday night for vice president, Jackson replied: ``That's really
a moot question.''
   Dukakis' rejection of the mediation proposal came after
Democratic Party chief Paul Kirk dismissed the idea and aides to
Jackson also expressed doubts about it.
   As Jackson left Indianapolis today on the second day of his bus
trip to Atlanta and next week's national convention, his convention
manager Ron Brown said the tension between the campaigns ``isn't a
question of personal pique or personal relationships.''
   ``It's a question of equity. It's a question of partnership,''
Brown said on ``CBS This Morning.''
   Dukakis insisted Thursday he has a good relationship with
Jackson, even as his remaining rival asked Carter to help resolve
``the creative tensions'' between them.
   Kirk disagreed with Jackson.
   ``I don't think, in my view, that the fact that there has been
some miscommunication at this point requires the president of the
United States to come to the table,'' Kirk said on CBS. ``I think
that Ron and his counterpart, Susan Estrich ... ought to come to
the table within the next several hours, talk over the issues, get
the platform discussions back on track and be ready for a real
celebration of unity here as we prepare for the fall campaign.''
   Brown said that any role for Carter was ``not clear yet.
Frankly, we've come to no conclusion on that.''
   Bert Lance, the Jackson adviser and former Carter White House
official, said in an interview, ``I'm not sure it's necessary. ...
Mike and Jesse can deal with whatever they have to deal with.''
   However, Lance also said some involvement by Carter could help
Dukakis with Jackson's followers.
   Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, a Jackson supporter, said it
was Lance who came up with the Carter idea, but Lance declined to
confirm that. He was budget director for Carter in the White House.
   ``We will exercise all of our rights,'' Jackson said in Chicago
before joining a seven-bus motorcade. ``It is an open convention.
... We are prepared to deliberate and debate, Tuesday, Wednesday
and Thursday.''
   Jackson remained indignant over the handling of the selection of
Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen as Dukakis's running mate.
   ``The Boston-Austin connection leaves Chicago out of the
equation,'' he said. But he also spoke of reconciliation.
   ``We hope in the next three or four days that matters will be
resolved,'' Jackson said at an Indianapolis news conference. He
added that he expected a meeting with Dukakis at ``some appropriate
time.''
   Meanwhile, a new state poll suggested the choice of Bentsen had
helped the Democratic ticket in Texas, adopted home state of
Republican George Bush.
   And Bush took advantage of his status as vice president, going
to the United Nations to defend U.S. actions surrounding the
downing of an Iranian airliner.
   ``I will not dignify with a response the charge that we
deliberately destroyed Iran Air 655,'' Bush told the Security
Council. ``The foreign minister of Iran knows better. He knows that
this tragedy was an accident.''
   It was to be Bush's last public appearance for a week, as he is
scheduled to leave for a six-day fishing trip on Saturday.
   Jackson spent the night in Indianapolis, and his bus caravan was
taking him today to Louisville, Ky., and Nashville, Tenn.
   Dukakis was spending today focusing on state government business
in Boston.
   The Massachusetts governor avoided public questioning on
Jackson, but repeated in a CBS News interview that he had
apologized to Jackson for failing to reach him before news of the
choice of Lloyd Bentsen of Texas as his running mate.
   ``Jesse and I have had a good relations over the past couple of
months and that's going to continue,'' Dukakis said.
   Asked if he expects that television viewers will see Jackson on
the podium for a unity picture on the last night of the convention
next week, Dukakis was optimistic: ``I expect that you will.''
   Campaign aides said efforts were under way to arrange a meeting
between Dukakis and Jackson in Atlanta on Sunday, the day Dukakis
is scheduled to arrive. Jackson's bus trip is slated to wrap up
Saturday afternoon with a big Atlanta rally.
   Jackson raised new possibilities as he began his bus trip,
revealing that he had called Carter early Thursday morning to ask
him to mediate.
   A new NBC News-Wall Street Journal poll nationally gave Dukakis
about a 10-point lead. The survey of 1,695 registered voters July
8-11 gave Dukakis 46 percent, Bush 36 percent. That is a similar
margin to other polls, but five points below the margin found in a
June poll.
</TEXT>
