<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Peace Groups Stage Own Convention As Democrats Head For Town</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 70 national and local peace and justice
groups, hoping to influence political policy, began their own
meeting in Atlanta Friday, three days before the Democratic
National Convention gets under way.
   Organizers of the Fannie Lou Hamer Convention plan to create a
``People's Platform'' during their three-day meeting to be sent to
Democratic and Republican national convention delegates.
   The platform will be produced from workshops with such titles as
``Military Counseling and Equal Access to our Youth,'' ``U.S.
Government and the Drug Connection,'' ``Global Struggles for
Self-Determination and Basic Human Rights'' and ``Right Wing
Authoritarianism and the Fascist Mentality.''
   The convention is named after a black Mississippi woman who led
a challenge to that state's all-white delegation to the 1964
Democratic convention.
   The convention is being held in a downtown church, across the
street from the state Capitol where white supremacists are
scheduled to hold a rally Sunday.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for white supremacists and minority
activists involved in the Fannie Lou Hamer Convention agreed in
court Friday not to interfere with each other's planned activities
this weekend.
   The settlement in Fulton County Superior Court came in response
to a complaint filed by three activist organizations _ the Center
for Democratic Renewal, the National Rainbow Coalition and LEGAL, a
gay rights group _ and various individuals against the city of
Atlanta, the white supremacist Nationalist Movement and three of
its leaders.
   The complaint asked for a temporary restraining order and a
permanent injunction to prevent the white supremacists from
``parading with weapons, inciting to riot, intimidating,
threatening, harassing or otherwise interfering'' with the rights
of the plaintiffs during simultaneous activities set for Sunday in
downtown Atlanta.
   As the Hamer convention wraps up in a church Sunday, the
Nationalist Movement is set to start a march directly across the
street at the state Capitol.
   Under Friday's agreement, both parties are enjoined from
entering the other's area. This limits the supremacists to the
Capitol grounds and the activists to the church.
   The groups also are ``mutually restrained from making threats of
immediate violence to each other,'' said Janise L. Miller, the
activists' attorney.
   The agreement also limits the size of flagpoles and sign poles
used by the marchers.
   Sam Dickson represented the Nationalist Movement leaders, none
of whom was present. ``I think it's a sensible order,'' he said.
``I think the Garden Club and the Elks Lodge would agree to it.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Court Rules In Favor Of City In Convention Marches Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city of Atlanta won a ruling from the 11th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Friday in its dispute with
demonstrators who sought to march on a street adjacent to the
Democratic National Convention site.
   The appeals court noted that the city had given permission for
demonstrators to march within one block of the buildings housing
convention activities.
   ``The visibility of the parade from the actual convention site
is not significantly diminished'' by holding it a block away, the
court said.
   Alternative '88, a coalition of protest groups planning to
demonstrate during next week's convention, had filed suit after the
city refused to allow parades on a section of Marietta Street next
to the Omni Hotel and the Georgia World Congress Center.
   U.S. District Judge Orinda Evans ruled last week that the city
has a ``significant'' government interest in guaranteeing
delegates' access to the convention and therefore was justified in
barring parades on the street from Monday through Thursday.
   The appeals court upheld the lower court ruling.
</TEXT>
