<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile-Letelier     07-15 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Letelier,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rules Out Probe Into Slaying Of Allende Aide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court rejected a request to
reopen an investigation of the 1976 assassination in Washington of
a Chilean dissident.
   The request was filed by lawyers for the family of the
dissident, Orlando Letelier, and was based on new testimony in a
U.S. court by a former Chilean army major who acknowledged a role
in the killing.
   The Supreme Court's unanimous ruling was made Thursday night and
was published Friday by Santiago newspapers.
   Letelier family lawyers argued that the new investigation was
necessary following testimony before a Washington court by Armando
Fernandez Larios, the army major who surrendered to U.S.
authorities in January 1987 and admitted to being an accomplice in
the killing.
   Letelier and an American aide, Ronni Moffitt, were killed when a
remote-control bomb blew up his car on Sept. 21, 1976, as it
rounded Sheridan Circle on Washington's Embassy Row.
   Letelier, a Socialist and former ambassador and Cabinet minister
under Marxist President Salvador Allende, was a prominent and
influential critic of the right-wing military government of
President Augusto Pinochet.
   Pinochet took power in the 1973 coup that toppled Allende.
   The Supreme Court said in its ruling that Fernandez Larios' U.S.
District Court testimony ``cannot be considered as better
information.''
   It also noted the testimony was made after a plea-bargain
agreement. Plea bargaining is barred by Chilean law.
   In 1978, a Washington court indicted Fernandez Larios and two
other Chilean army officers, all secret police agents, in
connection with the Letelier killing. The Chilean Supreme Court
rejected a U.S. request for the extradition of the three officers,
but last year Fernandez Larios slipped out of the country and
surrendered to American authorities in Washington.
   In 1987, the Reagan administration again called on Chile to hand
over the other two officers, Gen. Manuel Contreras, a former secret
police chief, and a top aide, Col. Pedro Espoinoza. Chile refused.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
