<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0595,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Heads South Demanding Respect, Seeking Conciliation</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS new graf 8 with Dukakis on Carter mediation; picks up
pvs graf 8: Paul Kirk</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson headed south today looking for
conciliation with Michael Dukakis, as top Democrats questioned
whether President Carter was needed to mediate tensions between the
two camps.
   Jackson, who called on Carter to help ease the rift, insisted
Thursday ``we have every reason to seek a bridge'' spanning
differences between him and the nominee-to-be.
   ``We hope that in the next three or four days that matters will
be resolved'' with Dukakis forces, Jackson said. ``No doubt _ we're
not going to give up on communications.''
   Jackson, in the second day of his three-day bus trek to next
week's convention in Atlanta, has expressed irritation over his
perceived snub during the selection of Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen for
the No. 2 spot.
   But he sent conciliatory signals, stressing ways to rebuild
relations with Dukakis.
   First, he said he had spoken with former president Jimmy Carter
about serving as a go-between. Carter has not said publicly whether
he will play any such role. Later, Jackson suggested that top
policy-makers from the two campaigns should talk.
   ``The chief policy advisers of both camps have not met,'' he
said. ``Maybe they could be a bridge in the process. We have every
reason to seek a bridge.''
   In Boston, Dukakis dismissed the idea. ``We don't need
mediators,'' he said.
   Paul Kirk, the party chairman, said today he sees no need for
Carter to be called in to mediate. Instead, he said on ``CBS This
Morning,'' top advisers to Jackson and Dukakis ``ought to come to
the table within the next several hours, talk over the issues, get
the platform discussions back on track and be ready for a real
celebration.''
   Bert Lance, the Jackson adviser and former Carter White House
official, said in an interview, ``I'm not sure it's necessary. ...
Mike and Jesse can deal with whatever they have to deal with.''
   However, Lance also said some involvement by Carter could help
Dukakis with Jackson's followers.
   On the same program, Ron Brown, Jackson's convention manager,
said no one should doubt that Jackson will support the
Dukakis-Bentsen ticket.
   ``The question is what (is) the level and intensity of the
support of his constituents going to be, and that is going to be
dependent upon Michael Dukakis, the message of the party, the
direction of the party,'' Brown said.
   At a news conference on his arrival in Indianapolis, Jackson was
asked if there was reason for optimism that platform and other
differences with Dukakis could be worked out and he said ``I
certainly hope so.
   ``At some appropriate time _ together _ we will meet. No
doubt,'' Jackson said.
   Jackson declined to be specific about what he would seek in
return for his help in turning out black voters, but said his
session with Dukakis should be ``a meeting of substance.''
   He also left open the possiblity that his forces will put his
name into nomination for vice president.
   ``We have not yet made a decision about all the strategies we'll
employ,'' Jackson said.
   Jackson aide Brown said today that ``the campaign has no present
plans to put Jesse Jackson's name up for vice president.''
   The bus caravan, aimed at bringing back memories of the civil
rights era, was also headed for Louisville, Ky., Nashville and
Chattanooga in Tennessee before arriving in Atlanta on Saturday.
   The caravan had been billed as a sort of rolling juggernaut
building steam as it headed South, but Jackson spent most of
Thursday closeted in his bus or meeting with advisers.
   Most of the passengers were reporters rather than Jackson
backers. There were at least 110 in the press entourage while
Jackson supporters numbered between 30 and 35.
   ``We're not picking up passengers, we're registering,'' Jackson
said. ``Because of travel time, we're not encouraging additional
passengers.''
   At a jammed church here Thursday night, Jackson returned to his
fiery speaking style, but focused on efforts to register new voters
for the fall fight against the likely GOP nominee George Bush.
   ``We're getting ready to send Bush back into private life,''
Jackson said. ``We're picking up registrations all the way down the
line.''
</TEXT>
