<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Democrats-Platform     07-15 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Platform,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Jackson Camps Said Near Agreement On Platform Before
Talks Broke Off</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dukakis and Jackson campaigns already had
smoothed out most of their differences on the Democratic platform
before the Jackson side called a halt to the formal negotiations,
Jackson's convention manager said Friday.
   Ron Brown said that when Jackson broke off the negotiations
Wednesday, the platform was ``close to completed. We had dealt with
most of the issues.''
   If the talks resume, Brown said in an interview in Atlanta,
``we'd be close to signing off on it.''
   In Washington, sources on the Platform Committee said the
Dukakis and Jackson campaigns had been seeking a compromise on the
Middle East that would speak of human rights for all under the Camp
David Accords, and make a specific reference to the Palestinians.
   Dukakis platform representatives rejected out of hand last month
in Denver Jackson's call for self-determination for the
Palestinians.
   The sources, who asked not to be identified, said it was likely
that the Dukakis forces would accept a Jackson minority plank on
child care and family issues, while voting down Jackson's call for
higher taxes and a military freeze.
   Jackson has reserved the right to take as many as 13 issues to
the floor for votes Tuesday when the convention takes up the
platform.
   But his negotiators said from the outset it was unlikely they
would pursue them all.
   Brown said that most of the work that remains to be done on the
platform deals with the format and how it will be presented to the
convention.
   Brown said he is in touch with Susan Estrich and Paul Brountas,
Dukakis' campaign manager and chairman, but they were discussing
the larger questions of Jackson's role in the fall campaign, not
the specific platform and convention matters.
   Michael Barnes and Eleanor Holmes Norton, the chief platform
negotiators for the Dukakis and Jackson campaigns respectively,
left Washington Friday for Atlanta.
   Four years ago in San Francisco, the Democrats rebuffed Jackson
by lopsided votes on three minority planks _ a call for a policy of
``no first use'' of nuclear weapons, ``substantial'' cuts in
defense spending, and elimination of runoff primaries _ while
accepting a compromise Jackson proposal on affirmative action. That
convention also adopted Gary Hart's call for limits on use of U.S.
military forces overseas.
   Jackson has nearly 1,150 delegates going to the Atlanta
convention, three times as many as he had in San Francisco.
</TEXT>
