<1ST_LINE>r w AM-IndustrialProduction     07-15 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Industrial Production,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Electricity Demand Boosts Industrial Production in June</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. industrial production, boosted by heavy
demand for electricity during the summer heat wave, climbed 0.4
percent in June, the ninth consecutive month without a decline, the
government said Friday.
   The Federal Reserve said the June advance followed identical
gains of 0.5 percent in both April and May and left output 5.8
percent higher than it was a year ago.
   Analysts said the continued improvement showed that American
manufacturers were still benefiting from an export boom, which has
helped push the nation's jobless rate down to a 14-year low of 5.3
percent while giving the country the smallest trade deficits it has
seen in almost three years.
   ``Manufacturing remains the healthiest sector of the economy,''
said Allen Sinai, chief economist of the Boston Co. ``We continue
to move ahead with an economy driven by the industrial side.''
   But David Wyss, an economist with Data Resources Inc., said the
June advance reflected in large part a big 2.6 percent rise in the
output at the nation's utilities.
   Manufacturing showed a much smaller 0.2 percent rise in output.
   ``We are looking for the increases in industrial production to
slow in coming months,'' he said, reflecting an overhang of
inventories at the consumer level that needs to be worked down.
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said in testimony
earlier this week that the central bank was also looking for
industrial output to slow. He said this would be considered a good
sign that inflationary pressures were easing.
   The 0.2 percent rise in manufacturing reflected a 0.3 percent
increase for factories making durable goods, items expected to last
three or more years, and a smaller 0.1 percent rise in production
of non-durable goods.
   While production of chemical products increased, the non-durable
sector was held back by declines in the output of textiles and
paper.
   Autos were assembled at an annual rate of 7.5 million units in
June, unchanged from May. Production of light trucks, while still
at a high level, edged down slightly last month.
   Production of business equipment showed continued strength, with
a gain of 0.5 percent pushing output in this sector 9.1 percent
above a year ago. The increase last month reflected solid gains in
all major components except construction, mining and farm
equipment, the report said.
   Output in the mining industry, a category that includes oil and
gas drilling, rose 0.6 percent in June, partially reversing a 1.4
percent drop in May.
   The various changes left industrial production at a seasonally
adjusted 136.6 percent of its 1977 base of 100.
</TEXT>
