<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson 1st Ld-Writethru, a0678,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Speaks to Dukakis and Talks of Harmony</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New throughout with Jackson news conference; edits to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rolling South aboard his ``Rainbow
Express'' bus caravan, Jesse Jackson spoke again with certain
Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis Friday, agreeing to
a meeting of top staffers from the two camps and talking
accommodation instead of discord.
   ``We simply cannot win without each other,'' Jackson said at a
news conference along the route to the Democratic convention in
Atlanta. ``We can only win with each other. It is in our distinct
advantage to find common ground.''
   In addition, Jackson continued to reach out to other top
Democrats, this time talking with New York Gov. Mario Cuomo. He
didn't say what they discussed.
   Jackson said he called Dukakis just prior to a noon rally, and
both agreed that their top policy advisers should meet in Atlanta
Saturday night to discuss differences over Democratic policies.
   ``It does not signal yet the resumption of negotiations,''
Jackson said, but added:
   ``Given the creative tension in the past few days, taking a
diplomative initiative to get more people involved is the right
thing to do,'' Jackson said. ``He (Dukakis) agreed it's the right
thing to do.''
   In preparation for the meeting, Jackson scheduled a gathering of
his aides in Nashville Friday night.
   He said the two have no ``acrimony and hostility'' and have only
policy matters to resolve.
   ``I see the tension we're going through as normal and healthy,''
Jackson said.
   But Jackson made it clear his role should be significant.
   ``People have asked repeatedly what do we expect,'' Jackson
said. ``It is not mysterious. We want a commitment in the platform
and by the nominee to new priorities, and to peace.
   ``We seek partnership and shared responsibility in a plan to win
in the fall,'' Jackson said. ``We seek a seat at the table in a
plan to govern in the spring.''
   Jackson declined to say whether a personal meeting between
himself and Dukakis had been scheduled, repeating only that they
``no doubt will meet at some time.''
   ``We obviously have a common interest in a successful
convention,'' Jackson said.
   But Jackson made it clear that conservative forces have had
their day with the selection of Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen to the No.
2 spot, and it's the liberals turn.
   ``All of the talks about conservative Democrats,'' Jackson said.
``They lost in the South on Super Tuesday.''
   Jackson battled Dukakis for the presidential nomination for
months, then lobbied for the vice presidential nomination. He was
then miffed at Dukakis' failure to tell him in advance of Bentsen's
selection.
   The caravan, leaving ripples of attention as it moved South,
included seven buses and an equal number of cars. Inside were about
120 reporters and photographers, 30 or so supporters and about a
dozen delegates, staffers said.
   They arrived in Louisville at mid-day for Jackson to have lunch
at an inner-city church.
   Construction workers stared curiously at the buses festooned
with banners and posters, and knots of people gathered each time
the motorcade swept into a city.
   At rallies along the way, Jackson focused on mobilizing his
supporters, though the convention is sure to nominate Dukakis for
president and Bentsen for vice president.
   Jackson's was the first bus in the caravan, equipped with a
kitchen. He was accompanied by his children and advisers.
   Wife, Jackie, was helping prepare for his arrival.
   ``She was wise enough to fly to Atlanta,'' Jackson said.
   ``We're not picking up passengers; we're registering,'' Jackson
said. ``Because of travel time, we're not encouraging additional
passengers.''
   In the midst of a tense, week-long focus on relations between
the Jackson and Dukakis camps, Jackson took time to lob some fire
at the Republicans and their expected nominee, George Bush.
   ``We survived Reagan, we can survive anything,'' Jackson said.
``We're getting ready to send Bush back into private life.''
</TEXT>
