<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1601EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-BusinessInventories     07-15 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Business Inventories,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Inventories As Well as Sales Climb in May</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business inventories climbed in May for the
17th consecutive month, the government said Friday, but sales also
rose strongly, easing economists' worries that too many goods are
accumulating on shelves and back lots.
   The Commerce Department said inventories rose 0.6 percent to a
seasonally adjusted $728.4 billion, while sales rose 0.9 percent to
$483.7 billion.
   The May gain in inventories followed a 0.5 percent climb in
April and was the strongest since a 0.7 percent increase in January.
   The jump in business sales came after a month of no change in
April and a steep increase of 1.9 percent in March.
   Economists generally take a combination of rising inventories
and falling sales as a sign of future production cutbacks. However,
because sales rose srongly in May, the jump in inventories is less
troublesome.
   ``Although there is inventory accumulation occurring now, it is
in line with the fact that sales and production are increasing,''
said Bruce Steinberg, an economist with Merrill Lynch. ``If sales
were to drop off, then there would be reasons for concern, but
that's not the situation we're in now.''
   Inventories in May were 7.5 percent higher than a year ago,
while sales were 7.8 percent higher.
   The May inventory buildup was boosted by a 0.8 percent climb at
the retail level, where sales were weakest, a 0.7 percent increase
at factories and a 0.3 percent increase at the wholesale level.
   The strength in business sales was paced by a 1.4 percent
increase at manufacturing plants. Wholesale sales climbed 0.6
percent, while retail sales edged up only 0.3 percent.
   Michael K. Evans, an economic forecaster in Washington, said
most of the retail inventory overhang occurred because of weak auto
sales in May.
   ``Excluding cars, retail inventories were up only 0.2 percent.
... June car sales rebounded very strongly which means car
inventories could be coming down,'' he said.
   An advance estimate of retail sales in June, released Thursday,
showed a 0.5 percent rise, bolstered by a strong 1.2 percent rise
in automotive buying.
   The combination of strongly rising sales and moderately rising
inventories held the inventory-to-sales ratio steady at 1.51
percent in May, the same as April. That means it would take 1.51
months to exhaust inventories at the April sales pace, a ratio not
considered abnormally high.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
