<1ST_LINE>r a AM-911Rape     07-15 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-911 Rape,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rape Victim Sues City Over 911</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who was raped in her home after police
responding to a 911 call searched outside, found nothing and left
sued the city Friday, blaming the attack on an inadequate telephone
emergency system.
   The rape Feb. 2 resulted in a shakeup of emergency procedures by
the city and the reprimand of five officers and three 911 employees.
   The suit, filed in state court by the woman and her husband,
seeks unspecified damages.
   The couple charged that the city failed to screen and train 911
employees adequately and failed to correct procedures ``so
deficient that the continued maintenance of them was outrageous and
shocking to the conscience.''
   City Public Safety Director Glenn Cannon and Solicitor Dan
Pellegrini declined comment Friday.
   The woman told police she dialed 911 about 11:15 p.m. after
hearing someone trying to break in to her second-story apartment.
   While she was talking to the 911 operator, a man with a knife
burst in and tore the telephone cord from the wall, authorities
said. The 911 operator thought the woman had hung up, officials
said earlier this year.
   When the intruder saw police walking around the house and heard
them knocking on her door, he threatened the woman and told her he
had ``nothing further to lose and that he might as well rape'' her,
the woman said.
   Police searched outside for several minutes and left. They
didn't break down the door because 911 operators failed to tell
them that the woman reported the break-in herself and that the call
broke off, authorities said.
   No arrests have been made in the attack.
   Cannon ordered 911 operators to pass on detailed information
about emergency calls and to question police about how they resolve
calls before the officers are permitted to leave the scene.
</TEXT>
