<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Lovers'Lawsuit     07-15 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lovers' Lawsuit,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Husband Can't Sue Wife's Lover over Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A husband can't sue his wife's lover for
the emotional distress he suffered when he learned the lover had
fathered her children, a state appeals court ruled.
   Courts should stay out of such affairs, it said Thursday.
   ``The innocent children here may suffer significant harm from
having their family involved in litigation such as this,'' the 1st
District Court of Appeal said in ordering the suit dismissed on
``public policy'' grounds.
   The court said, however, that a husband in such a situation
might be able to sue for reimbursement of money he spent to support
the children after being falsely told he was the father.
   The San Mateo County case involved a divorced couple, identified
by the court as Gerald B. and Linda B., and her lover, Richard P.
   During the affair, the court said, Linda gave birth to a
daughter in 1983 and to a son in 1984.
   She sued for separation from Gerald in 1985, saying at the time
that the children were his. But in a settlement of the divorce case
in January 1987, all parties agreed that Richard was the father.
   Gerald sued Richard the next month, claiming fraud and
intentional infliction of emotional distress, and sought $1.75
million in punitive damages.
   The suit said Richard knew shortly after the births that he was
the father of both children, but misled Gerald into thinking he was
the father, congratulating him and agreeing to be the daughter's
godfather.
   It was only after the children were one and two years old, and
Gerald and his parents had become emotionally attached to them,
that he was told the truth, he said.
   Superior Court Judge Thomas Smith refused to dismiss the suit
but was overruled by the appeals court on a 3-0 vote.
   While fraud and infliction of emotional distress normally are
grounds for a damage suit, the subject of this suit ``is not one in
which it is appropriate for the courts to intervene,'' said the
opinion by Justice Jerome Smith.
   He distinguished the case from suits that have been allowed for
deceit when a woman was infected with venereal disease that her
lover had concealed, or when a woman suffered an abnormal pregnancy
and needed a life-saving operation after her lover told her he was
sterile.
   Both of those cases involved physical injuries and neither had a
potential for harming innocent children, Smith said.
   He also said allowing the suit would conflict with the public
policy of encouraging natural fathers to acknowledge and support
their children.
   ``Men in Richard's situation, who are otherwise willing to
voluntarily acknowledge and support their children, would have a
strong disincentive to do so since revealing the truth would
subject them to this type of tort action,'' Smith said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
