<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Mondale-Democrats     07-15 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mondale-Democrats,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mondale Says Feuding That Goes Too Far Could Be Poison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ATLANTA ( AP) - Walter Mondale, who lost the presidential race
four years ago after a divided convention, said Friday Democrats
must avoid allowing tensions between Jesse Jackson and Michael
Dukakis from going so far they ``set poison down into the roots''
and spoil chances for the ticket in the fall.
   The former vice president, who is staying out of the spotlight
while Democrats hold their convention in Atlanta beginning Monday,
said he hopes Jackson will join in fully supporting the eventual
Democratic ticket with Dukakis and Sen. Lloyd Bentsen _ and
believes he will despite tensions now.
   ``It is traditional, almost to be expected, that we'll have some
struggles _ but it is how those struggles are conducted and whether
they'll stay within the lines that allow the nominee to come out of
the convention with a feeling in the public that he's ready to
president,'' Mondale said.
   ``I think Rev. Jackson knows that,'' he said.
   ``We always have rising tensions about this time; it's inherent.
... But I believe this is a year where Democrats understand these
fights, if they're carried on too far, become too personalized,
they set poison down into the roots that can be difficult to deal
with.''
   Mondale, in an interview with news agency reporters, also said
he believes Dukakis' failure to reach Jackson by telephone to
inform him of Bentsen's selection as vice president was not an
intentional slight. He said it should not be allowed to become the
basis of crippling divisions.
   ``It wasn't intentional,'' he said, noting that Dukakis tried to
call and was unsuccessful. ``It would have been far better if the
call had been completed in time, but those things happen, with the
best of intentions.''
   The former party standard bearer _ loser in a landslide to
President Reagan in 1984 _ said he was not disappointed that he was
not on the program to address the convention.
   ``No, the point here is to get Dukakis elected, Bentsen elected
_ it's not to revive 1984 or any of those other things,'' he said.
``I would play it exactly the way Mike is playing it. He's got to
be here on his own.''
   Mondale appeared at the start of a daylong conference at the
Jimmy Carter Presidential Center, where Democrats and political
observers held seminars on the 1988 election, and the American
political system, for 300 political and government leaders from
foreign countries.
   Ron Brown, Jackson's convention manager and top adviser, offered
a frank acknowledgement that Jackson would not be the Democratic
nominee while saying he would still have his name placed in
nomination for president.
   ``Although we've all concluded, as I do, that Michael Dukakis
will be the nominee of the party, there will actually be two names
to go to the floor of the Democratic National Convention on
Wednesday night, and those two names are Jesse Jackson and Michael
Dukakis,'' Brown said.
   He described Jackson's campaign as altering the political
landscape forever, making race ``much less a factor in American
politics today.''
   Former President Jimmy Carter spoke to the group at a luncheon
where he praised Democratic National Chairman Paul Kirk for having
``orchestrated ... what will be one of the most successful
conventions that we've ever seen, certainly in my political
lifetime.''
</TEXT>
