<1ST_LINE>u p AM-RepublicanCounterpoint     07-15 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Republican Counterpoint,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Find a `Chasm' Between Dukakis and Bentsen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE P. HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican leaders set up shop Friday to snipe at
the Democrats during their convention next week, and immediately
began talking about the policy differences between Michael Dukakis
and his running mate, Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen.
   Senate Minority leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., said that regardless of
whom Republican George Bush picks as his vice presidential
candidate, ``you're going to find only shades of difference in our
philosophy, not this chasm you find between Dukakis on the one hand
and Lloyd Bentsen on the other.''
   Dukakis and Bentsen have opposing views on subjects ranging from
Contra aid and the Reagan economic program to key defense issues
such as the MX missile, the Strategic Defense Initiative and the B1
bomber. Dukakis has said he doesn't want Bentsen to be a mere clone.
   Dole and Rep. Lynn Martin, R-Ill., held a news conference at a
downtown hotel to announce the opening of a GOP media center,
making Republican leaders available to reporters ``when they need a
quote, an opinion or a different perspective to round out a
story.'' The operation will run each day of the Democratic
convention next Monday through Thursday.
   The planned speakers includes members of Congress, governors,
White House budget chief Jim Miller and others.
   ``We are not here to be negative,'' Dole insisted. ``We are here
to be comparative.''
   Calling the presidential election a crossroads for America, Dole
said, ``We can build on the stable, record-setting economic pace of
the Reagan-Bush years, we can continue to pursue peace through
strength, or we can head down a road already traveled,'' Dole said.
   ``Do we want to go back to 1980? Do we want a reunion with
double-digit inflation, sky-high interest rates, massive
unemployment and America held hostage overseas? I don't think so,''
the senator said.
   ``We Republicans have listened to America and the last thing the
American people want is a radical, wrenching 180-degree change in
direction,'' Dole added.
   The news conference also highlighted differences among
Republicans when the two politicians were asked whether they think
President Reagan should sign a bill _ which the administration
strongly opposes _ requiring advance notice to workers of plant
closings.
   Ms. Martin said she opposes the bill, but Dole said that if he
were president, he might let it become law without his signature
because a veto probably would be overridden. Polls show that a
majority of Americans support the bill, and Democrats plan to make
it a campaign issue if Reagan vetoes it.
   ``In a way, you'd like it to go away cause it's not an easy
issue to explain,'' Rep. Martin commented.
   Dole also took the opportunity to advertise his availability as
a possible running mate with Bush.
   While decrying the differences between Dukakis and Bentsen, Dole
said the Republicans did not have that problem. ``I know. I looked
for sharp differences in my primary contest with George Bush _ you
couldn't find them, whether it was the line-item veto or balanced
budget amendment or a strong defense or SDI _ they weren't there.
   ``You can certainly find them in looking over the comparison
between my good friend Lloyd Bentsen and Gov. Dukakis,'' Dole said.
   While running against Bush, Dole complained repeatedly that the
vice president had not left his mark on foreign policy issues and
other matters.
   Dole also mentioned Ms. Martin as a possible running mate with
Bush. She, in turn, mentioned Dole's wife, Elizabeth, as well as
the senator, as possible candidates.
</TEXT>
