<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     07-15 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0655</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It wasn't the most pleasant experience, but
7-year-old Jessica Lafferty's reward for her pain was an unassisted
triple play.
   Jessica was playing shortstop for the Maroon team in Thursday's
Chester-YMCA T-ball league game against the Royal Blues.
   With runners on first and second, a Royal Blue batter hit a
sharp line drive that struck Jessica in the chest. Jessica doubled
over in pain, but in the process pinned the ball against her body
for the first out.
   Hurt and disoriented, Jessica stumbled toward her coaches, who
were standing at second base. In the process, she recorded the
second out by colliding with the Royal Blue runner who had strayed
off second base.
   Jessica, still cradling the ball and in obvious pain, eventually
reached second, where she found the Royal Blue runner who had been
on first. The player had not tagged up, and Jessica ran into him
for the third out.
   Jessica, flashing an occasional smile between sniffles, was able
to stay in the game.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Matar is up to his neck in Styrofoam
peanuts, so he must have had a birthday.
   Not that every July 14th it's peanuts _ sometimes there's an
elephant standing in his front yard. Or a couple of bathing
beauties serenading him. Or a 4,000-pound pet rock perched near his
house.
   The whacky birthday gifts come from John's brother, Sam Matar of
Carmel, Calif.
   The brothers have been trying to outdo each other for 14 years,
so it should have been no surprise that something was up when John
_ who gives his age as 39 _ unlocked the front door Thursday.
   ``This stuff just rolled out on me,'' he said.
   Brother Sam had arranged for 95 huge bags _ a full semiload _ of
the peanut-shaped packing material to be deposited in John's house.
   ``My house is just loaded with it,'' John said. ``It's neck
high, right up to my neck.''
   While this was his nuttiest gift, he said, the one he liked best
was the 2{-carat diamond he got a few years back. Of course, it was
embedded in a huge block of concrete.
   The following February, as Sam's birthday approached, John
arranged to have a truck full of balloons parked in the Las Vegas
casino where Sam was staying.
   ``I sent a note saying you gave me 2{ carats, so I'm going to
top you, here's four,'' John recalled. So Sam dug through the
balloons and found a small black box buried in the semi.
   ``In it was four wilting carrots,'' John said, with a note of
triumph in his voice.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WATERTOWN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
