<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 2206EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BeachDriving     07-15 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beach Driving,0645</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Permits Four-Wheel Drive Vehicles On Cape Cod Seashore</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has upheld Cape Cod National
Seashore guidelines allowing off-road vehicles on an eight-mile
stretch of beach, defeating conservationists who claim the vehicles
threaten the fragile ecosystem.
   U.S. District Judge David S. Nelson ruled that off-road vehicle
driving on Cape Cod's northern beaches ``is an appropriate public
use ... and does not adversely affect the Seashore's natural,
scenic and aesthetic values.''
   The Conservation Law Foundation, Massachusetts Audubon Society
and the Sierra Club, which sued over dune buggy use in 1981,
appealed the decision to the 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   The conservationists contend that vehicles threaten shore bird
nesting and the tender vegetation that stems erosion of the dunes.
They also say vehicles destroy the natural beauty and interfere
with other beach-goers.
   But Nelson said in a ruling signed late last month that dune
nesting and beach aesthetics are unaffected by the vehicles, and
that conflicts between drivers and other beach users are minimal.
   Under amended rules issued in 1985, vehicles are limited to the
eight-mile stretch from Hatches Harbor to High Head in Truro.
Winter driving is prohibited and the beach is closed when tides,
beach configurations or bird nesting make the route impassable.
   Just one of the Seashore's six public beaches, Race Point, is
open to drivers, who must get a permit, have their vehicle
inspected and watch a videotape on ecology. The Seashore issues
about 2,000 permits a year, Cape Cod National Seashore chief ranger
Tony Bonanno said Friday.
   All dune areas are off limits except a few tracts with deeded
access rights.
   The ruling ``reinforces the fact that we have taken the
appropriate steps to meet the natural resource objectives and meet
the public interest,'' Cape Cod National Seashore chief ranger Tony
Bonanno said Friday.
   The Cape Cod National Seashore, created by the 1961 federal
Seashore Act, enacted a resource management plan in August 1981 to
control increasing numbers of beach-goers and wheeled vehicles. The
three conservation groups sued the day the plan took effect.
   The original plan allowed vehicles on 12 miles of beach from
April to November, and on a 25-mile stretch in Eastham in winter.
After an order from Nelson, the plan was amended in 1985.
   ``The court is basically saying, yes, the '85 plan is a
resonable plan, it addresses adequately the balance of different
uses, accommodates all visitors to the Seashore and protects its
resources,'' Bonanno said.
   Conservationists say off-road vehicle use is prohibited under
the Seashore Act, which bans action that ``would be incompatible
with the preservation of the unique flora and fauna or the
physiographic conditions now prevailing.''
   But the act permits recreational development _ for activities
such as fishing, camping and sailing _ that is environmentally
``compatible'' and ``appropriate'' to the beach. The government can
ban off-road vehicle use if found to have adverse effects on soil,
vegetation or wildlife habitats.
   The law foundation said policing drivers is difficult, that even
small incursions on tender dune grass are harmful and that the
Seashore has handed over one-fifth of the beach to drivers, who
comprise just 3 percent of its 6 million annual users.
   ``The law did not envision the rampant off-road vehicle use that
has gone on since the Seashore was created,'' foundation staff
scientist Paul Hauge said Friday.
   Bonanno said rangers last year filed 236 reports of dune buggy
violations, issuing about 100 fines of $50 and 100 warnings.
   Seashore officials said most beach drivers are fishermen needing
access to the tip of Race Point.
   A National Park Service survey found that only a small
percentage of Seashore visitors opposed vehicle use or said they
were displaced by it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880715-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 2209EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Children'sHome     07-15 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Children's Home,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bethel Home for Children Hearings Conclude</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUCEDALE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifteen residents of the Bethel
Children's Home were placed in state custody when a judge found
they had been subjected to abuse from a director who has said he
relies on paddlings and exercise to reform.
   A 16th child was released to parents.
   Youth Court Judge Robert Oswald ruled Thursday 11 of the
children had been abused, three abused and neglected and one
neglected.
   Oswald's rulings were the latest action in a feud between the
state and the home's founder, the Rev. Herman Fountain.
   Fountain claims the First Amendment and its separation of church
and state shield Bethel from state intervention. State Welfare
Commissioner Thomas Brittain wants to use the case to persuade the
Legislature to require the registration or licensing of religious
boarding homes.
   Mississippi is one of five states that has no such law.
   The 16 children were among 72 Oswald ordered removed from the
home in June. That followed his decision that a 14-year-old runaway
had been abused and neglected.
   An unknown number of residents fled when officials arrived at
the home June 10. Fountain has told the media he had about 120
children at the home, most from out of state. But he has refused to
comply with a court order to provide a list of their names. About
50 children haven't been accounted for.
   Fountain, who has said he uses licks with a switch or exercise
to control and reform children, and two of his assistants are being
fined $500 each per day for refusing to answer questions in court.
   Two days of hearings were held this week concerning discipline
and care of the 16 children. Most of the other children already
have been released to their parents or guardians.
   State officials contend some of the practices at the 10-year-old
institution constitute abuse and that children have been medically
neglected while at Bethel.
   Youth Court hearings are normally closed to the news media, but
Oswald opened the hearings on the condition the children not be
identified.
</TEXT>
