<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Holocaust     07-15 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Holocaust,0654</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conference Cites Long Anti-Jewish Tradition In Christianity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conference on the Holocaust on Friday accused
Christian churches of centuries of anti-Jewish teaching, and one
U.S. expert said the tradition helps explain why Nazi genocide went
unchecked in Christian Germany.
   ``The failure of European civilization to stem the tide of evil
during the Holocaust makes it critically important to counteract
historical and traditional Christian anti-Jewish teaching,'' said a
statement issued by the international conference.
   The statement concluded a weeklong gathering of 500 academics,
concentration camp survivors, theologians and teachers. The
conference met in the university town of Oxford before moving to
London on Friday.
   Christian churchmen, including Britain's Roman Catholic Cardinal
Basil Hume, joined in prayers for the Nazis' 6 million Jewish
victims, and conference organizers read out messages from leaders
of the United States, France, Britain, Israel and the European
Economic Community.
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl received a standing ovation
for a message in which he acknowledged German responsibility for
the Holocaust and said: ``We Germans are prepared to live with this
terrible truth.''
   President Ronald Reagan said, ``The words `never again' must
ever be the pledge of all who pause in remembrance of those who
have perished.''
   A major theme of the conference was how Christians allowed the
World War II slaughter of Jews to happen.
   Delegates focused on longtime Christian church teachings that
the Jews were responsible for the murder of Jesus Christ and were
condemned to wander without a homeland. Most churches have since
stopped espousing this belief, including the Catholic Church in
1965.
   The Rev. Franklin Littel, an American Methodist minister and a
leading academic expert on the Holocaust, said that despite ``an
acute rise in sensitivity (by Christian churches toward Jews) in
the past 25 years ... the problem remains.''
   ``Why do you suppose the liberal Protestant churches find it so
hard to come to terms with Israel?'' asked Littel, a former
professor of religion at Temple University in Philadelphia and at
the Hebrew University in Jerusalem.
   ``It is because they are used to teaching that the Jew is a
loser,'' Littel said in an interview. ``They've been teaching for
centuries that he is supposed to wander, supposed to be miserable.''
   Littel said that in 1936, Germany's Catholic bishops
courageously protested the persecution of Jews.
   But he said the Nazi response was ``what are you complaining
about _ we're just doing what your churches have been teaching
about all along.''
   The Anglican bishop of Oxford, the Rt. Rev. Richard Harris, said
Christians had to examine ``how it is that at the heart of a
so-called Christian civilization, such unspeakable atrocities could
be perpetrated.''
   Harris heads an Anglican committee which will submit a new
policy document on the church's relations with Jews to the Lambeth
Conference, an international gathering of Anglican bishops opening
Monday.
   Several participants at the conference paid tribute to
Christians who helped Jews during the Holocaust.
   Historian Yehuda Bauer noted that 24 British doctors, only one
of whom was a Jew, went to treat those being liberated from
Auschwitz concentration camp. Many of the prisoners were known to
have typhoid and none of the doctors who volunteered had received
immunizations. As a result, many of them died.
   The conference was sponsored by publisher Robert Maxwell, 65, a
Czechoslovak-born Jew who fled to Britain as a teen-ager, and his
French Protestant wife, Elisabeth.
   Maxwell asked delegates to stand and applaud after reading out
Kohl's message.
   ``Germans became guilty of that crime (the Holocaust) as
individuals, but they are collectively liable for the injustice
committed in their name,'' Kohl, a Catholic, said in his message.
   ``No one can rule out the possiblity of comparable atrodcities
happening again,'' Kohl's message added. ``It must not be
forgotten.''
</TEXT>
