<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Moscow-Visas     07-15 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moscow-Visas,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Pressed To Lift Suspension of Soviet Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-three senators and nine House members
on Friday called for an immediate end to the State Department's
suspension of refugee processing, which has left thousands of
prospective immigrants to the United States temporarily stranded in
the Soviet Union.
   The senators told President Reagan in a letter: ``This decision
sends a terrible signal to those seeking freedom all over the
world, and could give the Soviets the opportunity to claim that it
is America and not the Soviet Union which is impeding emigration.''
   The House members, all members of the House Judiciary
subcommittee on refugees, asked Secretary of State George P. Shultz
either to find the estimated $10 million required to resume refugee
processing at the U.S. Embassy in Moscow or to ask Congress for
additional funds.
   The suspension went into effect on July 4 and is scheduled to
last until Oct.1.
   It came after a sudden surge in the number of visa applications
by Soviet citizens, mostly Armenians and Jews, and after the Reagan
administration had increased the annual number of refugees the
United States would accomodate.
   The Soviet Union relaxed emigration policies recently and in
June the U.S. embassy issued some 2,000 refugee visas, more than
the total approved for all of the 1987 fiscal year which began Oct.
1, 1986.
   ``In light of the promises this country has made to welcome and
resettle thousands of emigres from the Soviet Union, the suspension
should be lifted immediately,'' the House members told Shultz in a
letter.
   They said the suspension will result in the ``forced
displacement of many families who have already lost their homes and
their jobs, and who, in many cases, have made long journeys to
Moscow to begin refugee processing.''
   ``After urging the Soviets to open the gate of emigration, it is
important that we find this funding for refugee assistance, the
letter said. ``To do otherwise could leave thousands of people in a
state of uncertainty and desperation, and send a disturbing signal
that the United States is unwilling to back up its commitment to
accomodate those seeking refuge.''
   Rep. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., who initiated the House letter,
said his attention was drawn to the situation when a couple with
four children he been attempting to help leave the Soviet Union
were told the Moscow embassy could not process their applications
for three months.
   Schumer said two members of the family of Zoltan and Pepa
Forkosh are sick and two are infants.
   He said they had traveled to Moscow from the Ukraine, have been
compelled to move into an expensive apartment and are rapidly using
up their funds.
   Other signers of the House letter were Reps. Patrick L.
Swindall, R-Ga.; Bruce A. Morrison, D-Conn.; Howard L. Berman,
D-N.Y.; D. French Slaughter, R-Va.; Hamilton Fish Jr., R-N.Y.;
Barney Frank, D-Mass.; Bill McCollom, R-Fla.; and John Bryant,
D-Texas.
   Senators signing the letter to Reagan were Frank Lautenberg,
D-N.J.; John Stennis, D-Miss.; Robert W. Kasten Jr., R-Wis.; Daniel
K. Inouye, D-Hawaii; Arlen Specter, R-Pa.; Dennis DeConcini,
D-Ariz.; Quentin Burdick, D-N.D.; James J. Exon, D-Neb.; Paul
Simon, D-Ill.; Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M.; Larry Pressler, R-S.D.; Bob
Graham, D-Fla.; Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.; Harry Reid,
D-Nev.; Carl Levin, D-Mich.; Lowell Weicker, R-Conn.; Jay
Rockefeller, D-W.Va.; John Heinz, R-Pa.; George J. Mitchell,
D-Maine; Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt.; Tom Harkin, D-Iowa; Howard W.
Metzenbaum, D-Ohio; and Tim Wirth, D-Colo.
</TEXT>
