<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SmellResearch     07-15 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smell Research,440</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release at 6 p .m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Baltimore Scientists Find Key Protein In Detecting Aromas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A complex protein produced in a nasal gland
has been identified by researchers as the chemical messenger that
carries aromas to the odor-sensing nerves of the nose.
   Dr. Solomon Snyder of Johns Hopkins University School of
Medicine in Baltimore said Friday he and three other researchers
have cloned the gene that gives instructions for the creation of
the protein and may one day be able to use the protein to sharpen
the sense of smell.
   The protein, called the odorant binding protein or OBP, is
secreted by the lateral nasal gland and then carried by a duct to
the tip of the nose, Snyder said. When air is inhaled, the OBP is
sprayed as fine mist into the air that flows into the nose, he said.
   Snyder said the protein binds with airborne molecules as they
are inhaled and is then carried past a nerve bundle that picks up
the chemical message of the odor.
   ``The nerve endings are way back, high in the nose,'' Snyder
said in a telephone interview. ``Only a small portion of the nose
has these receptors.''
   When the OBP comes in contact with the receptors, the nerves
interpret the chemistry of the OBP as a particular smell.
   Snyder said the precise mechanism of how the nerves can
distinguish between different smells, such as sweet and sour, is
not yet understood. He said what is detected as a fragrance may
actually be caused by the chemical reaction of the OBP mixed with
the fragrance molecule.
   By cloning the gene that produces the OBP, Snyder said his team
should be able to produce large quantities of the protein and
conduct further studies into the sense of smell, one of the least
understood of the senses.
   Use of OBP may be of medical significance in restoring lost
appetite or helping patients who have totally lost the sense of
smell.
   ``This could help the elderly regain their appetite,'' said
Snyder. ``As people age, they lose their sense of smell'' and this
often is the reason that older people stop eating as they should.
   By spraying OBP into the nose, he said, it may help restore some
of the sense of smell.
   Snyder said much more research must be conducted before
specific, clinical uses for the OBP are found.
   A report on the study was published Friday in Science, the
journal of the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
   Others on the OBP research team are Jonathan Pevsner, also of
Johns Hopkins, and Randall R. Reed and Paul G. Feinstein of the
Howard Hughes Medical Institute.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
