<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DroughtSweetCorn     07-15 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Sweet Corn,0170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought-Stricken Community Imports Sweet Corn For Weekend Festival</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LODI, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lingering drought has forced organizers of
Lodi's seventh annual Sweet Corn Festival to import corn for the
event all the way from down South.
   ``You can't find anything home-grown right now; it is coming out
of Alabama and Georgia,'' said Jerry Miller, produce manager at a
store in Medina, who obtained the corn through a Cleveland food
terminal.
   In wetter years, festival organizers have had to go no farther
than Bill Richardson's Medina County farm to get sweet corn.
   But Richardson has no edible sweet corn to offer this year.
   Richardson provided sweet corn to past festivals for free but
this year, festival organizers paid $9 each for 50 cases of 45 ears.
   Miller said that in a normal year, he could have obtained corn
from an Ohio farmer for about half that price.
   Festival visitors, however, will still pay the 75 cents an ear
charged last summer.
</TEXT>
