<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Carter     07-15 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carter,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carter Says Communication Key for Dukakis, Jackson</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Wrtier</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Carter, declaring his services
as a mediator unneeded, said Friday that the relatively minor
differences between Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson could vanish
``if the two men understood each other a little bit better.''
   ``The compatability between Jackson and Dukakis and their
followers are so overwhelming that the differences are relatively
insignicant,'' Carter said in an interview with The Associated
Press at the Carter Presidential Center.
   ``I don't think they need any mediation,'' he said. ``I think
what is needed is to just have a better means of communication
directly with one another and to get any misunderstandings resolved
as early as possible in the convention.''
   Jackson, who sought to be named Dukakis' vice presidential
candidate, seemed miffed when the pick went to Sen. Lloyd Bentsen
of Texas and word got out before Dukakis personally relayed the
decison to Jackson. He said Thursday that he had asked Carter to
act as mediator between his and Dukakis' camps.
   However, Dukakis rejected that idea Friday, and Jackson aides
also expressed doubts about it.
   Carter said if any mediation is needed the role should go to
Democratic National Committee chairman Paul Kirk but that he might
get involved if Kirk asked him to. However, Kirk also said he saw
no role for a mediator.
   The former president said he did not see ill will over the vice
presidential choice lasting much past the convention. ``That's one
of the reasons for the convention, to resolve differences within
the party. It is not unprecedented,'' Carter said.
   ``When the Rev. Jackson called me ... we talked about the
procedures that I always used when I was running for president or
when I was in the White House.
   ``When I had a major decision to make ... I brought into the
White House key leaders of the black community, who were also my
political supporters. I asked them for advice and I listened very
carefully to them. There was never any doubt that in a very genuine
way they were a part of the deliberations of my government.''
   Carter said he thought the choice of Bentsen could help Dukakis
in the South against the expected Republican presidential
candidate, Vice President George Bush.
   He described Bentsen as ``a man who provides a philosophical
balance to the ticket'' and ``who has had a lot to do with minority
problems with Spanish and blacks in Texas, and I think he's
well-respected in the South.''
   Carter said he plans no major role for himself at the convention
or during the campaign. He is to address the convention Monday
night.
   If during the campaign incorrect statements are made about
events to which he was a party, or has special knowledge, Carter
said, ``I will reserve the right to set the record straight.''
</TEXT>
