<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1811EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Korb     07-15 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korb,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lehman Seeks Dismissal Of Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for former Navy Secretary John F.
Lehman Jr. asked a federal judge on Friday to dismiss a lawsuit
filed by an executive of a defense contracting company who says he
lost his job after publicly criticizing government spending.
   Other defendants in the lawsuit are Lehman's one-time deputies,
defense consultant Melvyn R. Paisley and assistant Navy Secretary
Everett Pyatt, and Carl Smith, a staffer with the Senate Armed
Services Committee.
   In the lawsuit, Lawrence J. Korb claims officials at Raytheon
Co. removed him from his position as vice president in the nation's
capital after they received complaints from Paisley and Pyatt about
Korb's public statements.
   Korb, who joined Raytheon in 1985, participated in a press
conference in February 1986 at which he suggested the Pentagon
could maintain a strong force with a smaller budget.
   After that, Paisley and Pyatt called Korb's superiors,
suggesting they tell the former Pentagon official to stop speaking
out against the president's budget.
   The Pentagon's inspector general concluded in a report released
in November 1986 that while Lehman did not direct Pyatt and Paisley
to called Raytheon, he erred in condoning their actions.
   The report said the three then-Navy officials were wrong in
complaining to Raytheon ``with the intention of restricting Dr.
Korb from making public statements.''
   But Lehman's attorney, Robert Bennett, told U.S. District Judge
Claude Hilton that there is ``simply no case against Lehman ... The
calls were made by two of his assistant secretaries.''
   Moreover, he said Navy officials have every right to express
their views to defense contractors.
   But Kate Martin, Korb's attorney, said that ``what these people
were doing was wrong ... putting pressure on Dr. Korb to keep
quiet.''
   Martin works for the American Civil Liberties Union, which is
representing Korb in his lawsuit in which he seeks $500,000 in
damages. Korb is now associated with the Brookings Institution, a
liberal think tank.
   Hilton said he would rule shortly on whether to dismiss the
lawsuit.
   The lawsuit is not related to the massive investigation into
defense procurement practices. Paisley is a key figure in that
probe, which centers on allegations that consultants paid bribes to
Pentagon officials to obtain classified information used to clinch
multimillion-dollar contracts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
