<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-UnitedNations     07-15 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-United Nations,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Urges Further U.N. Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Friday the United
Nations must make ``further progress on reform'' to satisfy
concerns that have prompted the United States to withhold dues from
the world organization.
   Reagan's remarks to U.N. Secretary General Perez de Cuellar were
relayed to reporters by White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
after a meeting between the two officials.
   The United States has withheld about $44 million in current
contributions to the United Nations because of objections to its
budget and personnel procedures.
   ``The president said that the U.S. recognizes its obligations to
the U.N. but that further progress on reform was necessary to meet
the concerns of Congress, which the administration shares,''
Fitzwater said.
   Fitzwater said that Reagan hopes the problem of overdue U.S.
contributions to the world organization ``can be worked out.''
   The White House spokesman listed three areas in which the United
States desires U.N. reforms: the U.N. budget-making process, the
need for a 15 percent cut in U.N. personnel and the practice of
short-term contracting of Soviet U.N. employees so that they remain
under their government's control instead of becoming U.N. career
employees.
   Perez de Cuellar warned last last month that U.N. budget arrears
of $691 million, including $467 million run up by the United
States, would leave the organization out of money, with all its
reserves exhausted, by late October or early November. He was
expected to warn Reagan that the United Nations might be unable to
meet its payroll or other obligations.
   ``The secretary general was concerned that we have not been
forthcoming with our share,'' Fitzwater said.
   The $44 million was an amount the Reagan administration sought
to pay last year but Congress held up until Reagan certified
progress on reforming the U.N. budget decision-making process and
the two other areas of concern.
   Richard S. Williamson, U.S. assistant secretary of state for
international organizations, has described overall progress on U.N.
reforms as encouraging but suggested the demands of Congress have
not yet been fully met on the budget-decision making process.
   Posing for photographs with Perez de Cuellar, Reagan
acknowledged to reporters that recently there has been ``some
problem again with the Congress on this.''
   As the richest U.N. member, the United States is earmarked for
25 percent of the U.N. general budget. It has pressed for more
weighted voting by the major financial contributors on the U.N.
budget.
   Fitzwater said Reagan praised the secretary general for the U.N.
role in the Geneva accords on Afghanistan, saying that without U.N.
participation the agreement would not have been possible.
   Perez de Cuellar said the international organization would
continue to be active in Afghan refugee resettlement. The Soviet
Union and the Afghan government in Kabul have been accusing
Pakistan and the United States of violating the accord with
continuing help for the anti-Soviet guerrillas.
   Fitzwater said Reagan expressed regret over the shooting down of
an Iranian airliner by the U.S. cruiser Vincennes and thanked Perez
de Cuellar for his efforts to implement the yea-old Security
Council Resolution cutting off arms supplies to Iran and Iraq in
the Persian Gulf war.
   ``The president stressed the importance of the growing U.N. role
in controlling international production and trafficking of illicit
drugs,'' the spokesman said.
   The United Nations ``certainly can be influential in urging
other countries to take action in helping us with our initiatives
to eliminate (narcotics) crops and in enforcement measures against
drug traffic,'' Fitzwater told reporters.
   Perez de Cuellar flew back to New York after the White House
meeting without speaking to reporters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
