<HEAD>Food Shortages, Illnesses Rampant in Disputed Region</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 18th pvs, Asked what ... UPDATING with
other strike effects. PICKS up 19th graf pvs, Armenian activists .
..</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Food shortages and illnesses caused by stress are
plaguing Armenians living in a disputed region trying to break away
from Azerbaijan, a resident and the state-run media reported Friday.
   One resident, a journalist with the state broadcasting
authority, claimed Azerbaijani authorities were preventing food
from getting to the region, Nagorno-Karabakh.
   ``We are under a virtual economic blockade,'' said the
journalist. ``The Azerbaijanis are trying to morally kill our
movement, to strike down our just demands.''
   The official news agency Tass, however, blamed the supply
problems in Nagorno-Karabakh on a nearly 2-month-old strike. Tass
said more than 130 freight cars and more than 300 containers of
food have backed up at the railway station in Stepanakert,
Nagorno-Karabakh's main city.
   ``There are no more fruits or vegetables in our shops,'' said
the reporter, who spoke on condition he not be identified by name.
``We have almost no economic ties now with Azerbaijan.''
   Ethnic Armenians make up more than three-quarters of
Nagorno-Karabakh's 160,000 people and most are Christian.
   They have complained for months of economic, cultural and
religious discrimination by the Azerbaijan government.
   Early this year, they began protesting and demanded that control
of the region, given to predominantly Moslem Azerbaijan in 1923, be
transferred to the neighboring republic of Armenia.
   In February, 32 people were killed in ethnic riots in Sumgait,
Azerbaijan, 26 of them Armenians.
   Tass said residents were suffering because of the tensions in
the region.
   ``The population of Stepanakert is exhausted by the situation
that has arisen. People have forgotten about weddings and family
holidays. The incidence of illnesses caused by excessive stress has
grown,'' the news agency reported.
   It said an Armenian resident was being sought after murdering
his wife and two relatives, seriously wounding a 2-year-old child
of his sister-in-law and trying to kill his son. Tass said the
suspect, G.S. Adamyan, has a criminal record but that the motive
for the attack was not known.
   The journalist said Azerbaijaini authorities refused Thursday to
allow a plane of the state-run airlines Aeroflot from the Armenian
capital of Yerevan to land in Stepanakert. Instead, the airliner
touched down in the Armenian city of Goris, he said.
   The Azerbaijanis, the journalist added, have suspended bus
service between Stepanakert and the Armenian cities of Kirovakan
and Kafan, but buses have been leaving Stepanakert for Yerevan with
a police escort.
   The legislature of the Delaware-size region voted Tuesday to
secede and join Armenia. But the Azerbaijani government voided the
decision within hours.
   A general strike in solidarity with Nagorno-Karabakh residents,
begun July 4, was continuing in Armenia, sources said.
   Khovik Vasilyan, an Armenian activist, said by telephone from
Yerevan that most of the factories in the city of 1.1 million
people were still on strike but that transportation was functioning
normally.
   Asked what the prospects were for resolving the 5-month-old
dispute, a woman reached by phone in Yerevan sighed and said: ``I
don't know what will happen. We are in a difficult situation.''
   Soviet television reported Friday that many workers at a Moscow
alarm clock factory were idle and not receiving pay because an
Armenian factory that makes electronic parts was on strike. The
newscast portrayed life as normal in Susha, the second biggest city
in Nagorno-Karabakh, despite what it said were rumors in
Stepanakert that Azerbaijani residents had attacked Armenians there.
   Armenian activists have scheduled a rally outside Yerevan's
repository of ancient Armenian manuscripts for Saturday night.
   They believe the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the highest
legislative body in the Soviet government, will meet Monday and
they hope it will consider the Nagorno-Karabakh question. Soviet
officials have said such a meeting is likely but have not given a
date.
   Pravda, the Communist Party daily, said Thursday the work
stoppage in Armenia had cost $65 million in lost production and
that $29 million worth of construction had not been completed.
   Tass said that about 20,000 Azerbaijanis living in Armenia had
fled to Azerbaijan and that as of Wednesday, 7,265 Armenians who
once lived in Sumgait and other Azerbaijan cities had returned to
Armenia.
</TEXT>
