<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis-Budget     07-15 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Budget,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Defends Use of Taxes and Borrowing to Close State Deficit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis defended his use of taxes
and borrowing to cover a state budget shortfall as he awaited final
legislative action on the plan before heading to the Democratic
convention.
   In an interview Friday with The Associated Press in his
Statehouse office, Dukakis rejected any comparisons between his
borrowing and the federal deficit spending of the Reagan
administration.
   ``Obviously, we're not going to do anything around here that
jeopardizes our credit rating. If all goes well, we'll come out of
this with some end-of-year surplus,'' Dukakis predicted.
   He also defended his recent signing of a $24 million sales tax
on cigarettes on the grounds that it would pay for the first year
phase-in of his universal health care plan.
   ``If we didn't have the health care bill, we wouldn't have
needed that. Frankly, I think that's a modest price to pay for the
first universal health care bill in the history of this country,''
the governor said.
   He acknowledged, however, that the cigarette tax would not pay
for universal health insurance in later years when the program
becomes more expensive. He did not address himself to the other
revenue measures proposed to shore up next year's state budget.
   Dukakis did show a willingness to tangle with George Bush if the
expected Republican presidential nominee accuses him of being a
tax-raiser.
   ``Let 'em do it,'' said Dukakis, who recently accused Bush of
violating a no-new-taxes pledge by supporting a federal
catastrophic illness health care bill that calls for $6 billion in
new revenues.
   ``I haven't heard much the last week or two from the vice
president on the subject, since his no-tax pledge has disappeared.
And I don't think you're going to hear much,'' Dukakis said.
   As he spoke Friday afternoon, an $11.75 billion budget for the
current fiscal year was awaiting his signature. Dukakis said he
would use his line-item veto to reduce the total, but he would not
say how.
   At the same time, Dukakis is awaiting a package of bills
designed to close a deficit in last year's budget that ranges from
the administration's estimate of $370 million to as much as $470
million projected by some legislators.
   Dukakis has proposed closing the budget gap through converting
some $200 million in operating expenses into long-term bonds,
tapping a $27 million pension system surplus and diverting $50
million in surplus lottery proceeds from local government.
   In addition, to shore up next year's budget, the governor is
seeking to raise more than $200 million by closing corporate tax
``loopholes,'' re-coupling the state income tax with federal law
and collecting unclaimed bottle deposits.
   The governor traced his budget problems to an unanticipated _
and, he says, unforeseeble _ downturn in state tax collections this
spring.
   ``Remember this,'' he said, ``The Revenue Advisory Board, as
recently as three months ago, gave us a revised report, which
forecast a $70 million shortfall for FY88 and a $40 million
shortfall for FY89.
   ``Now, if that revised forecast had been accurate, it would have
been like a day at the beach,'' Dukakis said.
   According to the governor, he and legislative leaders made a
decision last year to take advantage of the now-evaporated state
budget surplus by paying cash for some highway and building repair
projects that normally would have been funded through bonds.
   Now, faced with a shortfall, Dukakis said he is simply shifting
the funds back into a category where they belonged all along.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
