<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DefenseProbe-Contracts     07-15 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Contracts,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Announces `Special Procedures' for Future Contracts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a new reaction to the ongoing Pentagon
fraud investigation, the Defense Department announced Friday it is
requiring ``special procedures'' for future contracts with 16
defense firms.
   The procedures will include a certification that none of the
companies improperly obtained inside information relating to
contracts, the Pentagon said.
   The contractors also will be required to include a clause in
contracts permitting the government to recapture profits if it is
later determined the company won the contract through ``illegal or
improper activity,'' the Pentagon said.
   The announcement results from the investigation into allegations
that private defense consultants, many of whom are former military
or Pentagon officials, paid bribes to current Pentagon employees
for inside information about contracts.
   That information could be crucial in winning contracts worth
hundreds of millions of dollars. No charges have yet been filed in
the two-year-old case, which became public a month ago when search
warrants were served across the country on a number of contractors
and consultants.
   The Pentagon announcement said the procedures will affect future
contracts worth more than $100,000 and is ``an interim measure
designed to protect the government's interests.''
   The Defense Department said the list of 16 companies could be
expanded ``as additional information becomes available.''
   The Pentagon said it was acting because the contractors, or
their subsidiaries, ``either were the subject of search warrants in
connection with the ongoing procurement investigation, or other
official information currently available that requires
certification of business integrity prior to awarding of future
contracts.''
   The list includes some of the nation's largest defense
contractors, including McDonnell Douglas, Northrop, Unisys,
Teledyne Electronics, and United Technologies.
   Two weeks ago, Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci announced he
was suspending contracts in nine military programs worth $1 billion
because of the possibility they may have been tainted. He said he
was acting on the basis of information contained in an affidavit
unsealed by a federal court in Dallas.
   Carlucci rescinded that action Monday and told Congress a review
of the contracts had found no problems with the pacts.
   But he also said action should be taken as a warning to
contractors that the Pentagon would act if questions were raised
about future contracts.
   Carlucci and other Pentagon officials have said the Pentagon has
the legal authority to recoup profits if the money turns out to
have been earned through some illegality. But members of Congress
have been pushing for inclusion of a separate clause in future
contracts to spell out that right more clearly.
   The firms affected by Friday's announcement include Armtec Inc.,
Palatka, Fla.; Cubic Corp., San Diego, Calif.; Emhart Corp.,
Hartford, Conn.; Executive Resource Associates, Arlington, Va.;
Hazeltine Corp., Commack, N.Y.; Kane Paper Corp., Baldwin, N.Y.;
Litton Data Systems, Van Nuys, Calif.; Loral Aircraft, Akron, Ohio.
   McDonnell Douglas, St. Louis; Northrop Corp., Newbury Park,
Calif.; Teledyne Electronics, Newbury Park, Calif.; Unisys Corp.,
Detroit, Mich.; United Technologies, Hartford, Conn.; Varian
Associates, Inc., Palo Alto, Calif.; Whittaker Corp., Farmington,
Ariz.; Zubier Enterprises, Harrisburg, Pa.
</TEXT>
