<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Germany-Solzhenitsyn 2ndLd-Writethru a0735 07-15 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Solzhenitsyn, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0735,0446</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs, RECASTING to emphasize denial and
UPDATING with quotes from Mrs. Solzhenitsyn; picks up 7th graf,
Solzhenitsyn incurred...</NOTE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE BONN, West Germany</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Natalya Solzhenitsyn, the wife of Soviet
emigre writer Alexander Solzhenitsyn, on Friday denied a German
radio report that she and her husband would return to their
homeland for a visit and that his works would be published there.
   ``Everything is (a) lie. Everything is false,'' Mrs.
Solzhenitsyn said in a telephone interview with The Associated
Press from her home in Cavendish, Vt.
   The Munich-based Bayerischer Rundfunk radio station said
Solzhenitsyn and his wife planned to visit the Soviet Union in
November or December and that the Soviet Union wanted to publish
all his works, including the novella ``Cancer Ward'' and ``The
Gulag Archipelago.''
   It said the information came from its correspondent in New York
City.
   In an interview with The Associated Press, the New York-based
correspondent said Solzhenitsyn's wife told him by telephone
Wednesday that Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev had written two
letters to her husband with offers to return and to have
Solzhenitsyn's works published in the Soviet Union. The
correspondent asked that his name not be used.
   Mrs. Solzhenitsyn said, ``I never talked to (an) unnamed
reporter from New York.''
   ``I cannot confirm (the report),'' she said. She also said she
could not speculate on the report's origin or motive. ``I have no
idea. I have no comment at all.''
   Earlier, Mrs. Solzhenitsyn, who rarely speaks to reporters,
spoke to an aide to U.S. Rep. James Jeffords, R-Vt., and denied
that her husband had received letters from Gorbachev.
   The aide, Bernice Murray, quoted her as saying, ``It's a lie.
The interviews never took place ... It's absurd.''
   Solzhenitsyn incurred the wrath of the Soviet Union's Communist
leadership with novels such as ``One Day in the Life of Ivan
Denisovich,'' ``Cancer Ward'' and ``The First Circle,'' as well as
the non-fiction work ``The Gulag Archipelago,'' an expose of terror
and hopelessness in Soviet labor camps.
   He won the Nobel Prize for Literature in 1970.
   In February 1974, Solzhenitsyn was arrested, formally accused of
treason, stripped of his citizenship and deported to the West.
   In June, Sergei P. Zalygin, editor of the Soviet monthly Novy
Mir, said negotiations for publishing ``Cancer Ward'' in the Soviet
Union were under way.
   However, Mrs. Solzhenitsyn was quoted by The New York Times as
saying at the time that Soviet officials had not approached
Solzhenitsyn about publishing any of his works in the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
