<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Richards-Keynote     07-15 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Richards-Keynote,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Keynoter Sees Unified Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas state Treasurer Ann Richards said Friday
she will talk about the American family, the Republican record and
her admiration for both Michael Dukakis and his rival, Jesse
Jackson, in her keynote address at the Democratic National
Convention.
   Richards, 54, said the Democrats are more unified than at any
other time in her lifetime, despite the rift that developed this
week between the Jackson and Dukakis camps over Dukakis' failure to
notify Jackson in advance of his selection of Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of
Texas as his running mate.
   ``What you have here are two superb leaders, two bright
individuals, two of our party's best. And I think that, whatever
the difficulties, they will be able to resolve those,'' she said of
Dukakis and Jackson.
   Richards said at a news conference that she did not intend to
focus in her Monday night speech on the estrangement that Jackson
has been feeling from the Dukakis campaign. Since the dispute over
Dukakis' running mate occurred on Tuesday, contacts between the two
campaigns have been initiated to discuss Jackson's role in the
Democrats' plans for November.
   ``I'm going to talk about Jesse Jackson because I think he's
been a passionate, energetic and exciting voice in this country and
I want to compliment him for that,'' Richards said.
   Mentioning general themes of her speech without revealing
specifics, Richard said she would speak about GOP nominee-to-be
George Bush and the last eight years under a Republican
administration and will laud the records of Dukakis, Bentsen and
Jackson.
   She said she also would talk about ``the American family,'' an
issue popular this year with both Republicans and Democrats,
liberals and conservatives. ``It's something I feel like I've
lived,'' she said.
   She noted the dramatic, crowd-rousing speech given by New York
Gov. Mario Cuomo at the Democratic convention four years ago and
said the issues he talked about _ such as homelessness, drugs and
ghettos _ still are important in the country.
   Well known for her crowd-pleasing speaking style, Richards said
she did not expect to match Cuomo's effort.
   ``I kind of feel like a student who is facing final exams and
knowing that this one is important, this one is tough and I had
better be prepared for it,'' she said. ``So I'm still cramming and
doing some finishing touches and will be ready to open the
convention Monday night.''
   Richards has been state treasurer since 1982, and was the first
woman elected to a statewide office in Texas in 50 years when she
assumed the post.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
