<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Thailand-Refugees     07-15 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thailand-Refugees,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thailand to Move Cambodian Refugees Closer to Border</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities will begin moving about
17,000 Cambodian refugees from the Khao-I-Dang camp to a location
closer to the Thai-Cambodian border, a military commander said
Friday.
   The United States and other countries have expressed concern
about the refugees' safety if they are moved from Khao-I-Dang, whic
is eight miles from the frontier.
   Thousands of Cambodians have entered Thailand to escape the war
in their country between guerrilla forces and Vietnamese and
government troops. Vietnam sent troops into Cambodia in December
1978, ousted the radical Khmer Rouge regime and installed another
communist government.
   Most of the Cambodians settled in camps along the border, and
Khao-I-Dang is considered the only refugee camp not controlled by
the differerent guerrilla groups. It also is the only camp where
there is an official program to resettle the refugees in other
countries.
   Thailand had declared on Dec. 31, 1986, that it would close
Khao-I-Dang, but only a small number of refugees were forced to
leave.
   Col. Sanan Kajornklam, of the Supreme Command's Joint Operations
Center, spoke of moving the refugees at a meeting Friday.
   Later, in an interview with The Associated Press, Sanan said
that within three months authorities will start moving the
Khao-I-Dang refugees to the area of Site 2 close to the border.
Site 2 adjoins the Ban Thad camp where the government, trying to
discourage more Indochinese from entering Thailand, has placed
about 3,000 Vietnamese refugees.
   Sanan said the Khao-I-Dang refugees would be resettled because
they have not been accepted by other countries and they must
prepare to return to Cambodia.
   ``If we close Khao-I-Dang, the Cambodians will know that they
must go home,'' Sanan said.
   Kobsak Chutikul, director of the Foreign Ministry's Social
Afffairs Division, said that in its plans to move the Khao-I-Dang
refugees the government will follow three objectives that U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar outlined in a letter to
the government last year.
   He said those objectives are that the new site be safe, that it
be neutral and that the refugees remain under the protection of the
office of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
