<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 2107EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Murder-Racial     07-15 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Murder-Racial,0645</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DA: Racial Motivation In Murder A Serious Concern</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents beginning with 9th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE ZGANJAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The murder of a 19-year-old black woman
whose body was found with ``KKK'' carved on her leg is being
investigated as possibly racially motivated, a prosecutor said
Friday.
   District Attorney Michael Kavanagh said he talked with Gov.
Mario Cuomo about the case Friday and Cuomo had pledged ``full
support of state resources'' to help with the case.
   Anna Kithcart, 19, was found dead Tuesday, but information about
the letters on her leg were not released until Thursday. The
letters were written with a sharp instrument, said Kavanagh, who
refused to comment on many aspects of the investigation.
   ``As far as racial involvement, we are concerned,'' Kavanagh
said. ``We are concerned.''
   Preliminary autopsy results indicated Miss Kithcart was
strangled and struck on the head with a blunt instrument, police
said. A bite on the neck and other marks also were found on her
body.
   Miss Kithcart had last been seen Monday evening at the Royal
Grill, a few doors down from the alleyway where her blood-stained
sweatsuit was found. Her partly clothed body was found another
block away.
   While Kavanagh wouldn't comment on reports that Miss Kithcart
was a drug addict, the woman's father told the Kingston Daily
Freeman that his daughter had fallen victim to drugs.
   ``I'm almost positive it was a drug rub,'' Kithcart told the
newspaper.
   The only arrest in the case came Wednesday, when a man police
described as a transient was charged with engaging in sexual
contact with Miss Kithcart's corpse.
   Joseph Kiernan, 41, being held on $10,000 bail, told radio
station WDST in Woodstock Thursday night that he was innocent of
any charges and thought Miss Kithcart's body was a life-sized,
pornographic doll when he saw it.
   ``I never saw a dead body before,'' Kiernan said. ``I looked
down and touched it and it felt like rubber, sort of warm and sort
of cold.''
   Kiernan said when he saw the head wound, he ``flipped out'' and
ran to call police.
   While Kiernan was being questioned, Kavanagh said Friday that
there was still no suspect in the murder.
   There are ``similiarities'' between the murder and the Tawana
Brawley case, but there was no evidence of a connection in the
cases, Kavanagh said.
   Miss Brawley, 16, of Wappingers Falls was found last November
with the letters ``KKK'' and racial epithets scrawled in a
charcoal-like substance on her skin after being missing for four
days. She later said she had been abducted and raped by a group of
white men, but she and her family have refused to cooperate with
the investigation.
   Kingston is about 25 miles north of Wappingers Falls, on the
opposite shore of the Hudson River.
   On Friday, Brawley advisers the Rev. Al Sharpton and lawyer
Alton Maddox arrived at the Ulster County Jail to conduct what they
said would be their own investigation of the murder.
   ``If our investigation leads to the Kingston Police Department,
then we'll go there,'' Maddox said.
   Kavanagh said the Brawley advisers' appearance in Kingston was
``a nightmare come true.''
   State Attorney General Robert Abrams, the special prosecutor in
the Brawley case, said he would push the grand jury investigating
it to begin writing a report next month on what it believes
happened to the black teen-ager during the four days she was
missing late last year.
   ``There may not have been any crime committed here,'' he said in
an interview about the Brawley case reported Friday in New York
Newsday. ``If a crime, or crimes, were committed, then you would
surmise that there would be suspects.'' But Abrams said his
investigation had turned up no suspects.
</TEXT>
