<DOCNO> AP880715-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 2230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-StarWars-Laser     07-15 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Star Wars-Laser,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teller Claimed X-Ray Laser Could Destroy All Land-Based Soviet
Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hydrogen bomb developer Edward Teller once
told a top administration arms control adviser that a proposed
``Star Wars'' laser could ``potentially shoot down the entire
Soviet land-based missile force,'' a congressional report says.
   That and some other details in the report back the charge by a
disaffected former director of the X-ray laser research program
that Teller made unsupportable claims about the potential of the
proposed weapon, Rep. George Brown Jr. said Friday.
   ``Let me plead guilty to the great crime of optimism,'' Teller
countered Friday.
   Roy Woodruff resigned in 1985 as director of the Lawrence
Livermore Laboratory's research program into the X-ray laser
because of the dispute, and said he was demoted to an entry-level
job.
   Last year, Woodruff filed grievances alleging that Teller and
another scientist, Lowell Wood, made ``overly optimistic,
technically incorrect statements regarding this research to the
nation's highest policy-makers.'' He also accused Roger Batzel,
then the lab's director, of blocking his efforts to correct those
statements.
   An internal study eventually concluded that Woodruff was made
into an ``unperson'' because of his dispute with Batzel.
   The General Accounting Office report, written at Brown's
request, cited some optimistic statements by Teller and Wood but
also concluded that Woodruff and his colleagues at Livermore shared
that optimism to some extent.
   ``The report is trying to straddle the fence,'' Brown said by
phone from Washington. ``It says that Woodruff made similar
(optimistic) statements, but that in a couple of instances _ the
two Woodruff objected to most _ the statements (by Teller and Wood)
were indeed overly optimistic and not factual.''
   Teller, interviewed by telephone from Livermore, contended the
GAO report backs his point of view. The report, he said, shows that
Woodruff's criticisms were over the way Teller worded his claims,
but that Woodruff ``supported (them) in substance.''
   The claim about the laser being able to shoot down all 10,000
Soviet land-based missiles sounds absurd because it was quoted out
of context, the physicist said.
   ``I tried to illustrate the possibly great effects that the
X-ray laser might produce,'' Teller said. ``If you read the letter,
you will find qualifiers: `eventually,' `potentially' and
`perhaps.'''
   In a telephone interview, Woodruff also contended that the GAO
report generally backs his point of view, but he had some criticism
for it.
   The report, he said Friday, ``establishes everything I ever
alleged, but I am very unhappy with the finding that suggests there
was a great deal of similarity between Dr. Teller and myself.''
   ``He was an enthusiast for the X-ray laser and I was an
enthusiast. But the points we differed on were very important,''
Woodruff said, adding, ``I am still struggling to tell the truth
against what I would call reprisals.''
   A space-based system of X-ray laser beams, powered by nuclear
detonations, is no longer viewed as the centerpiece of Reagan's
proposed Strategic Defense Initiative, known as SDI or Star Wars.
SDI research now focuses on land-based weapons to defend the United
States against Soviet nuclear missiles, Brown said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
