<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Tornadoes     07-15 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tornadoes,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dozens Injured, 100 Homes Damaged By Tornadoes</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AH4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT SONNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massive thunderstorms packing tornadoes and
wind gusts up to 92 mph slammed into Omaha and Council Bluffs,
Iowa, on Friday, injuring at least 40 people and damaging more than
100 homes.
   One tornado uprooted trees, downed power lines, started fires
and overturned railroad cars in a 2-mile stretch in western Council
Bluffs along Interstate 29 and the Missouri River, which divides
the two cities.
   Most of Council Bluffs' 60,000 residents were without power
Friday night and the situation was not expected to change through
morning, said Matt Daunis of Iowa Power and Light Co.
   Council Bluffs Mayor Tom Hanafan ordered a curfew from 10 p.m.
to dawn to guard against looting. Members of the Iowa National
Guard patroled the streets.
   An Omaha man was reported in critical condition with neck and
possible internal injuries after a tree crashed onto the roof of
his car. Most other injuries were minor, said officials of three
hospitals who counted a total of 40 people treated for
storm-related injuries.
   Exits off Interstate 29 into Council Bluffs were closed and the
Iowa Highway Patrol sealed off the area most heavily damaged.
   Possible tornadoes and funnel clouds were reported throughout
the Omaha area as hail fell and more than 2 inches of rain caused
street flooding.
   ``We went to the hallway and we were praying very hard,'' said
Council Bluffs resident Lu Guzenhauser, who was baby-sitting for
two children when the storm hit her neighborhood.
   Ms. Guzenhauser and the children were not injured. However, part
of the tool shed behind her house was hanging from power lines in
the front of her home after the storm.
   Trees as thick as 48 inches in diameter snapped in half in
Council Bluffs and others as tall as 100-feet were uprooted at
Dodge Park Golf Course in Omaha.
   In the worst 2-mile stretch in Council Bluffs, the tops of
hundreds of trees were sawed off by the twister, sidewalks were
uplifted and roofs were blown off houses.
   A wind gust of 92 mph was reported at Omaha's Eppley Airfield at
4:21 p.m., the National Weather Service reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
