<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 2348EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-RefineryFire     07-15 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Refinery Fire,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Apparently Unrelated Fires At Same Plant Kill One, Injure Seven</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORRANCE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion and fire at a Mobil Oil
refinery killed one man and injured two Friday just hours after a
flash fire in another part of the plant injured five other people,
officials said.
   The two fires were not believed to be related, and both involved
employees from private companies contracted by Mobil Oil, said Fire
Chief Denny Haas.
   ``They were different companies, with different processes in
different parts of the plant,'' said Haas.
   Shortly before 10 a.m., a flash fire injured five men from an
outside contractor who were working on the refinery's sewage
system, said Haas. Investigators believed sparks from a welder's
torch ignited fumes rising from water that was mixed with volatile
liquids, he said.
   The second fire erupted about 3:20 p.m. and was quickly
extinguished, but the blast left thousands of gallons of toxic
hydrogen peroxide and other chemicals mixed with oil on the ground,
said Haas.
   The dead man and the two men injured in the second fire are all
employees of Benecia-based Calcat Chemical Co. They were removing
the residue from pipes containing a number of chemicals when the
pipes exploded, said Haas. The reason for the blast was not
immediately determined, he said.
   Of the seven workers injured in the two fires, four were
hospitalized, one in critical condition. The dead man was
identified as Winston Alexander Jones, 30, no hometown available,
Haas said.
   After the second fire, firefighters sprayed foam on the ground
to control the spread of the spilt hydrogen peroxide, arsenic, oil,
and other materials, but no evacuations were ordered, said Haas.
   In November, a huge blast at the refinery shattered windows
throughout the area 15 miles south of downtown Los Angeles, sending
a huge fireball into the air and sparking a blaze that burned for
two days. One refinery worker suffered minor injuries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
