<DOCNO> AP880715-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0108EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0836 07-15 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0836,0702</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Urges U.S. Not to Give Contras More Military Aid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout UPDATING with deputy foreign minister
condemning U.S. Senate resolution, more demonstrators sentenced,
reax to expropriation from refinery manager. CORRECTS family name
from Pallas to Pellas. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega said Thursday
that any U.S. decision to resume military aid to Nicaraguan rebels
would amount to ``newly legitimizing'' a war in which a truce was
declared months ago.
   A source close to the rebels, known as Contras, said in the
Dominican Republic that the leadership would meet this weekend in
that nation's capital, Santo Domingo, to reorganize the movement.
   Leading foes of the leftist Sandinista government meanwhile
vowed that their fight against the government's latest crackdown
had just begun.
   Ortega spoke to journalists in Campoa, 58 miles northeast of
Managua, where he inaugurated an agricultural fair.
   ``We hope they (the United States) do not commit this madness,
since it would be newly legitimizing'' the civil war that began
seven years ago, he said in remarks broadcast on the state radio,
Voice of Nicaragua.
   The U.S. House of Representatives voted 385-18 on Thursday to
condemn Ortega's government for ``brutal suppression of basic human
rights.''
   A similar resolution passed by the Senate by a 91-4 vote
Wednesday night included the possibility of renewed military aid to
the Contras if Sandinista policy did not change. The resolution
would make democratic reform a condition of economic aid to
Nicaragua.
   In their resolution, House members urged Central American
leaders ``to convene immediately to assess the conditions in
Nicaragua described in this resolution.''
   They condemned the Sandinistas for arresting 43 demonstrators,
including opposition leaders, and closing the opposition newspaper
La Prensa and the Roman Catholic Church radio station this week.
   Deputy Foreign Minister Victor Hugo Tinoco told The Associated
Press the U.S. Senate resolution was ``tremendously interventionist
and illegal.'' ``We call this imperialism,'' Tinoco said.
   Patricia Orozco of the Interior Ministry's press office said 31
anti-government demonstrators arrested Sunday were sentenced by
police courts to six-month jail sentences for violating public
security laws.
   Five demonstrators were sentenced similarly on Wednesday.
   Security forces violently broke up the demonstration Sunday in
Nandaime, south of Managua.
   The source in Santo Domingo said more than 50 prominent Contras
were expected to attend the weekend meeting, including Adolfo
Calero, political head of the organization, and military
coordinator Enrique Bermudez.
   Internal disputes, notably between Bermudez and the movement's
political leaders, have divided the rebels in recent weeks. The
source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said new leadership
was expected to be chosen.
   ``This is a very hard dictatorship,'' Enrique Bolanos, a critic
of the government, said in an interview. He is president of the
Superior Private Enterprise Council, an opposition group.
   ``They cannot stand the tremendous opposition that is gaining
momentum,'' Bolanos said. ``Everybody now knows they are
Marxist-Leninists.''
   On Monday, the Sandinistas ordered U.S. Ambassador Richard
Melton and seven other American diplomats to leave the country.
Melton left Tuesday and the others followed on Thursday.
   The Reagan administration ordered the same number of Nicaraguan
diplomats out of the United States.
   Ortega's government expropriated Nicaragua's largest and oldest
sugar refinery on Wednesday, claiming it was not productive enough
and the owners, the wealthy Pellas family, were not investing
enough to keep it going.
   The century-old refinery is a leading symbol of Nicaraguan
private enterprise.
   Carlos Pellas, the refinery's general manager, told reporters
Thursday the expropriation was ``a very hard blow for the economy.''
   He said the related Flor de Cana rum distillery, known
throughout Latin America, was legally separate from the refinery
and not affected by the expropriation.
   The crackdown reverses an easing of restrictions on the
opposition that began in November as part of a Central American
peace plan approved in August 1987 by the presidents of Nicaragua,
El Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras and Costa Rica.
   Under the plan, the Sandinistas and rebels reached a cease-fire
agreement March 21 that has survived occasional violations.
Negotiations on a permanent truce are deadlocked.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
