<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     07-15 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Much Ado About Nothing' Starring Kevin Kline Opens in Central
Park</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``A merry war'' is the way one character
describes the relationship between Benedick and Beatrice, those
tempest-tossed, tart-tongued lovers in ``Much Ado About Nothing.''
   That's pretty much the way it's played in Central Park where the
New York Shakespeare Festival opened its boisterous revival of one
of Shakespeare's most durable comedies on Thursday night.
   Director Gerald Freedman opts for the robust rather than the
romantic in his staging of the play, an approach that accentuates
the laughs rather than the poetry.
   Fortunately, he gets both from Kevin Kline, who probably could
walk on water if asked to do so by his director.
   Kline does just about everything else in ``Much Ado,'' and he
accomplishes it with such style, wit and grace that he gives
hamminess a good name. The actor makes a first-rate arrogant,
foolish and finally lovestruck Benedick.
   Consider Kline's entrance in the play. It's no quiet walk-on.
It's a full-fledged sword fight, staged with an alarming
athleticism by fight director B.H. Barry. In the middle of this
ruckus, Beatrice sits quietly and reads a book. The battle lines
are drawn as soon as the play begins.
   If Blythe Danner, who appears as the equally obstinate and
egocentric Beatrice, can't match the Kline juggernaut, she gives it
a good try. Her Beatrice is too much of a lady, and her odd, almost
squeaky voice is not particularly suited for Shakespeare. Still,
she exudes an impertinence that mangages to charm Benedick and the
audience by the end of the evening.
   A special joy of Freedman's production is the strong supporting
cast which usually fades into the background. Brian Murray makes a
comical yet touching Don Pedro, the nobleman who instigates the
matching up of Benedick with Beatrice and Claudio with Hero.
   Don John, the melancholy villain of the play, is a strange
character. He sets in motion a subplot to besmirch Hero's honor and
then disappears. David Pierce does a fine comic turn _ all smirks
and sneers _ and remains in one's memory even after he leaves the
stage.
   There is more good support from Robert Gerringer as Leonato,
Beatrice's uncle, another of those underrated roles, and from Jerry
Stiller as the dumbest of Dogberrys. Because Beatrice and Benedick
are so strong, the actors playing the other set of lovers tend to
disappear into the plot. That's the case with Don Reilly, a
colorless Claudio, and Phoebe Cates, a one-dimensional Hero.
   Designer John Ezell has provided a fairy tale 19th century
Italian town, which is where Freedman sets the play. The costumes
by Theoni V. Aldredge are colorful and apppropriate to the period.
   There is an inevitable falloff after the exuberant first act.
But that's because the ending has been telegraphed long before the
play is over and the involved plot convolutions must be
straightened out before the curtain falls.
   Still this ``Much Ado About Nothing'' spins gaily for much of
the evening and most of it turns because of the whirlwind
performance of Kevin Kline. He makes it the airiest, most bouyant
production in New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
