<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AlohaHearing     07-15 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aloha Hearing,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tiny Cracks Found In Nearly Half Of Inspected Boeing 737s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tiny cracks were found in nearly half the aging
Boeing 737 jetliners known to have been inspected since the top
ripped off an Aloha Airlines 737 in late May, a Federal Aviation
Administration official testified Thursday.
   James W. Hart Jr., manager of the airframe branch in the FAA's
Seattle aircraft certification office, described the initial
responses to an FAA ``airworthiness directive'' in testimony to a
National Transportation Safety Board hearing on the accident.
   The order, issued within a week after the April 28 accident,
required all Boeing 737s with 30,000 or more landings to undergo a
special visual inspection of fuselage lap joints, or areas where
parts of the fuselage are bonded and riveted together.
   The directive ordered those with more than 50,000 landings to
have additional inspections using high-frequency electronic
equipment. Airlines were required to fix any problems found and to
report the results to the FAA.
   A flight attendant was killed and 61 persons injured when a
portion of the fuselage on a Boeing 737 peeled off during an Aloha
flight from Hilo to Honolulu, exposing the first-class section to
the open air at 24,000 feet.
   The pilot and co-pilot managed to land the crippled jet 13
minutes later in Maui although one of the two engines quit.
   Hart said 291 737s were affected by the inspection order issued
shortly after the accident. As of this week, he said, the FAA has
received reports on 100 planes, of which 49 reported cracks.
   The largest crack found was about one-half inch, but most were
three-eighths of an inch or smaller, he said. The most found in one
plane were 31 cracks within a 40-inch space. Five or more cracks
were found in 14 of the planes, he said.
   Cracks can occur around the rivets used to join the panels. Hart
said none of the cracks reported had joined up _ ``In other words,
they had not gone from fastener to fastener.''
   Boeing spokesman Jack Gamble declined comment on the cracks
until he had spoken with the airlplane manufacturer's engineers.
   Bill Ashworth, manager of the FAA's Seattle aircraft
certification division, said he was concerned about the cracks but
saw no imminent danger to the planes or to air passengers.
   As of today ``we have not seen evidence of impending failure in
any airplane. We of course are requiring that all cracks we finds
be repaired. That's only prudent maintenance,'' he said.
   In testimony earlier Thursday, Boeing's Robert L. Oldani said he
was shocked to learn in an October 1987 meeting with Aloha
officials that the airline did not have a specific program to
prevent corrosion of its air fleet.
   Oldani told the NTSB that Henry Arii, Aloha's staff vice
president of quality control and engineering, told him that Aloha
had stopped its corrosion control program three years earlier.
   Much of the testimony at the hearing has focused on technical
studies of how cracks form in 737s. The inquiry is trying to
determine the cause of the Aloha accident, but early investigations
have focused on possible structural failure, perhaps aggravated by
corrosion.
   Hart told the panel that the FAA was formulating ``very
demanding'' new rules to require extensive inspections of early
737s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
