<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NeedleExchange     07-15 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Needle Exchange,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Social Service Agency Delays Needle Exchange</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB BAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insurance problems will delay a plan aimed
at reducing the spread of AIDS by distributing free needles to
intravenous drug users, a social service agency official said
Thursday.
   Kathy Oliver, executive director of the agency Outside In, said
her organization hopes to begin giving out the hypodermic needles
by late August.
   Oliver said the insurance company, St. Paul Fire and Marine of
St. Paul, Minn., is concerned about the agency's liability because
the project, which was scheduled to begin this month, is
unprecedented in the United States.
   ``It is difficult to assess the exposure and risk, and therefore
it's difficult to determine rates,'' she said.
   Beth Murray, spokeswoman for St. Paul Fire and Marine, said the
company notified Outside In that the project wasn't covered under
its existing policy.
   ``It takes us into areas of unknown liability,'' she said.
``We're especially concerned for the potential of the spread of
AIDS from needles supplied by the clinic and later re-used.''
   Under the yearlong project, 125 drug abusers will exchange used
needles for new ones and receive counseling.
   The project is financed by a $67,000 grant from the American
Foundation for AIDS Research. If the insurance cost increases
greatly, Oliver said, she is confident that more funds can be
obtained because of the interest in the experiment nationwide.
   St. Paul, the largest medical liability insurer in the country,
has provided comprehensive medical malpractice and liability
insurance to Outside In for 10 years. The agency never has had a
claim filed against its policy.
   ``We're negotiating with them to work this out,'' Murray said.
``They've been insured with our company for several years and it's
important for us to work it out with them.''
   Oliver said the company's action came as a surprise because the
problems didn't surface when agency officials spoke with the
insurance company about the proposed project a year ago and again
when the financing was obtained earlier this year.
   She said the company apparently became concerned after news
accounts of the project were published. Outside In learned about
the problem about two weeks ago, she said.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is most often spread through
sexual contact, sharing of needles by intravenous drug abusers, or
by transfusions of blood or blood products, experts say.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
