<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1148EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:Bayreuth Adv19   07-15 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Bayreuth, Adv 19,0724</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tue AMs, July 19 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>New Production of ``Ring'' Cycle Highlights Beyreuth Festival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN FISCHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAYREUTH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mix an experimental director from
communist East Germany with Richard Wagner's legendary operas, and
you come up with one of the most eagerly awaited Bayreuth seasons
in years.
   A new production of Wagner's epic ``Ring'' cycle under East
German director Harry Kupfer and celebrated Israeli conductor
Daniel Barenboim, will be the centerpiece of Bayreuth's Richard
Wagner Festival, which opens on July 26.
   ``From Kupfer one can expect a modern, perhaps even socially
critical production,'' critic Gerhard Koch of the Frankfurter
Allegemeine Zeitung newspaper said in an interview.
   ``The story of the family tragedy and its elements of greed,
particularly in `Die Walkuere,' lends itself well to a socially
critical interpretation.''
   The new ``Ring'' production is clearly the highlight of the
season.
   Previous festival ``Ring'' productions have set the old Germanic
myths in various time periods, and in styles ranging from bombastic
to relatively spare and modern.
   The festival, first held in 1876, transforms the placid northern
Bavarian town of Bayreuth for one month every summer into a
gathering place for Wagner lovers across the world.
   For nearly 40 years, Wolfgang Wagner, the composer's grandson,
has been running the festival, occasionally also producing festival
performances.
   Performances regularly sell out way ahead of time, as there are
only 1,925 seats available in the theater Wagner built specifically
for his works.
   The theater was financed by Bavaria's King Ludwig II, nicknamed
``Mad King Ludwig'' because of his extreme shyness and love of
overspending on elaborate, Disneyland-like castles.
   According to Mathias Vogt, a spokesman for the festival, this
year was no exception to the festival's sell-out tradition.
   ``Demand for the festival was greater this year than ever,'' he
said. ``Tickets sold out shortly after going on sale last
November.''
   The festival will open with the return of last year's
``Parsifal,'' directed by Goetz Friedrich and conducted by James
Levine.
   ``My favorite opera is `Parsifal' and that's why I'm really
looking forward to going,'' said Wagner fan Manfred Schuldt, 34, of
Hamburg. Schuldt has been making the annual trek to Bayreuth for
the last 10 years.
   ``But it's the new `Ring' production that's causing the most
excitement,'' he said. ``Barenboim has a special style. You really
notice when he's conducting.''
   Barenboim, musical director of the renowned Orchestre de Paris,
will conduct the four works comprising the mighty ``Der Ring des
Nibelungen'' cycle to begin on July 27 with ``Das Rheingold.'' The
other works, ``Die Walkuere,'' ``Siegfried'' and
``Goetterdaemmerung'' will follow.
   Opera lovers also say they are eager to see what East German
director Kupfer does with the new ``Ring'' production.
   ``That's the sensation of the season to me,'' August Everding,
general director of the Bayerischen Staatstheater (Bavarian State
Theater) said. ``Kupfer is a wonderful opera director.''
   Critic Koch looked to Kupfer's 1978 Bayreuth production of ``The
Flying Dutchman'' as a clue to what audiences might expect this
summer.
   ``It was highly imaginative, but critical at the same time,'' he
said. ``Kupfer manages to bring current aspects into his work, and
audiences today can easily identify with it.''
   Other festival presentations will be a return of last year's
romantic opera, ``Lohengrin'' and ``Die Meistersinger von
Nuernberg.''
   Opera singers in this year's festival include some of Bayreuth
favorites such as Siegfried Jerusalem as Parsifal and Siegfried,
Franz Mazura as Klingsor and the Wanderer, and Waltraud Meier as
Kundry and Waltraute.
   Among those appearing in Bayreuth for the first time include
Alan Opie, Marie-Claire O'Reirdan and Jane Turner.
   There will be a total of 30 performances at the festival, which
runs until Aug. 29.
   Meanwhile, Bayreuth tourist officials laugh at some aspects of
the summer invasion.
   ``We get people writing letters to the mayor asking for
tickets,'' Bayreuth Tourist director Jo Schumacher said. ``And lots
of tourists just stumble in here casually and are astounded when
they can't get tickets.''
   Bayreuth, a picturesque town founded in the 12th century, also
shows a number of art exhibits during the Wagner festival, much of
them Wagner related.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, July 19</NOTE>
