<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   07-15 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0541</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banks have raised their prime lending rate to
9.5 percent from 9 percent, pushing the benchmark interest rate to
the highest level in more than two years.
   Thursday's increase reflected a rise in the banks' own borrowing
costs and signaled more expensive loans for consumers and
businesses.
   It marked the second time this year the nation's banks have
raised the prime, which is used to calculate a range of fixed and
adjustable-rate corporate and consumer loans.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GAF Corp. and its vice chairman have pleaded
innocent to charges they manipulated Union Carbide Corp.'s stock
price after a takeover attempt of the much larger company fizzled
in 1986.
   During a brief proceeding in federal court Thursday, lawyers for
GAF and James Sherwin entered the pleas to the 10-count indictment
returned last week by a grand jury.
   Sherwin, who could face a 50-year prison term and $15 million in
fines if convicted, was released without bail. A trial date was not
immediately set.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wells Fargo & Co. is reviewing the books of
ailing First RepublicBank Corp. in preparation for a possible
purchase offer.
   Wells Fargo's eight-member team visiting Dallas Thursday is the
third group to go over the finances of First Republic, Texas'
largest bank. Citicorp of New York and NCNB Corp. of Charlotte,
N.C., also are considering bids.
   Meanwhile, owners of the Dallas-based company's bonds sought to
get their money back.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge in Delaware has blocked publishing giant
Macmillan Inc. from going ahead with a massive restructuring plan
designed to thwart an unwanted bid from the Robert Bass Group of
Texas.
   After nearly five weeks of consideration, Jack B. Jacobs of the
Delaware Chancery Court issued a 58-page opinion Thursday granting
Bass's request for a preliminary injunction that effectively blocks
the restructuring.
   Josy Ingersoll, an attorney representing the Bass group, said
the judge found that Macmillan's attempt to restructure was an
unreasonable response to Bass's buyout bid.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCI Communications Corp. has signaled confidence
in its future by announcing plans to repurchase for $677 million
the 16.2 percent stake held by its largest shareholder,
International Business Machines Corp.
   But MCI defrayed the cost and kept a link to IBM by saying it
would sell IBM a new issue of $400 million in preferred shares. The
shares will give IBM 10 percent of the voting rights in MCI.
   Investors reacted positively to the announcement, bidding MCI up
75 cents to $16.12{ a share in national over-the-counter trading, a
5 percent increase.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hot, dry weather that has caused grief for
many U.S. farmers proved to be a boon for the nation's retailers in
June as consumers rushed to purchase items ranging from summer
clothes to air conditioners.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday that retail sales rose a
moderate 0.5 percent to a seasonally adjusted $132.8 billion last
month.
   Much of the strength in June came at department stores and other
general merchandise outlets.
</TEXT>
