<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlight, 1st Add,0526</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Ways and Means Committee has
approved a bill correcting errors in the 1986 tax overhaul, after
tacking on a fistful of special-interest benefits and the tax
increases to pay for them.
   Pipe smokers, some farmers and moonlighters accustomed to
writing off part of their telephone bills would pay more.
   The bill endorsed Thursday could provide $7.1 billion of tax
cuts over the next three years and raise an equal amount to finance
them.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MARION, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is promising farmers in the
country's drought-stricken midsection that he would do everything
to help America cope with the ``worst natural disaster since the
Dust Bowl of the 1930s.''
   At the same time, he called on Congress to ``act quickly'' on a
package of legislation aimed at making emergency federal aid
available to farmers.
   Reagan used his tour Thursday to announce that he was
dispatching Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng on a tour of several
states hard hit by the dry spell.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Three of the nation's biggest banking companies have reported
profits in the second quarter after posting losses a year earlier.
   Chemical Banking Corp., Security Pacific Corp. and Bank of New
York Co. _ had sustained heavy losses in the second quarter of 1987
from writeoffs for potential losses on loans to developing
countries.
   First City Bancorp. of Texas, meanwhile, which recently received
a $970 million federal bailout, reported net income of $17.2
million for the 72-day period immediately following its $1.6
billion reorganization.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices have risen sharply and partly erased
steep losses from earlier this week, but traders attributed the
rebound to short-term influences and Saudi Arabia's denial that it
was boosting production.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange Thursday, the near-month
contract for West Texas Intermediate crude advanced 32 cents per
barrel from its 21-month low to close at $14.76.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale
unleaded gasoline rose .06 cent a gallon to 50.54 cents, and No. 2
heating oil rose .77 cent a gallon to 40.91 cents.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Lloyd Bentsen, back in the Senate
after a campaign trip, says running for vice president will not
distract him from pushing for final approval of a wide-ranging
trade bill.
   The House approved a revised trade bill Wednesday and sent it to
the Senate, where action could follow next week's break for the
Democratic National Convention.
   Some Democrats are saying the decision by Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis to tap Bentsen as his running mate heightens
prospects for Senate approval of the legislation.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn, oat and soybean prices rose Thursday on forecasts for
another month of drought conditions in the Midwest.
   Stocks posted small gains. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials rose 9.25 to 2,113.62.
   Bonds were mixed.
   The dollar rose in advance of Friday's report on the nation's
trade deficit. Gold prices fell.
</TEXT>
