<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0307EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Cosmetics-Business Bjt   07-15 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cosmetics-Business, Bjt,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cosmetics: Lucre, Snob Appeal and Fame</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Cosmetics, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It is no accident that many department stores
put their cosmetics counters just inside the front door, the area
with the highest customer traffic.
   When Bloomingdale's redid the first floor of its flagship
Manhattan store a few years ago, the centerpiece was the makeup and
perfume department.
   It also is no accident that the front pages of women's magazines
often are dominated by ads for Revlon, Estee Lauder, Clairol, Coty
and other big names in beauty, while inside, articles dispense tips
on how women can totally make themselves over.
   Cosmetics is a big and lucrative business, bringing in $17
billion in sales last year.
   The world's largest cosmetic company, Avon Products Inc., had
1987 sales of nearly $1.81 billion from its cosmetics, fragrances
and toiletries business. That produced a $251.3 million pre-tax
profit.
   Numbers like that make successful cosmetic companies desirable
properties. Ronald O. Perelman battled for three months in 1985
before finally winning a $1.65 billion takeover fight for Revlon
Inc., one of the world's top cosmetic manufacturers.
   The profitable business lately has come under scrutiny by
Congress, too. The House small business panel on Wednesday held a
hearing to examine health and safety questions about cosmetics,
some of which are said to contain chemicals that could cause
cancer, birth defects, central nervous disorders, skin and eye
irritations and allergic reactions.
   Cosmetics are profitable because they are relatively inexpensive
to produce and their prices can be marked up heavily because of
snob appeal. The cosmetic industry has its own equivalent of
designer fashions.
   For example, a mascara by Maybelline was priced at $3 in a
Manhattan drug store, while a similar Estee Lauder product sold for
$10 at Saks Fifth Avenue.
   Manufacturers and retailers both are big beneficiaries of
makeup's high profit margins.
   ``If you pay $10 for an item, the manufacturer probably gets
$6,'' leaving $4 for the retailer, said Diana Temple, a cosmetic
industry analyst for the investment firm Salomon Brothers Inc.
   One reason why retailers do so well from makeup is that at
bigger department and specialty stores, such as Bloomingdale's,
Marshall Field's, Nordstrom and Macy's, the people selling the
cosmetics often are paid at least in part by the manufacturer, Ms.
Temple said.
   In shopping for cosmetics, women generally are motivated by
price and the image created for the product by ad campaigns.
   But if you put the Maybelline mascara and the Estee Lauder item
side by side, is there any difference between the ingredients of
the two?
   ``Not a heck of a lot,'' said Jack Salzman, an analyst with the
investment firm Goldman Sachs & Co.
   ``There are differences in quality but the differences in price
are greater,'' Ms. Temple said.
   Cosmetics sell because they can make women more glamorous. But
they also have given the people associated with the industry their
own special aura.
   The late Charles Revson, one of the founders of Revlon, was
constantly in the society pages. And actress Lauren Hutton made it
into the movies after her impeccably made-up face appeared in many
a Revlon ad.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880715-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0308EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TelephoneAds Bjt   07-15 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Telephone Ads, Bjt,0679</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Long-Distance Commercials Take Lighter Approach</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You can quit cringing at the first sight of
those long-distance telephone commercials: telephone admakers plan
to lighten up.
   AT&T is winding down its use of ads that show corporate
underlings getting chewed out by the boss _ or worrying that they
might be fired _ for picking the wrong telephone service. Instead,
it is phasing in new ads that show its employees describing how
they can help your business.
   Competitor US Sprint, meanwhile, plans to begin using a new
series of ads next week that indirectly pokes fun at AT&T's old
approach as it humorously demonstrates how important it is to get a
clear line when you want to place a business call.
   The ads were directed by Joe Sedelmaier, best known for his
``Where's the Beef'' ads for Wendy's and his fast-talker spots for
Federal Express.
   In one new Sprint ad, four men are in an office waiting for the
boss's call. ``That's him,'' they say as the phone rings.
   But as the camera catches every expressive twitch of the face of
the guy who picks up the phone, the boss' instructions are reduced
to gibberish because of the poor quality of the phone line.
   ``Listen carefully ..500 cases .. by Monday ... we'll lose the
account'' are some of the fragments that can be heard.
   After the boss hangs up, the man who took the call dutifully
repeats for the others exactly what he heard.
   The message is that this won't happen if you use Sprint. But
there is no suggestion that somebody is about to lose his job over
it.
   Sprint executives and their admakers at J. Walter Thompson in
San Francisco said they felt the ads coming from American Telephone
& Telegraph Co. and, to a lesser extent, from MCI Communications
Corp. were ``depressing and colorless.''
   ``We wanted to be upbeat. We wanted to be fiesty, and we wanted
to poke fun at AT&T who lately have been taking themselves too
seriously,'' said Sherry Carniglia, the Sprint account director for
Thompson.
   MCI, which is based in Washington, D.C., has been using a series
of ads that show no-nonsense business types who describe a wide
range of MCI services that they say helps businesses operate more
efficiently and at lower cost.
   In one ad, an MCI technical supervisor looks wistfully out his
office window and says, ``Maybe some day we'll work 9 to 5. At
least that's what I tell my wife.'' In another ad, a comptroller
snaps, ``I want to know where every dollar is going,'' and adds
that MCI's billing itemizes every call.
   But the Sprint admakers also wanted to be noticed, and felt
Sedelmaier's deft touch for making people smile could help them do
that.
   Sprint, a joint venture of GTE Corp. of Stamford, Conn., and
United Telecommunications Inc. of Kansas City, Mo., is running
behind AT&T and MCI in the estimated $50 billion a year
long-distance market.
   Jack Grubman, telecommunications analyst for the investment firm
PaineWebber, estimates AT&T has about 72-73 percent of the
intercity long-distance market, while MCI had about 10 percent and
Sprint about 7 percent.
   The companies refuse to say how much they spend on advertising.
   Burke Stinson, an AT&T district manager in New York, said the
company knew that the grim ads it put on the air last winter would
make some people uneasy, but believed they would get the attention
of decisionmakers in small- and medium-size businesses.
   He said the plan always had been to run the first wave of ads
for about six months, and then phase them out by the fall as a
second wave of ads rolled out that featured bright AT&T employees
talking about what the company offers.
   ``The plan was to get people's attention. Then the question has
to be `How are you going to help me?''' Stinson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880715-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0309EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Gillette-Coniston Bjt   07-15 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gillette-Coniston, Bjt,0633</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Analysts: Rematch Would Give Coniston New Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court-ordered rematch of the proxy fight beween
Coniston Group and Gillette Co. would be unprecedented and would
strengthen the New York partnership's attempt to control the
personal care giant, according to industry analysts.
   A federal judge said Wednesday he was inclined to order a new
proxy vote in the six-month battle because Gillette misled
stockholders about Coniston before the election.
   Analysts said institutional investors, seeking a quick profit
from the personal care giant, probably own more Gillette stock than
before the April vote and would be more likely to back Coniston's
dissident slate of board candidates.
   Coniston controls about 5.8 percent of Gillette's common shares
outstanding. The partnership wants to win board seats to pressure
the 12-member Gillette board to sell the company, which Coniston
believes would boost the value of its stock.
   ``I think it's safe to assume that there are more arbitragers
holding Gillette today than back in March,'' said Nancy Hall, an
analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham. ``I think that Gillette is
definitely viewed as a speculative plot.''
   Judges in the past have ordered new proxy votes, but that
typically has been in cases involving huge vote discrepancies where
a new vote was deemed irrelevant. The Gillette case is rarer
because it involves information a judge determined could have
affected the outcome.
   ``The court found that there was something misleading,'' said
Robert Todd Lang, a partner with the New York law firm Weil
Gotschal & Manges. ``This doesn't happen very often. Usually when
you have a challenge it's a challenge to the tally.''
   In the April 21 election, Gillette's 27,000 shareholders
rejected Coniston's slate of four candidates to the board by 52
percent to 48 percent proportion.
   U.S. District Judge Mark L. Wolf said at Wednesday's hearing
that he was inclined to order a new election because ``the essence
of the election was tainted in a material way.''
   Last week, Wolf ruled Gillette misled stockholders about
Coniston in newspaper advertisements leading up to the proxy vote.
He also said a failure by Boston-based Gillette to disclose a
series of standstill agreements with potential suitors was not
misleading and would not have affected the election.
   Wolf scheduled a trial the week of Aug. 22 on Gillette's charges
that Coniston violated federal securities laws by failing to
disclose the limited partners in RB Partners, a Bahamian company
formed to buy Gillette stock.
   The judge said Wednesday that regardless of his ruling in the
second phase of the case, he is likely to order the new vote.
Coniston has asked for a new election of eight directors in the
fall, pre-empting Gillette's normal spring meeting.
   Coniston principal Augustus K. Oliver said stockholders would
consider the standstill agreements _ under which 10 companies
agreed not to attempt to buy Gillette for two years ending in
November _ if Wolf orders a new election.
   ``I think there's a totally new mix of information available to
stockholders,'' Oliver said. ``We'll just have to see next time
around whether that's enough to change things.''
   Gillette sued Coniston in April, alleging the securities law
violations. The New York investment firm responded with its claim
of misrepresentation.
   The counterclaim was heard in court first because Judge Rya
Zobel, then handling the case, felt that if Coniston lost its
challenge to the proxy vote then Gillette's case would be moot.
   ``The judge indicated he was still evolving his thinking and he
hasn't come up with a remedy yet,'' Gillette spokesman David Fausch
said. ``One of the remedies that is possible is a new election.
Let's take that at face value.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
