<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FarmersInsurance     07-15 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farmers Insurance,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers Welcomes Oregon Rejection Of Hostile Takeover Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Farmers Group Inc. says a hostile
takeover attempt of the company by a British conglomerate should be
dropped following the rejection of the plan by Oregon's insurance
commissioner.
   Batus Inc., a Louisville, Ky.-based subsidiary of the British
B.A.T. Industries PLC, has offered $4.5 billion for the Los
Angeles-based Farmers. Farmers directors rejected the proposal.
   Oregon Insurance Commissioner Ted Kulongoski concluded on
Thursday that the proposed buyout of Farmers Insurance Co. of
Oregon would adversely affect Farmers' policyholders and
competition in Oregon's insurance trade.
   Kulongoski cited the intention of Batus, which owns a major
tobacco company, to restrict the non-smoker policies sold by
Farmers.
   ``Director Kulongoski's decision on this matter confirms our
belief that this proposed transaction would ultimately be
detrimental to Farmers and its Oregon policyholders,'' said Leo E.
Denlea Jr., Farmers' chairman.
   Batus said in a statement it was ``completely astonished'' by
the decision.
   ``A cursory reading of the decision strongly suggests that the
commissioner has reached conclusions that are contrary to law and
appear to be unsupported by the record and the facts,'' a spokesman
said.
   Kulongoski's order can be appealed to the courts. The takeover
bid as now structured would require approval of insurance
regulators in nine states.
   California's insurance commissioner also has rejected the
proposal, and Arizona has approved it.
   ``Following the recent decision by the California Department of
Insurance, this is a second very significant setback to Batus'
unwanted hostile takeover attempt,'' Denlea said. ``We believe that
Batus will face further regulatory difficulties in current and
pending reviews by other state insurance departments.''
   Kulongoski, citing his role as hearings officer in the case,
made only limited remarks outside his statements in the order.
   He said the case is unique in Oregon insurance history because
it does not involve a troubled insurer being acquired by a more
financially sound company.
   ``Rather, it is the proposed acquisition of a very well-managed
company by a larger company seeking to diversify into the financial
services market in this country,'' Kulongoski said.
   Batus' statement also took issue with Kulongoski's
characterization of Farmers as well-managed.
   The ``statement to the effect that this is not a financially
distressed company, but rather a well-managed one being acquired by
a larger company seeking to diversify, suggests that the decision
is anti-takeover, rather than protection for the policyholders,''
the statement said.
   The commissioner in his ruling said the proposed acquisition
``subjects policyholders and shareholders to substantial risks
while providing no benefit that Farmers does not already enjoy.''
   He also said the continued denials by B.A.T. and Batus ``of the
known adverse health effects of tobacco smoking, and its stated
intentions of precluding Farmers from referring to such health
effects in its marketing literature, do not promote the interest of
the insurance-buying public.''
   Batus owns Brown & Williamson Tobacco Corp. along with retail
concerns including Saks Fifth Avenue and Marshall Field's.
</TEXT>
