<HEAD>Dollar Rises on Trade Report</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: updates with dollar rising strongly after trade report.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose strongly today after the U.S.
government reported that the U.S. merchandise trade deficit widened
to $10.9 billion in May, less than expected.
   Gold prices fell in morning trading.
   The dollar rose almost one cent against the British pound and
nearly one Japanese yen in London after the Commerce Department
reported the second smallest deficit in almost three years. The
U.S. currency also surged higher in New York trading.
   The markets had been predicting a deficit of around $11 billion
after a deficit of $9.9 billion in April.
   The dollar had moved higher in calm European trading in advance
of the report. Foreign exchange dealers said that although market
turnover was somewhat subdued ahead of the announcement, the
currency was buoyed by optimism over the trade deficit.
   In London, it cost $1.6730 to buy one pound after the report,
cheaper than $1.6820 at midmorning and $1.6890 late Thursday.
   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday's
prices, included: 1.8655 West German marks, up from 1.8475; 1.5465
Swiss francs, up from 1.5320; 6.2860 French francs, up from 6.2315;
2.1030 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0815; 1,380.98 Italian lire, up
from 1,367.75; 1.2088 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2085.
   In Tokyo, the dollar ended the week at 133.40 yen, up 0.45 yen
from Thursday's close. Later, in London, after the release of the
report, it was quoted at 134.75 yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $438 a troy ounce and at
midmorning the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $438.10. Both were lower than Thursday's late
bid of $439.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $438, down from late Thursday's
$441. Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold dropped 48 cents an ounce to
close at a bid of $440.05.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $7.30 late this
morning, down from late Thursday's $7.35.
</TEXT>
