<HEAD>London Stocks Sharply Lower At Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were sharply lower Friday in
anticipation of a possible rise in British interest rates.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was down 11.1
points, or 0.6 percent, at 1,852.2 at midday. Volume was light at
288.8 million shares, compared with 297.8 million shares at the
same time Thursday.
   The index was fell sharply as expectations increased that the
British commercial banks' base lending rate might rise above the
current 10 percent.
   Late in the morning, the government reported that Britain's
retail price index rose 0.4 percent in June from May and was up 4.6
percent from June 1987.
   The annual inflation rate was at the high end of market
expectations, and confirmed expectations tht interest rates might
be headed higher in the near term.
   Jeffrey Thompson, an equities strategist at Barclays de Zoete
Wedd Ltd., said he doubted the Bank of England would engineer a
base rate rise ahead of the release of the U.S. trade numbers.
   ``Monday could certainly provide the right sort of opportunity''
he said, adding: ``I think we're in for a spell of inflation and
interest rate fears over the next few weeks.''
