<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Macmillan-Bass     07-15 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Macmillan-Bass,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Macmillan To Appeal Injunction Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Macmillan Inc. said it would appeal a judge's
ruling that blocks the publishing giant from proceeding with a
massive massive restructuring designed to thwart an unwanted bid
from the Robert Bass Group.
   After nearly five weeks of consideration, Jack B. Jacobs of the
Delaware Chancery Court on Thursday issued a 58-page opinion
granting Bass's request for a preliminary injunction that
effectively blocks the restructuring.
   Macmillan said in a statement that it was taking an expedited
appeal to the Delaware Supreme Court in an effort to reverse the
decision.
   An unidentified Macmillan spokesman said in the statement that
Jacobs' ruling was ``erroneous as a matter of law'' and that
Macmillan was confident of succeeding on appeal.
   The ruling came after the close of the stock market. But in
trading on te New York Stock Exchange, Macmillan fell 50 cents to
$74 on Thursday.
   Josy Ingersoll, an attorney representing the Texas-based Bass
group, had no comment on whether Bass would proceed with a tender
offer. The group previously had said it would launch a tender offer
upon granting of a preliminary injunction.
   ``There's no action to prevent anybody from doing a tender
offer,'' she said. The Bass group also has said it has the
necessary financing to complete its $1.9 billion buyout.
   Bass originally offered to acquire Macmillan for $64 a share in
May, but raised his bid to $73 a share, or about $1.9 billion for
the 90.1 percent of Macmillan shares the group does not already own
after the publisher unveiled its restructuring plan.
   Ingersoll said the judge found that Macmillan's attempt to
restructure was an unreasonable response to Bass's takeover
proposal.
   Based on legal precedents, ``when a board does something in
reaction to an offer for the company, there has to be a threat ...
and there wasn't a threat'' in this case, she said from her
Wilmington, Del. office.
   Bass had charged that Macmillan's restructuring, which would
have separated the company's information services and publishing
operations into two separate, publicly traded companies, was
inadequate and misleading. The group also charged that the plan
would have transferred control to four top Macmillan executives for
a cheap price.
   In rejecting Bass's buyout offer as well as a counter proposal
to restructure the company, Macmillan repeatedly said its own plan
was in the best interest of shareholders.
   Macmillan was just hours away from beginning its restructuring,
which included paying shareholders a special $52.35-a-share
dividend, when Jacobs issued a temporary restraining order on June
10.
   Bass's restructuring plan would pay shareholders a dividend of
$58 per share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880715-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1013EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Labor     07-15 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Labor,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Calls For Improved Working, Living Conditions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government report, noting that Japanese work
longer than people in other industrialized nations but have less
buying power, calls for improved working and living conditions in
this country.
   The report, issued by the Labor Ministry Friday, urged shorter
work weeks, lower consumer prices, more housing land and cheaper
housing.
   The report said Japanese worked an average 2,150 hours in 1986,
the last year for which such statistics were available, compared to
1,938 hours for Britons, 1,924 hours for Americans, 1,655 hours for
West Germans and 1,643 hours for the French, said Atsuko Ishii of
the ministry's Labor Affairs Division.
   Of Japan's total workforce of 60.8 million, 59.11 were employed
in 1987, for an unemployment rate of 2.8 percent compared to 6.2
percent in the United States, 7.9 percent in West Germany, 10.4
percent in Britain and 10.6 percent in France, according to Miss
Ishii.
   Japan calculates its unemployment rate differently from other
Western countries, counting its armed forces and those who work as
little as one hour a month. Japanese officials say Japan's official
rate would be about double if it were calculated by Western methods.
   Women accounted for 36.5 percent of the work force last year,
the report said.
   The average worker's annual salary in 1987 was 4.99 million yen,
or $38,380, including summer and winter bonuses, Miss Ishii quoted
the report as saying.
   Workers in primary industry _ farming, forestry, fishing and
mining _ numbered 5.41 million, or 9.3 percent of all workers, in
1985, the most recent year for which statistics were available, she
said.
   In the secondary or manufacturing industry, there were 19.33
million workers, or 33.1 percent of the working population.
   The largest number of workers in 1985 were 33.44 million in
tertiary industry, defined as power and water supply, transport,
communications, sales, food, financial, real estate and public
sectors, the report said. They represented 53.7 percent of Japan's
working population that year, Miss Ishii said.
   The report noted 18.9 percent of Japan's workforce was older
than 55 last year, as opposed to 12.9 percent in the United States
and 10.2 percent in West Germany.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880715-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1013EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     07-15 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0297</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices headed higher today, inspired by
news of a smaller-than-expected monthly U.S. trade deficit
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 6.93 to 2,120.55 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 7 to 4 in the early tally of
New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 531 up, 300 down and
501 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 43.21 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   The dollar jumped after the Commerce Department reported that
the merchandise trade deficit in May was $10.9 billion, the second
smallest in almost three years. The April deficit was revised
upward to $10.3 billion from $9.9 billion.
   In other economic news, the Labor Department said wholesale
prices rose 0.4 percent in June despite a drought that sent prices
for raw food soaring at their steepest pace in more than 2{ years.
   Industrial production rose 0.4 percent in June, the ninth
consecutive month without a decline, the Federal Reserve said.
   Among blue-chip issues, International Business Machines stock
gained 1 to 125}. The company said its second-quarter profit fell
18.1 because of a restructuring charge. Earnings would have risen
12.7 percent without the charge.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
.29 to 153.05. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .44 at 308.58.
   On Thursday the Dow Jones industrial average rose 9.25 to
2,113.62.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 5 to 4 on the
NYSE, with 773 up, 636 down and 537 unchanged. Big Board volume
came to 172.41 million shares, against 218.93 million in the
previous session.
</TEXT>
