<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Lower, Turn Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened lower but
quickly turned mixed in volatile activity today on the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   Analysts attributed the lower opening to a continuation of the
profit-taking that surfaced late in Thursday's session following
two days of sharply higher prices.
   Forecasts for another month of hot, dry weather in the parched
Corn Belt provided incentive for traders to bid prices higher this
morning but uncertainty about the prospects for rain next week
added an element of edginess to the markets, analysts said,
   ``People are not sure we're not going to get another rain front
in the middle of next week and the markets are very, very
nervous,'' said Ted Mao, grain specialist in New York with Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc.
   In early trading, wheat was 3 cents to 7 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.91 a bushel; corn was 3{ cents
lower to 1} cents higher with July at $3.36 a bushel; oats were 1
cent lower to 3 cents higher with July at $3.07 a bushel; soybeans
were unchanged to 15{ cents higher with July at $9.81 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .20 cent lower to .25 cent higher with August
at 64.35 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .85 cent
higher with August at 74.65 cents a pound; hogs were .27 cent lower
to .65 cent higher with July at 45.77 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .80 cent to 1.40 cents higher with July at 36.70 cents
a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Thursday.
</TEXT>
