<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1318EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-MagicChefPresident     07-15 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Magic Chef President,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rymer Out, Creagan In As Magic Chef President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWTON, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J. Hoyle Rymer has resigned as president of
the Magic Chef Co., which was founded by his grandfather S.B. Rymer
in 1916, officials of Maytag Corp. said Friday.
   Magic Chef, a manufacturer of cooking appliances such as stoves
and microwave ovens and marketer of a full line of major home
appliances, merged with Maytag in May 1986. Magic Chef is based in
Cleveland, Tenn.
   C. Wayne Creagan, president of Maytag's diversified products
division, will take over Aug. 1 for Rymer, Maytag Chairman Daniel
J. Krumm said.
   Rymer, 43, has been president of Magic Chef since 1978. His
resignation is effective Aug. 1.
   ``I think he just wants to pursue personal interests and other
business interests,'' said Maytag spokesman Jim Powell.
   Maytag had sales of $1.9 billion in 1987. Magic Chef had net
sales of $975 million in 1985, its last full year of operation
before the merger.
   Powell said the corporation does not break out sales figures for
its 14 divisions.
   Maytag previously reported that its profits in the first three
months of this year dropped to $32.5 million, or 43 cents a share,
from a record $41.2 million, or 49 cents a share, in the same
period last year.
   Rymer had served as the general manager of Magic Chef's
microwave division, company vice president of operations and was
elected to the board of directors in 1977.
   Creagan, 59, joined Maytag in 1948, working in the engineering
department and serving as the company's vice president of labor
relations. He became senior vice president of human resources when
Maytag and Magic Chef merged and was elected to Maytag's board of
directors in February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880715-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1323EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Icahn-Texaco Bjt   07-15 0795</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Icahn-Texaco, Bjt,0823</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Icahn Can Sell Texaco Stock Soon _ But Will He?</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY30</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like a casino player fingering the chips in his
pocket, corporate raider Carl C. Icahn is likely to wait awhile
before he walks up to the window and cashes in his Texaco Inc.
stock for a multimillion-dollar prize.
   The beleagured oil giant's largest shareholder and most vocal
critic is just days away from being able to sell his roughly 36
million shares and keep the profits.
   But will he?
   Speaking from his new offices in Mount Kisco, N.Y., Icahn said
that ``at this point we haven't made any decision yet'' about the
14.8 percent Texaco stake.
   He noted there is ``a myriad of possibilities _ including doing
nothing _ and we've made no determination of what we're going to
do.''
   Under the ``short-swing'' profit rule, a holder of more than 5
percent of a company's stock must keep those shares for at least
six months, otherwise any profits revert back to the company. That
period ends Wednesday for Icahn.
   Texaco stock traded at just over $45 a share on Friday. At that
price, Icahn has a paper profit of about $410 million, based on his
average purchase price of $34 a share.
   Wall Streeters agree Icahn is least likely to just dump the
shares on the open market, considering the depressing effect such a
move would have on Texaco's stock price.
   ``The bottom line is that neither Texaco nor Icahn want to see
the shares go down,'' said Paul Ting, an analyst at the investment
firm Oppenheimer & Co.
   Far more handsome would be the sale of Icahn's shares in a block
to a third party willing to pay a heftier price. At $60 a share,
the price Icahn put on the table in his proposed $14 billion-plus
buyout, he would reap nearly a billion in profits.
   Icahn would not comment on whether he had spoken recently with
Husky Oil Ltd. or Gulf Canada Ltd., two companies with whom he once
discussed a joint Texaco bid.
   ``It's impossible to know if he is under pressure to liquidate
something,'' said Rosario Ilacqua, a vice president at Nikko
Securities Co. International Inc. ``But if he believes the assets
are worth $70 to $80 a share, why would he sell at $46?''
   When asked whether Texaco had been in contact with Icahn
regarding the disposition of his holdings, a spokeswoman said the
White Plains, N.Y.-based company ``does not comment on the
activities of our shareholders.''
   But a source close to the company said, ``Obviously (Texaco) is
concerned about Icahn, they know that he is not someone you take
lightly.''
   ``I would assume Texaco management would like to get him out,
and get their stock up in the $50s,'' Ilacqua said.
   Icahn's concession of defeat in a heated proxy contest for five
seats on Texaco's board does not put the oil giant's managment in
the clear.
   Some experts speculate Icahn might be waiting to see just how
close he came in the battle, which took place last month at the
company's annual meeting. Texaco has said it would take between
three and four weeks for an official tally, and results are
expected soon.
   Icahn, who also heads TWA Corp., was dealt what might have been
a fatal blow in the fight by the aggressive leveraged buyout firm
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co., which voted its 4.9 percent stake
for Texaco management.
   In conceding defeat shortly after Kohlberg's announcement, Icahn
called the company's stake the swing vote.
   But analysts are not so sure. One suggested Icahn's losing
margin may have been far wider than he has let on.
   ``If it had been a close call, he wouldn't have conceded
defeat,'' said one analyst who asked not to be quoted by name.
``His nature is being a battler, stubborn and persistent.''
   Meanwhile, Texaco is knee-deep in its own restructuring, which
includes a $3 billion payment to Pennzoil Co. to settle a lawsuit
resulting from Texaco's 1984 acquisition of Getty Oil Co. after
Pennzoil had made earlier moves to acquire Getty.
   In addition, Texaco has begun selling off up to $5 billion worth
of marginally profitable assets and says it will distribute $1.7
billion of the proceeds to shareholders.
   That, coupled with the $3-a-share annual dividend the oil
company has resumed paying already spells a decent return for Icahn.
   Wall Street insiders look upon Icahn as a ``trader type,''
someone whose long-term strategy may be vague and whose forte is
quick decisions.
   A month ago one analyst said he would ``rather go to Vegas''
than predict what Icahn might do. When asked again this week, he
said he would still rather go to the gambling resort.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880715-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1333EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   07-15 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices finished marginally lower Friday on
London's Stock Exchange as the market was stumped by U.S. trade
figures.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished the
session off 1.8 points, or 0.1 percent, at 1,861.5.
   Trading volume was a healthy 591.5 million shares, compared with
Thursday's 526.6 million shares.
   The Commerce Department reported that the U.S. merchandise trade
deficit widened to $10.9 billion in May from a revised $10.3
billion shortfall in April. But the latest deficit came well within
the expected range.
   ``We would've known what to do had it been high or low, but when
the figures came in close to home, we didn't know what to do with
it,'' one equity salesman said.
   Glenn Davies, an equity analyst at CL-Alexanders Laing
Cruickshank Ltd., said the trade figures amounted to ``damp
fireworks'' for equities.
   ``Financial markets are beginning to prepare themselves for
another interest rate hike,'' Davies said.
   A government report that Britain's retail price index rose 0.4
percent in June compared with May and was up 4.6 percent from June
1987, heightened suspicions that British interest rates might be
headed higher.
   ``People are definitely concerned about higher interest rates,''
one analyst said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880715-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv15   07-15 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 15,0701</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday, July 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>Consumer Attitudes, The Best Bet Against Inflation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Everyone is worrying about inflation, but a lot
of folks are doing something about it, and they just might have the
final say.
   Those folks are consumers, and they have been resisting price
increases for several years now and seem intent on continuing their
vigilance. This isn't an assumption; the activity shows up in
official statistics.
   The measurements that prove the case are the gross national
product implicit price deflator and the gross national product
fixed-weight price index.
   For practical purposes, the important thing to remember about
the fixed-weight price index is that it measures only changes in
prices, and these prices are of the same products month after month.
   The implicit price deflator is a bit more sophisticated,
measuring not just prices but changes in the composition of
purchases. It has been rising much more slowly than its more rigid
cousin.
   The importance of this disparity is that it indicates a
resistance to price increases by consumers. They have continued to
buy, but they have avoided items rising in price and, when
possible, switched to more stable items.
   Such behavior is enormously significant, suggesting a
fundamental change in consumer attitudes from earlier periods.
   An analysis by Wright Investors' Service contrasts this price
resistance to the attitude that prevailed during much of the 1960s
and 1970s, when consumers simply went ahead and bought. In fact,
many consumers bought more than they needed at any given time,
convinced that future prices would be even higher.
   Those were very different times. Consumers were fatalistic,
convinced that they could have little impact on pricing factors.
Why try to hold down the budget when OPEC was forcing up gasoline
and heating oil prices?
   But there was more to it than that. Many workers had broad
cost-of-living increases built into union contracts, enabling them
to offset higher prices. Industry's attitude toward wage increases
was simply to give in and then raise prices. And, for reasons not
explained logically, there existed a feeling that inflation was a
way of life that couldn't be disciplined.
   In those days, the two indicators of inflation rose in relation
to each other. It was only in the 1980s that they began to diverge,
indicating that consumers felt they could do something about
pricing, such as declining to buy.
   This relatively new sense of consumer power is especially
noticeable in automobile sales, which for several years have relied
on incentives. Take away those incentives and sales dive; replace
them and they rise again.
   It has occurred in housing sales as well, as many would-be
sellers in some of the more affluent neighborhoods have discovered
over the past few months. Houses that a year ago sold within days
of listing, now remain on the market for months, even though
mortgages have been relatively easy to obtain.
   Some retailers are complaining, but in view of today's consumer
attitude you might say they should have known better. Early this
year apparel prices rose sharply, followed quickly by sales
problems for many apparel retailers.
   The new attitude hasn't been lost on producers of services and
manufactured goods, many of whom have chosen to absorb higher costs
in order to maintain sales, rather than pass on increases and lose
customer loyalty.
   The resistance applies even to interest rates. Strange as it
sounds to some folks who couldn't get an appointment with a bank
loan officer a few years ago, many banks now advertise for
customers, especially for home loans.
   The new attitude can be found in, of all places, wage
settlements. Learning from the 1970s, when wage increases were more
than offset by price increases, workers have been seeking less,
opting instead for wage-price stability.
   It is encouraging news, this inflation fight by a lot of
ordinary folks. Together, they make an anti-inflation force as
strong as almost any other, perhaps even matching the vaunted power
of the august Federal Reserve Board.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday, July 15.</NOTE>
</DOC>
