<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1355EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AudiVerdict     07-15 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Audi Verdict,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Brain-Damaged in Audi Crash Awarded Nearly $2.2 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   German automaker Audi says it will appeal a
jury's award of nearly $2.2 million to a brain-damaged woman
injured in a crash the jury blamed partly on an alleged defect in
her car.
   A Superior Court jury made the award Wednesday to Diane Rose,
53, who was injured when her 1981 Audi 5000S crashed into a wall as
she drove down Benedict Canyon in May 1982.
   The jury agreed with Mrs. Rose's lawyers' contention that the
accident was caused by a design defect that places the car's gas
and brake pedals too close together. Jurors found Audi 75 percent
at fault and Ms. Rose 25 percent responsible for leaving her seat
belt unbuckled.
   Audi denies there is any defect, and argued that Mrs. Rose took
a curve too fast and lost control, said spokesman Joseph Bennett at
Audi of America Inc. in Troy, Mich. The company, a division of
Volkswagen of America Inc., will appeal the decision, he said
Thursday.
   Mrs. Rose was alone in the car and there were no witnesses. The
case rested on testimony of expert witnesses from each side.
   The case is unrelated to uncontrolled acceleration problems in
automatic-transmission Audi 5000S models that prompted a 1987
recall of all 240,000 Audi 5000 models sold in this country since
1978. The cars were fitted with shift-lock devices which require a
driver to press the brake pedal before operating the automatic
transmission.
   In addition to the almost $2.2 million award to Mrs. Rose, the
jury awarded her husband, Joseph, $700,000 for his suffering.
   Mrs. Rose suffered a broken neck, brain damage and bladder
problems and has incurred medical expenses of more than $500,000,
her lawyers said.
   The jury found Volkwagen innocent of malice despite the design
defect, ruling the company did not deliberately disregard the
rights and safety of others.
   The Audi 5000 has been recalled twice before: In 1982 to raise
the height of the brake pedal so the brakes will work even if the
driver steps on the brake and accelerator pedal at the same time;
and in 1981 to anchor floor carpets so they couldn't slide up over
the accelerator and keep it from rising when the driver's foot is
removed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880715-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1424EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Coleco     07-15 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coleco,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bankruptcy Papers Show Coleco Has Negative Net Worth Of $156
Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coleco Industries Inc., which
earlier this week filed for protection under Chapter 11 of the
federal bankruptcy law, said in court papers it has a negative net
worth of $156 million.
   The toy manufacturer listed assets of $384.3 million and
liabilities of $540.3 million in its petition filed late Monday in
U.S. Bankruptcy Court for the Southern District of New York.
   The West Hartford-based company, whose fortunes rose and fell
with the popularity of Cabbage Patch Kids dolls, said it owes
$104.3 million to secured creditors, including $94.4 million to 11
foreign and U.S. banks that loaned it money to finance daily
operations.
   It also owes $335 million to investors who bought Coleco bonds
during four separate issues over the past several years. The
company is in default on interest payments on those bonds.
   Coleco owes another $135.2 million to more than 1,200 other
creditors. Among the 20 largest creditors are six manufacturing
firms in Hong Kong owed $13.69 million. Most of the company's toys
have been made in Hong Kong.
   A Chapter 11 filing allows a company protection from its
creditors while it reorganizes and works out a plan for paying its
debts.
   The bankruptcy papers also showed that Coleco's board of
directors, aware of the company's deteriorating financial position,
first authorized the Chapter 11 filing nearly three months ago
during an April 15 meeting. The board voted last week to file on
Monday.
   Coleco has said it had to file for protection from creditors
because it could not persuade banks and debt holders to restructure
its heavy debt load. Without a restructuring, the company said, it
could not obtain financing to guarantee it could continue producing
toys.
   The papers also revealed that 35 creditors owed a total of $2.7
million have sued Coleco, including landlords seeking overdue rent
and suppliers seeking payment for business forms, heating oil, and
packaging.
   The largest case explained in the bankruptcy petition is one
filed May 19 by Concord Express Inc., a California air freight
company that is seeking payment of $1.5 million. Concord shipped
toys for the company for several months last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
