<DOCNO> AP880715-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1425EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Eastern-Machinists     07-15 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Eastern-Machinists,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern, Machinists Far Apart, Negotiator Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines and its combative Machinists union
are $200 million apart on terms of a new contract, according to a
company negotiator, even though the union says it has made a series
of concessions.
   Meanwhile, the steadily shrinking airline is considering
abandoning Palm Beach International Airport, according to a report
published Friday.
   The protracted negotiations between Eastern and the Machinists
have prompted the concern of Florida's congressional delegation,
which is circulating a letter that would ask the National Mediation
Board to expedite the talks.
   The letter asks the board to set ``a definite time frame for
resolution'' of the problems, according to an aide to Rep. Charles
Bennett, a Jacksonville, Fla., Democrat, but does not ask for a
30-day cooling-off period.
   Eastern's negotiators say the union's latest proposal, made
Wednesday, is ``disappointing.''
   In a letter circulated to Eastern managers, chief negotiator
Thomas Matthews claimed the Machinists' proposal would cost the
carrier $50 million a year, while the company was demanding $160
million in cost cuts.
   ``The parties are now more than $200 million apart,'' he wrote.
   Machinists negotiator Roy Anderson responded that his union has
made a steady string of concessions in an effort to win a new
contract, but Eastern has rejected them.
   The Machinists' latest two-year proposal calls for a 1.5 percent
pay raise in the first year and a 5 percent increase in the second
year, compared with the two 10 percent raises the union asked for
when the talks began.
   Anderson said the union also has agreed to more flexible work
rules and Eastern's voluntary job retraining program.
   The Palm Beach Post reported Friday that sources in the Eastern
Machinists and pilots unions, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the negotiations include stipulations by Eastern that it will
cut back and perhaps abandon operations at the Palm Beach airport
as early as this fall.
   Eastern's gates are the second-busiest at Palm Beach
International, where Delta Air Lines carries around 26 percent of
the passenger traffic and Eastern about 23 percent. Eastern
operates 14 flights a day out of the airport, and increases that
number by four or five during the winter.
   But Eastern has been retrenching for the past year, pulling out
of some markets in favor of those areas where business is stronger.
   Eastern spokesman Roger Powell said the fall flight schedule
won't be released for several weeks, but that union claims that
Eastern is facing a 20 percent to 25 percent reduction in flight
hours ``is probably pretty factual.''
   ``Surely (the fall schedule) hasn't been put to bed yet, and
it'll probably change 50 times before it is put to bed,'' Powell
said. ``As it now stands, we may see a reduction. But we have no
intentions of withdrawing from Palm Beach.''
   Eastern is a subsidiary of Houston-based Texas Air Corp., the
nation's largest airline company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880715-0268 </DOCNO>
