<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Ford-LandPurchase     07-15 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ford-Land Purchase,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Buying Land Adjacent to Avon Lake Plant, Wants EPA Expansion
Permit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. said Friday it will purchase 108
acres for possible expansion next to its Avon Lake, Ohio, truck
plant, which has been suggested as a site for a Ford-Nissan joint
venture.
   Ford applied June 2 for an Environmental Protection Agency
permit to install environmental equipment that would be required
for expansion or new construction, Ford spokeswoman Judith Muhlberg
said.
   EPA spokesman Allen Franks said the agency has conducted an
initial review of the application but is awaiting further
information about the project, which Ford is expected to submit
within a month.
   ``Our engineers are looking at Aug. 11 to get together and go
over the additional information and review the full permit
application,'' Franks said. If Ford decided to go ahead with
construction, it would have to apply for a separate permit to
operate the equipment.
   Ford officials declined to give details on the possible
expansion or new construction, saying only that making such an EPA
application is routine when either are being considered because the
federal process takes so long.
   Ford and Nissan Motor Co. Ltd, based in Japan, said earlier this
year that they had decided to move into the second stage of a study
of a possible joint venture, examining potential plant sites,
vehicles and parts sources.
   But Ford spokesman Jay Meisenhelder cautioned against connecting
the land purchase and the EPA application to the joint venture,
often reported to be a Ford-Nissan minivan.
   ``We haven't made a decision that there's even going to be a
joint venture. It's pure speculation at this point,'' Meisenhelder
said.
   Ford exercised an option on the land but had yet to close the
purchase, Meisenhelder added.
   The 1 million-square-foot, 1,500-worker Avon Lake plant builds
and paints bodies for Econoline vans and Club Wagons. The bodies
are trucked to Ford's Lorain, Ohio, assembly plant, where they are
married to chassis.
   The Lorain plant is Ford's largest in the world at 3.3 million
square feet, Muhlberg said. It also builds Ford Thunderbird and
Mercury Cougar cars.
   Ford bought the Avon Lake site from Fruehauf Corp. in 1972. It
added 60 acres to its original 170 acres in 1973. The new purchase
brings the site's total acreage to 338.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
