<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   07-15 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grains, Soybeans Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain futures closed mixed while soybeans posted
strong gains Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid conflicting
weather forecasts for the drought-stricken Farm Belt.
   Forecasts for next week's weather were so mixed that ``every
time I pick up the telephone I hear a different one,'' said John
Frazier, Chicago-based grain specialist with Balfour Maclaine Corp.
   Temperatures soared above 100 degrees Friday afternoon in
Chicago and some private meteorologists were calling for dry
conditions and searing temperatures to linger in the Midwest
through Thursday.
   ``If that's true, we're going to go higher and higher next
week,' Frazier said.
   But Frazier said other forecasters expected cooler temperatures
and scattered showers to move into the region this weekend.
   ``We're in the hands of the weather and the weatherman,'' he
said.
   The mixed finish ended a week marked by wide swings in futures
prices. For example, soybeans for July delivery ranged during the
week from $8.56 to $10.20 a bushel.
   At the close, wheat was 3 cents lower to 5 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.85 a bushel; corn was 7{ cents
lower to 1 cent higher with July at $3.32 a bushel; oats were 1
cent to 7{ cents higher with July at $3.11{ a bushel; soybeans were
3 cents to 33{ cents higher with July at $9.95 a bushel.
</TEXT>
