<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0718EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Motorola     07-15 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Motorola,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Motorola Net Jumps 50 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCHAUMBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Second-quarter profits at Motorola Inc.
soared 50 percent amid sharply higher sales of the company's
communications and computer products, the suburban Chicago firm
said Thursday.
   Motorola reported net income of $120 million, or 93 cents per
share, for the three months ended June 30, compared with $80
million, or 62 cents per share for the same period a year ago.
   Second-quarter sales rose 27 percent to $2.09 billion from $1.64
billion a year earlier.
   Motorola's computer and cellular telephone unit showed the
greatest improvement in the second quarter with a 43 percent
increase in sales and an 84 percent leap in orders, the company
said.
   Sales of semiconductors increased 27 percent in the quarter
while sales of two-way radio systems and paging equipment advanced
25 percent.
   ``We continue to see strong growth in our major businesses,
consistent with the trends of the last two years,'' said Chairman
Robert W. Galvin in a statement.
   He noted that Motorola products were gaining acceptance around
the world.
   For the first half of 1988, Motorola reported a 72 percent
increase in net income to $234 million, or $1.81 per share,
compared with $136 million, or $1.06 per share during the
year-earlier period.
   Sales totaled $4.04 billion in the first half, compared with
$3.19 billion a year ago.
</TEXT>
