<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Britain-Rover     07-15 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Rover,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Aerospace to Proceed with Rover Takeover Despite Aid Cut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Aerospace PLC will go ahead with its
takeover of Rover Group PLC despite conditions the European
Commission has imposed on the deal, the government said Thursday.
   The commission on Wednesday approved the takeover on the
condition that the British government cut by $428 million the
amount of cash the government is to inject simultaneously into the
state-owned automaker.
   Trade Secretary Lord Young told the House of Lords in an
emergency statement: ``Talks with the European Commission this
morning have clarified the position in terms satisfactory to the
British Aerospace Board.''.
   Young said that the EC commissioners agreed to requests for
certain changes in the details of the deal's treatment of Rover tax
losses.
   British Aerospace had reached an agreement with the government
to acquire its 99.8-percent stake in the automaker for $254
million. At the same time, the government had said it would inject
$1.35 billion into Rover to reduce the automaker's debt.
   But the European Economic Community commission, which has the
power to block deals that it considers harmful to competition in
the 12-nation Common Market, said Wednesday it approved a smaller
aid package of $793 million.
   Because some regional aid also would be allowed, the state
subsidy effectively would be reduced to $924 million, Young said.
   British Aerospace on Wednesday had requested more time to
consider its proposed takeover in light of the conditions.
</TEXT>
