<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SteelImports     07-15 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steel Imports,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Producers Say Steel Imports Surged in May</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel imports surged in May to their highest
level since July 1986, domestic producers said Friday.
   An importers association, interpreting the same Commerce
Department data, said, however, that imports, excluding
semi-finished metal bound for processing on American mills, were
held within the limits of the U.S. steel quota system for the first
five months of the year.
   May imports totaled 1.94 million tons, compared with 1.53
million tons in April and 1.85 million tons in May 1987, according
to the American Iron and Steel Institute.
   Imports of all steel products, including semi-finshed ordered by
U.S. producers, totaled 9.05 million tons, up from 8.4 million tons
in the comparable 1987 period, the Washington-based AISI said.
   ``These figures reinforce the domestic industry's assertion that
the system of voluntary restraint agreements, which has been in
effect since October 1984, should be extended for at least another
five years,'' said the AISI said in a printed statement.
   The American producers said the quotas program ``has fallen
short of its objective for the almost four-year period of its
implementation.''
   Excluding semi-finished steel, January through May imports
totaled 7.8 million tons, or 17.8 percent of apparent domestic
consumption. President Reagan set a limit of 18.5 percent market
penetration when he initiated the quotas.
   American steelmakers imported about 238,000 tons out of the 1.93
million tons imported in May, the New York-based AIIS said.
   ``Steel imports have been a critical support for American steel
producers, who could contiue to meet demand as a result of imported
steel slab,'' said Erwin Klein, AIIS president and vice chairman of
the importing firm Steelinter USA of New York. ``Industry and
government should carefully review the fact that imports relieve
shortages and cut costs.''
</TEXT>
