<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp Bjt   07-15 0786</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp, Bjt,0814</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain Futures End Wild Week With A Whimper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Conflicting weather forecasts for the drought-stricken Farm Belt
brought a wild week of grain trading to a fairly subdued close
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade. Soybeans posted strong gains
but corn and wheat were mixed.
   On other markets, pork bellies surged the limit for daily
trading; precious metals were slightly higher; energy futures were
mixed; and stock index futures advanced.
   Forecasts for next week's weather were so mixed that ``every
time I pick up the telephone I hear a different one,'' said John
Frazier, Chicago-based grain specialist with Balfour Maclaine Corp.
   Temperatures soared above 100 degrees Friday afternoon in
Chicago and some private meteorologists were calling for dry
conditions and searing temperatures to linger in the Midwest
through Thursday.
   But other private forecasters expected cooler temperatures and
scattered showers to move into the region this weekend.
   ``We're in the hands of the weather and the weatherman,''
Frazier said.
   Ted Mao, grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in
New York, agreed: ``People are not sure we're not going to get
another rain front in the middle of next week, and the markets are
very, very nervous.''
   The drought has taken a heavy toll on the corn crop. The
Agriculture Department estimated in a report on Tuesday that 1988
corn production would fall 27 percent below last year, and the
damage mounted during the week as the stunted crop neared the end
of its pollination stage.
   Soybeans will enter a critical growing period within two weeks,
analysts said. The USDA report predicted a 14 percent drop in
soybean production, based on Tuesday's conditions.
   Friday's mixed close ended a week marked by wide swings in
prices. Soybeans for July delivery ranged during the week from
$8.56 to $10.20 a bushel and July corn ranged from $2.86 to $3.50 a
bushel.
   Heavy profit-taking dragged soybeans down to a 5-week low on
Monday. But the USDA crop report renewed fears of heavy yield
losses, and traders responded by bidding prices back up to levels
close to the previous week's highs.
   Wheat settled 4 cents lower to 5 cents higher with the contract
for delivery in July at $3.84 a bushel; corn was 7 cents lower to
1} cents higher with July at $3.33{ a bushel; oats were 1 cent to
7{ cents higher with July at $3.11{ a bushel; soybeans were 7{
cents to 32 cents higher with July at $9.94{ a bushel.
   Frozen pork belly futures continued their recovery from recent
lows near 32 cents a pound amid higher cash prices and retail
featuring of bacon, analysts said.
   Friday's gain of 2 cents a pound _ the maximum allowed _ on
contracts for July and August delivery marked the fourth straight
day of the pork belly rally on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   A decline in hog slaughter numbers lent additional support to
the belly and hog futures, said Dale Durchholz, an analyst with
AgriVisor Services Inc. in Bloomington, Ill.
   Most cattle futures advanced in pre-weekend position-squaring,
analysts said.
   Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .85 cent higher with August
at 64.27 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .80 cent
higher with August at 74.75 cents a pound; hogs were .25 cent lower
to .75 cent higher with July at 46.27 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .68 cent to 2 cents higher with July at 37.30 cents a
pound.
   The soaring dollar kept a lid on the precious metals market
despite the possibility that Peruvian silver miners will launch a
nationwide strike on Monday.
   The dollar soared against several currencies in reaction to the
government's report of a $10.9 billion merchandise trade deficit in
May.
   ``This was a fantastically strong dollar,'' said Bette
Raptopoulos, precious metals analyst for Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. in New York. ``It just surged and put pressure on
outside markets.''
   Gold settled $1 to $1.40 higher with August at $441.30 a troy
ounce; silver was 3 cents higher across the board with July at
$7.31 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures finished mixed on the New York Mercantile
Exchange in light pre-weekend trading that brokers attributed
largely to internal market influences.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 16 cents lower to 10 cents
higher with August at $14.86 a barrel; heating oil was .21 cent to
.45 cent higher with August at 41.12 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .91 cent lower to .01 cent higher with August at 49.73
cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures advanced slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for September delivery of the Standard
& Poor's 500 index settled 1.35 points higher at 272.80.
</TEXT>
