<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmers-BAT,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Battles British Takeover of Insurance Company</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AT-1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Texas lawmaker on Friday charged that British
BAT Industries PLC's $4.5 billion bid for Farmers Insurance Group
threatens jobs and anti-smoking efforts and urged state regulators
to reject the move.
   ``I have serious doubts about whether we should permit ...
hostile takeovers of American companies by foreign firms, which are
not motivated by a long-term commitment to the maintenance of
American jobs or the well-being of the American people,'' said U.S.
Rep. John Bryant, a Dallas Democrat.
   The bid must be approved by nine states in which the insurance
company operates. Oregon and California have rejected the bid. But
Bryant said litigation is planned in California.
   A spokesman for BAT Industries' U.S. subsidiary, the Louisville,
Ky.-based Batus Inc., could not be reached for comment.
   But the company said in a statement that it has extended to Aug.
11 the deadline of its tender offer to purchase all of Farmers'
outstanding common shares for $63 each.
   BAT is the world's largest tobacco company; Farmers, based in
Los Angeles, is a leading U.S. insurance company.
   Hostile takeovers ``have consumed larger and larger shares of
American capital and productive capacity,'' Bryant said, calling
takeovers by foreign-owned companies particularly worrisome.
   Farmers has 1,940 Texas employees, 2,000 agents and more than
1.26 million policy holders in the state. Bryant said the takeover
would ``jeopardize the jobs of employees and the security of
policyholders in Texas,'' many of whom have taken advantage of
premium discounts for non-smokers.
   BAT ``has indicated it does not approve of and would not
continue Farmers' health-oriented, money-saving, anti-smoking
efforts,'' Bryant said.
   Besides offering discounts to non-smokers, the insurance company
produces anti-smoking literature.
</TEXT>
