<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1817EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Bonds     07-15 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bonds,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Edge Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices edged higher in moderate trading
Friday as investors reacted to a surge in the dollar following the
government's report that the U.S. trade deficit for May had not
worsened considerably.
   The Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond rose about \ point, or
about $2.50 for every $1,000 in face amount. Its yield, which moves
inversely to its price, slipped to 9.14 percent from 9.17 percent
late Thursday.
   Long bond prices made the biggest gains, but trading in those
securities was light, said William Sullivan Jr., director of money
market research for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   The bond market had been sluggish during the week in
anticipation of three key economic reports _ on the trade deficit,
producer prices and industrial production, all released Friday
morning.
   But all of the reports were about as expected, and as a result
had little impact on bond prices, analysts said. They said bond
prices got a push, however, from the dollar's rise in foreign
exchange markets.
   ``There were really no jolts or surprises as far as the economic
data,'' Sullivan said. ``But the international markets interpreted
the trade figures very bullishly and the dollar moved up smartly.
The dollar's firmer trend helped support higher bond prices.''
   The Commerce Department reported the deficit widened to $10.9
billion in May, from a revised April figure of $10.3 billion.
   Analysts had expected the trade gap would expand to the $11
billion area. The $10.9 billion imbalance was the second lowest in
almost three years.
   ``The continued improved trend in the trade figures and strength
in the dollar as a result of them have temporarily offset fears of
higher short-term interest rates,'' said Marshall B. Front, an
economist at the Chicago investment and mutual-fund management firm
of Stein Roe & Farnham.
   A sharp widening of the trade gap in the past has hurt the
dollar and led to declines in bond prices. Bond investors fear a
lower dollar will lead to inflation, credit-tightening by the
Federal Reserve and surging interest rates.
   A moderate 0.4 percent rise for June in the government's
Producer Price Index also boosted investor confidence, Front said.
   ``Bond prices were up modestly reflecting a sense of relief that
the trade figures and the Producer Price Index didn't provide any
important shocks and didn't reveal any negatives,'' he said.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
government issues rose about 1-16 point, intermediate maturities
rose by between [ point to 7-32 point and 20-year issues were up
5-32 point, according to the financial information service Telerate
Inc.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Daily Treasury Bond Index, which measures
price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with maturities
of a year or longer, was up 1.61 to 1,138.97.
   Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures
price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years
or longer, rose 0.65 to 281.88.
   Among tax-exempt municipal bonds, general obligations were
unchanged while dollar bonds were up \ point. Trading was moderate.
   Three-month Treasury bills were down 1 basis point to a
discounted rate of 6.71 percent, for a yield of 6.91 percent.
Six-month bills rose 4 basis points to a discounted rate of 7.05
percent to yield 7.40 percent and one-year bills were unchanged at
7.26 percent to yield 7.77 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discounted rate is the interest rate the market uses to price bills.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 7 13-16 percent, up from 7} percent late
Thursday.
</TEXT>
