<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0747EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Coke     07-15 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Coke,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coca-Cola's Profit Up 13.8 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coca-Cola Co. reported Thursday that its profit
rose 13.8 percent in the second quarter from a year earlier, led by
strong sales in Europe and the Pacific that were helped by the
weaker dollar.
   The beverage maker and distributor said net income increased to
$303 million, or 82 cents a share, from $266.4 million, or 70 cents
a share, in the second quarter of 1987.
   Second-quarter revenue rose 9.9 percent, to $2.3 billion from
$2.1 billion a year earlier.
   For the first six months of the year, Coca-Cola's profit jumped
13.7 percent, to $513.6 million, or $1.39 a share, from $451.8
million, or $1.19 a share, in the first half of 1987.
   Revenue for the half expanded 14.5 percent, to $4.2 billion from
$3.6 billion.
   ``The excellent second-quarter results reaffirm our expectation
that 1988 will be another year of strong volume and solid,
double-digit earnings growth for our company, coming on top of a
record 1987,'' Roberto C. Goizueta, chairman and chief executive
officer, said in a press statement.
   ``Our core soft drink business has never been on more solid
ground by any measure,'' he said. ``We expect the next six months
to benefit from the strong momentum with which our business is
moving into the second half of this year.''
   The company said its worldwide soft drink unit sales increased 5
percent in the latest quarter and 7 percent in the first six months.
   Outside the United States, second-quarter soft drink volume grew
an average 5 percent, including advances of 8 percent in Europe and
6 percent in the Pacific. The dollar's decline against key foreign
currencies boosted Coke sales by making the product cheaper
overseas, the company said.
   U.S. sales in the quarter grew 6 percent, including a 9 percent
rise in shipments of Coca-Cola Classic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
