<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0748EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Farmers-Batus     07-15 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmers-Batus,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oregon Official Rejects Proposed Farmers Insurance Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oregon's insurance commissioner on Thursday
rejected Batus Inc.'s attempted hostile takeover of the Oregon unit
of Farmers Insurance Co.
   Commissioner Ted Kulongoski concluded that the proposed buyout
by Batus, the U.S. arm of British conglomerate BAT Industries PLC,
Inc. would affect Farmers' policyholders adversely and be harmful
to free competition in the Oregon insurance trade.
   Kulongoski also cited the intention of Batus, which owns a major
tobacco company, to restrict the non-smoker policies sold by
Farmers. The commissioner said that also would be bad for
competition.
   Kulongoski's order can be appealed to the courts.
   Batus has offered about $4.5 billion to acquire Los
Angeles-based Farmers. Farmers directors have rejected the
proposal, which would require approval of insurance regulators in
nine states where Farmers has units.
   California's insurance commissioner also has rejected the
proposal, and Arizona has approved it.
   The commissioner's ruling stated the proposed acquisition
``subjects policyholders and shareholders to substantial risks
while providing no benefit that Farmers does not already enjoy.''
   He also said the continued denials by BAT and Batus ``of the
known adverse health effects of tobacco smoking, and its stated
intentions of precluding Farmers from referring to such health
effects in its marketing literature, do not promote the interest of
the insurance-buying public.''
   Batus owns Brown & Williamson Tobacco Corp. along with
department store concerns including Saks Fifth Avenue and Marshall
Field.
   Kulongoski said the proposed purchase would increase risks to
Farmers' policyholders because of potential judgments over
liability lawsuits involving tobacco products.
   ``In addition,'' Kulongoski said, ``there is evidence that the
proposed financing of the acquisition is unworkable.''
   And he said the takeover would be ``detrimental to free
competition in the Oregon insurance marketplace.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
