<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0736EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Lockheed     07-15 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Lockheed,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aerospace Company Says 6 Pct. Profit Increase Due to Tax Cut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALABASAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lockheed Corp. reported a 6 percent
profit second quarter profit increase on Thursday, but the
aerospace company attributed the gain largely to lower taxes.
   Lockheed earned $106 million, or $1.77 per share, in the second
quarter, up from $100 million, or $1.51 per share, in the same
period of 1987.
   Sales during the quarter ended June 26 fell to $2.7 billion from
$2.9 billion the year before.
   The per-share earnings figures for the two years are not
comparable because the company has bought back some 7 million
shares of its stock since the October 1987 stock market crash.
   Operating profit declined in the second quarter, to $163 million
from $195 million, partly because Lockheed's contract to build the
C-5B military transport plane is nearing an end, the company said.
Additionally, new Pentagon policies requiring contractors to pay a
larger share of the cost of development contracts has reduced
operating profit, the company said.
   Net income rose primarily because of lower tax rates, said
Lawrence Kitchen, chairman and chief executive.
   In the first half of 1988, Lockheed reported a profit of $220
million on sales of $5.3 billion, up from profit of $186 million on
sales of $5.4 billion in the same period of 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
